<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Egypt-U.S.Military     10-25 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-U.S. Military,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney Says Engineer Recruited By Egyptian Defense Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for a rocket expert accused
in a $1 million scheme to smuggle American missile technology to
Egypt said Tuesday that Cairo officials claimed the operation had
been approved by the U.S. government.
   Marcus S. Topel, an attorney for Abdelkader Helmy, an
Egyptian-born U.S. citizen who was a rocket specialist at the
Aerojet Solid Propulsion Company near Sacramento, said the American
government possesses a report from Egyptian officials making that
claim.
   Topel said he is attempting to obtain the document as part of his
defense for Helmy, 40, who is jailed on a no-bail warrant pending a
trial expected to begin next spring.
   Topel said American government documents also support his
contention that his client was recruited by Egypt's defense
minister, Lt. Gen. Abdel-Halim Abu-Ghazala.
   In papers filed Monday in federal District Court in Sacramento,
Topel said Helmy met twice with Abu-Ghazala _ in Cairo in September
1987 and in Washington last March. The papers said the general asked
for Helmy's aid in buying material for an Egyptian military research
and development program.
   Topel identified the program as a joint effort with Argentina and
perhaps other countries to develop medium-range missiles.
   ``Our investigation has shown these meetings did occur,'' Topel
said in a telephone interview from San Francisco. ``We expect at an
appropriate time in trial to provide more than sufficient evidence
that the meetings occurred. ... The appropriate time is not now.''
   Helmy, his wife and another American were charged last June with
money laundering and conspiring illegally to export technology for
sophisticated weapon systems. Two colonels in the Egyptian army also
were accused in the case but claimed diplomatic immunity.
   U.S. authorities claim Helmy received $1 million in payments from
Egyptians for his role involving the illicit export of a substance
called carbon-carbon or carbon composite. The material is a
low-radar-visibility compound used in missile nose cones and Stealth
aircraft.
   They accuse Helmy of belonging to an international export ring
illegally sending sensitive material to Europe and the Middle East.
   Egypt has said it is cooperating with the investigation, but
President Hosni Mubarak has said the Egyptian defendants were guilty
only of procedural errors and had committed no crimes.
   Federal prosecutors have declined comment on the defense
allegations. They have until Nov. 7 to file a formal response in
District Court. A hearing is scheduled for Dec. 1.
</TEXT>
