<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     10-25 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Series Tops Week; `Roseanne' Joins Top 10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As baseball wrapped up its season, the new
television season started taking place, as evidenced by a weekly
Nielsens list that sported more entertainment shows and few reruns.
   The last three games of the five-game World Series joined ``The
Cosby Show'' to give NBC the top four spots in the A.C. Nielsen Co.
rankings and a substantial victory last week.
   But everybody got a share of the top 10, with ABC adding its new
sitcom ``Roseanne,'' the highest-rated premiere of an ABC comedy
since ``Joanie Loves Chachi'' 6{ years ago.
   CBS won the Sunday movie battle and got a top 10 rating from the
conclusion of the two-part movie ``Jack the Ripper.''
   The final game between the Los Angeles Dodgers and the Oakland
A's was the week's highest-rated program with a 26.3 rating and 43
share.
   NBC won the week with an average prime-time rating of 18.8 to
ABC's 13.9 and CBS' 12.7.
   A rating point equals 904,000 homes with televisions. The share
is a percentage of sets in use.
   The average rating for NBC's coverage of the Series was 23.7, one
point higher than the first five games of last year's series between
Minnesota and St. Louis.
   The top-rated shows of the week were: ``World Series _ Game 5,''
``The Cosby Show,'' ``World Series _ Game 3'' and ``World Series _
Game 4,'' all on NBC; ``Roseanne'' and ``Who's the Boss?'' ABC;
``NBC Monday Night Movie _ Double Standard;'' ``60 Minutes,'' ``CBS
Sunday Movie _ Jack the Ripper, Part Two'' and ``Murder, She
Wrote,'' CBS.
   ABC's ``World News Tonight'' and the ``CBS Evening News'' tied
for first place in the news category with an average 10.2 and 20
share. ``NBC Nightly News,'' pre-empted by baseball, had an 8.9 and
18.
   ABC's limited-run remake of ``Mission Impossible'' made its debut
at 24th. NBC's new ``Empty Nest'' was 16th. But ``Something Is Out
There,'' based on last season's successful NBC miniseries, ranked
only 42nd.
   The lowest-rated shows of the week were: ``Bugs Bunny: Battle of
the Video Stars,'' ``Wiseguy special,'' ``48 Hours,'' ``Incredible
Sunday,'' ``Smothers Brothers Special,'' ``MacGyver,'' ``West
57th,'' ``High Risk,'' ``Live! Dick Clark Present'' and ``Simon &
Simon.''
</TEXT>
