<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada 1stLd-Writethru a0722 10-25 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0722,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Canada Free Trade Pact Dominates Debate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Editing and new material throughout, UPDATING with debate
finale. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S.-Canada free trade agreement negotiated by
Prime Minister Brian Mulroney dominated the debate Tuesday among
leaders of the three major parties in a critical prelude to the Nov.
21 election.
   Mulroney said the agreement achieved by his Progressive
Conservative Party was central to Canada's future and he described
his rivals' attacks against the pact as ``scare mongering.''
   John Turner of the Liberal Party and Ed Broadbent of the
socialist New Democratic Party criticized Mulroney and then argued
about who had most effectively opposed the agreement.
   The three-hour, English-language debate was broadcast nationally
from Ottawa and followed a three-hour French-language debate Monday
night.
   Mulroney said the agreement, scheduled to take effect Jan. 1,
will allow Canada to move ahead and compete internationally to
assure future prosperity. He challenged his foes to outline an
effective alternative.
   ``They would tear up the free trade agreement and then what? They
offer you nothing but the poverty of protectionism,'' he said.
   Turner again vowed to battle the pact.
   ``This election is not a popularity contest. The issue is the
future of Canada,'' he said. ``He (Mulroney) now wants to turn us
into a pale replica of the United States.''
   Polls early in the campaign that began Oct. 1 generally placed
the Conservatives first, with at least 40 percent of the vote
usually needed for a majority government. Mulroney called the
election Oct. 1 after serving four years of his maximum five-year
term.
   He won a landslide victory in 1984 and is seeking to put together
a second consecutive majority government, which has not happened in
Canada since 1953.
   The New Democrats pushed the Liberals to third in most polls
before the debates. That would be a stunning setback for the party
of former Prime Minister Pierre Elliott Trudeau.
   Broadbent also strongly attacked the free trade agreement. ``This
deal must be stopped because it takes away our right to make
decisions about our own country in our own way,'' he said.
   Critics of the trade pact say the huge population and economic
power of the United States would force Canada to renounce social
welfare programs and regional development plans.
   ``What we have here is a deal that touches virtually every aspect
of Canadian life,'' Broadbent said.
   Turner said, ``I hope Canadians defeat this deal by defeating Mr.
Mulroney.''
   Mulroney responded by saying Canadians are fully capable of
competing internationally and there was ``not the slightest
justification'' for raising fears of loss of identity or social
protections. ``You've been scare mongering,'' he said.
   The U.S. Senate voted, 83-9, in September in favor of the trade
agreement signed in January by Mulroney and President Reagan.
   In Canada, however, only the elected House of Commons controlled
by the Conservatives passed it. Liberals in the non-elected Senate
balked and kept the agreement bottled up.
   A Mulroney win with a parliamentary majority would let the
world's two largest trading partners proceed to form a North
American free trade zone on Jan. 1, eliminating all tariffs over a
10-year period and dismantling barriers to investment and
competition.
   A Gallup poll published Tuesday by the Toronto Star found support
for the agreement slippng, with 42 percent of Canadians opposed and
34 percent in favor. The others said they had no opinion or neither
supported nor opposed the proposal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
