<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Fashion     10-25 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fashion,0755</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ungaro Summer Offerings Mostly A Variation Of Last Year</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Summer sirens in sizzling colors and clinging short
skirts ambled down the runway at Emanuel Ungaro's summer
ready-to-wear show.
   While the rest of Paris is easing up on summer profiles with many
dropped hemlines, Ungaro went his own way _ fitting, draping and
adding little bows to sexy outfits.
   Most of the dozens of looks in Tuesday's long and somewhat
monotonous show were variations on last year's.
   There were countless gorgeous but familiar nipped-waist spencer
jackets with long points, plus plenty of peplums above the
body-hugging skirts. The newer flowing babydoll jackets in hot
colors are easier toppers.
   Varied fabrics were mixed in an outfit, another Ungaro forte. His
new short skirt is shiny red, burgundy or brown patent leather,
teamed up with flowered blouses and jackets.
   Ungaro's flower garden sprouted all kinds of posies, in every
spring color imaginable from pink to robin's egg blue to lime,
fuchsia and amethyst. The decorator's dream prints were heavily
charged with big peonies and roses, but the best flower jackets were
simpler _ white pique sprigged with wild flowers.
   Ungaro's pants are original. Instead of the favorite wide
pantskirt, he chose droopy drawers, long or short fluid harem or
bloomer pants, teamed up with the showy, flowered fitted tops.
Evening wear with plenty of lace and lame was predictably flounced
and elaborate looking, as most of the show did, a dead-ringer for
couture.
   Guy Douvier's styles for Guy Laroche were much simpler and
undoubtedly will be less expensive. This clean-cut collection
featured short skirts, smart pea jackets and long, straight pants or
shorts in red, white and navy nautical lines.
   Careful cut and finish gave blue or grey denim skirts and shorts
suits smooth city elegance. Big color prints burst out here, too, on
flowered strapless bustier sheaths with puff-sleeved boleros. Other
feminine lines in turquoise, fuchsia and yellow were paneled and
wrapped like flower petals. And with all this color, Douvier was
dotty over black polka dots on the hot colors.
   Jean-Louis Scherrer showed a huge group of navy-and-white
nautical outfits, beautifully cut with flowing trousers, and neat
variations on the pea jacket, as well as lots of stripes.
   Scherrer showed full shorts and a striped mini-jersey, but he
usually preferred less leggy looks. A white pique sundress with a
long, swirling skirt and little blue jacket could be a winner.
   There were enough safari outfits and jungle prints here to make a
planter pleased as punch. In desert shades of sand and burnt orange,
or printed in green and violet, they ranged from sexy tulip-draped
skirts to belted but full light cotton bush jackets over ample long
pants.
   For after-hours, Scherrer opted for flowered, draped sheaths or
lacy inspiration in short or long evening dresses of expensive
lingerie inspiration.
   The froths of lace bubbled all over like champagne, including the
soft peach and sky blue dressy evening pyjamas, and bustier dresses
with silk chiffon blazers.
   Scherrer ended the show with navy lame and lurex sailor suits,
quite handsome indeed for the skipper or first mate on the night
watch.
   Valentino also was big on lace. But he didn't seem to know where
to stop, pairing it with chiffon prints and huge swaths of
rhinestone embroidery. On some outfits it looked demure; on others,
it was rather heavy-handed.
   Day wear was more successful, especially the suits _ lean, short
and sleek as only Valentino knows how to make them. He showed very
pure lines in battle-jacket tops, or easily fitted glen plaid or
checked jackets over white pique vests, silk blouses underneath.
   Valentino's favorite trouser line still looked new, straight and
not too full, with a cuff at the ankle. Other trousers included
short, full culottes, lean pedal pushers _ topped by boxy plaid
jackets.
   Erik Mortensen at Balmain was applauded for a collection that
looked both simple and elegant. His idea of the trapeze pants was a
suit in awning stripes of red or green, topped with a neat little
bolero.
   Suits were lean, dressy and short, sometimes cut in diagonal,
two-colored combinations. And Mortensen's clinging ribbed knit
dresses in hot shades of red, orange and yellow were intriguingly
textured with panels of the ribbed knit cut so the ribbing was
placed at several angles all over the dress.
</TEXT>
