<HEAD>`Halloween' Returns To Scare More Money From Moviegoers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Weekend moviegoers spent more than $6.2 million
to see the sequel of a movie that wouldn't die, ``Halloween 4, The
Return of Michael Myers.''
   In second place of the weekend box office rankings was ``The
Accused,'' which earned more than $4 million, followed by ``Alien
Nation'' with $2.6 million. ``Punchline,'' which drew $2.3 million
was in fourth place, followed by ``Gorillas In The Mist'' with $2.1
million.
   ``Without A Clue,'' starring Michael Caine and Ben Kingsley as a
stupid Sherlock Holmes and a patient Dr. Watson, respectively, came
in sixth with $1.1 million.
   ``Mystic Pizza,'' a teen romance film in its first week of
release, followed with $1.1 million.
   ``A Fish Called Wanda'' was eighth with more than $1 million,
edging ``Crossing Delancey.''
   In 10th was ``Bat 21,'' starring Gene Hackman as an Air Force
colonel downed behind enemy lines during the Vietnam War. The movie
was released at 248 theaters and earned more than $980,000, enough
to get it into the top 10.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Inc., with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   1. ``Halloween 4, The Return of Michael Myers,'' Galaxy, $6.2
million, 1,679 screens, $3,710 per screen, $6.2 million, one week.
   2. ``The Accused,'' Paramount, $4 million, 930 screens, $4,327
per screen, $9.9 million, two weeks.
   3. ``Alien Nation,'' 20th Century Fox, $2.6 million, 1,436
screens, $1,815 per screen, $17.6 million, three weeks.
   4. ``Punchline,'' Columbia, $2.3 million, 916 screens, $2,613
per screen, $13.2 million, four weeks.
   5. ``Gorillas In The Mist,'' Universal, $2.1 million, 1,073
screens, $2,039 per screen, $15.6 million, five weeks.
   6. ``Without A Clue,'' Orion, $1.2 million, 280 screens, $4,452
per screen, $1.2 million, one week.
   7. ``Mystic Pizza,'' Goldwyn, $1.1 million, 401 screens, $2,902
per sceen, $1.1 million, one week.
   8. ``A Fish Called Wanda,'' MGM-UA, $1.044 million, 747 screens,
$1,398 per screen, $56.2 million, 15 weeks.
   9. ``Crossing Delancey,'' Warner Bros., $1.042 million, 302
screens, $3,451 per screen, $10.2 million, eight weeks.
   10. ``Bat 21,'' Tri-Star, $982,080, 248 screens, $3,960 per
screen, $982,080, one week.
