<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 0031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TreasuryBills     10-25 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yields Mixed on Short-Term T-Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities were mixed in the latest auction.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.0 billion in three-month bills
Monday at an average discount rate of 7.45 percent, up from 7.36
percent last week. Another $7.0 billion was sold in six-month bills
at an average discount rate of 7.54 percent, down from 7.55 percent
last week.
   The three-month rate was the highest since the bills sold for
7.69 percent on May 13, 1985. The six-month rate was the lowest
since the bills averaged 7.46 on Oct. 11.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 7.70 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,811.70 and 7.95 percent for six-month bills selling for
$9,618.80.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said the average yield
for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for making
changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, rose to 8.12 percent
last week after averaging 8.07 percent the week before.
</TEXT>
