<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--MolassesSpill     10-25 0139</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Molasses Spill,0142</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Molasses Spill A Sticky Hazard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIGONIER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tanker-truck hauling 3,000 gallons of
molasses lost its brakes and overturned, spilling about half its
sticky load onto a highway, police said.
   Route 30's two lanes were closed nearly nine hours after
Wednesday afternoon's accident. To prevent the syrup from running
into highway drains and a reservoir, crews built a dike of logs,
stones and mud. Sawdust and sand also was spread. What was left of
the syrup was hosed down.
   ``For as sticky a problem it is, it's not as bad as it looks,''
said Robert Cammarata, assistant chief of Westmoreland County's
hazardous materials unit.
   The driver of the Baltimore-based P&R Tank Lines Inc. truck
suffered lacerations and was in good condition at Latrobe Area
Hospital, officials said.
   No charges were filed, police said.
</TEXT>
