<NOTE>Eds: Version of the following item moved on the financial wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Resorts International Inc. could
change hands from one millionaire entrepreneur to another if
entertainer Merv Griffin persuades investors to buy bonds this week.
   Griffin expects to complete the purchase of Resorts
International from developer Donald Trump on or around Nov. 3.
   Griffin will acquire the gaming and real estate company's
casinos in Atlantic City and the Bahamas, and will sell back the
unfinished Taj Majal casino project here to Trump.
   The former talk show host is visiting several U.S. cities this
week to try to persuade investors to buy bonds in his new company.
He needs to raise $325 million through bond sales to buy Resorts.
   Under the deal, Trump would be paid $63 million to break his
lucrative management contract with the casino company. He then
would pay Griffin $273 million to buy back the Taj Mahal.
   ``I'm also getting the airline service and the piers going out
over the water and the land around the Taj Maal,'' Trump said
Monday.
   Griffin will pay Trump $96 million for his controlling block of
Resorts stock and Resorts stockholders $205 million.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Versions of the following items moved on sports wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A street party by 50,000 ecstatic Dodgers
fans to celebrate their team's unlikely World Series triumph had
pitcher Orel Hershiser quoting Jackie Gleason.
   ``How sweet it is!'' the ace righthander yelled during the
celebration Monday outside City Hall.
   Hershiser, the fall classic's Most Valuable Player, struck out
the final Oakland batter Thursday to win the championship and rack
up his second Series victory.
   ``I want to thank the greatest team that any manager could ever
have,'' said Manager Tommy Lasorda.
   Moments later, he began lurching back and forth in a unique
twist-style dance step. During spring training, he predicted that,
come October, he would be dancing in the streets.
   The party isn't over. On Wednesday, the Dodgers are set for a
White House reception with President Reagan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Pittsburgh Steelers quarterback
Terry Bradshaw was given a clean bill of health following medical
tests for chest pains and will be back in CBS' anchor booth.
   ``Terry has a normal, healthy, 40-year-old heart,'' Dr. David
Carter, who examined Bradshaw at Harris Methodist Hospital in
Bedford, said Monday. ``His blood vessels are excellent and the
test revealed no problems in that area.''
   Bradshaw, who led the Steelers to four Super Bowl titles, missed
his last two CBS assignments because of the chest ailment. He is
scheduled to return for Sunday's telecast of the Los Angeles
Rams-New Orleans Saints game.
   The tests found a small amount of scar tissue in the middle of
Bradshaw's chest, but Carter said the condition was not serious.
   ``We'll check him again in a couple of months to make sure he
continues to do well,'' the doctor said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laser surgery is planned this week for Brigitte
Nielsen, whose illness fiancee Mark Gastineau cited as his reason
for quitting pro football, the actress' publicist says.
   Publicist Joel Brokaw said from Los Angeles that Nielsen did not
tell him what her ailment was, but said it was not life-threatening
when he spoke with her Monday afternoon.
   Last week, Nielsen told The New York Times she had cancer of the
uterus and planned to enter an unspecified Arizona hospital on
Monday for a biopsy.
   Brokaw said he had no other information on the surgery.
   Last week, Gastineau announced he was quitting the New York Jets
and football because he wanted to help Nielsen through her illness.
The couple flew to Arizona, where his family lives.
   Gastineau's estranged wife, Lisa, said Sunday she didn't think
her husband was quitting football because of Nielsen's illness and
said he was exaggerating his fiancee's illness.
