<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 0118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MercyMission Bjt   10-25 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mercy Mission, Bjt,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former U.S. Marines On A Peace Offensive To Vietnam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE ESPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mercy mission of six former Marines to clear
mines in Vietnam is an exchange of good will that the Vietnamese
hope will blossom into diplomatic recognition, an infusion of aid
and the lifting of a trade embargo.
   Three of the Americans who are going on the Jan. 9 mission, Gene
T. Spanos, of Rosemont, Ill.; Robert Dalton, of Davidsonville, Md.;
and Frank Noe, of Stoughton, Mass., were at the Vietnamese mission
to the United Nations on Monday.
   They met with Ambassador Trinh Xuan Lang, head of the Vietnamese
mission, and reviewed their planned nine-day trip to former
battlefields below the Demilitarized Zone, including Khe Sanh where
Marines withstood a 77-day siege in 1968.
   Their sentiments were expressed in a plaque presented to Vietnam
with the inscription: ``In the hopes of preserving the peace, we
come to Vietnam once again, this time to help the preservation of
human life. 11th Engineers January 1989.''
   The humanitarian ``people-to-people'' visit is private and is
being paid for by an anonymous businessman. The other Marines in
the group returning to Vietnam from the 11th Engineer Battalion,
3rd Marine Division, are Nate Genna, of West Roxbury, Mass.;
William Johnson, of Manchester, Conn.; and Mike Wallace, of
Langdon, Kan.
   The mission to verify the Vietnamese claim that they have
removed all of the land mines the Americans planted 20 years ago is
the latest in a series of gestures between the two countries to
improve relations. Vietnam, one of the poorest countries in the
world, badly needs U.S. aid it likely would receive with
normalization of diplomatic relations.
   Nguyen Xuan Oanh, a member of Vietnam's National Assembly and a
key economic adviser, conferred with American businessmen this
month on a rare visit to the United States.
   Oanh said again that Vietnam will withdraw its 100,000 to
120,000 troops from neighboring Cambodia by the end of 1990, a
condition Washington has imposed before it will recognize the Hanoi
government.
   And just last month, the United States and Vietnam began joint
searches for witnesses of wartime plane crashes in efforts to find
the remains of some of the 1,757 Americans missing in action and
presumed dead. The United States says it has no evidence that any
of them are alive but it is seeking an accounting.
   At a joint news conference Monday, Lang said the mines had all
been cleared at the cost of thousands of civilians killed,
particularly from the end of the war in 1975 until 1978 when land
was being cleared for farming and housing.
   Spanos said the 11th Engineers planted about 100,000 mines below
the Demilitarized Zone between 1966 and 1969 and left them intact
when they pulled out. He said American veterans visiting hospitals
in Vietnam had seen children who had been killed and maimed by old
mines.
   ``No one knows for sure,'' said Spanos. ``Basically what
Ambassador Lang has said is true, that a lot of areas have been
cleared, but exactly where these people are still coming up from
being injured, we want to go back, review, walk the terrain, write
our reports and submit our findings to both governments.''
   They will be working with reconstructed battlefield maps and
have asked the Vietnamese for a team of their counterparts to
accompany them.
   The ambassador and Spanos agreed that the most important part of
the mission is a better understanding between the countries.
   ``They are welcome,'' said Lang. ``They return without any
animosity. From the beginning of this year till now, from 60 to 80
American teams have visited Vietnam, journalists, congressmen,
senators, scholars and tourists. These visits will contribute to
better understanding.''
   Spanos said letters of support his team has received from
Americans across the country, veterans and non-veterans, has been
phenomenal.
</TEXT>
