<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Environmental Group Files New Challenge of Nuclear Simulation
Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A regional planning commission and an
environmental group are asking a federal judge to halt the testing
of a high-powered generator that simulates electro-magnetic pulse,
one of the effects of a nuclear blast.
   A suit filed Monday accuses the Navy of starting tests of the
Empress II generator off the North Carolina coast this summer on
the basis of a ``hopelessly premature and flawed'' environmental
impact statement.
   In asking a judge for preliminary and permanent injunctions, the
suit It accuses the Navy of ignoring potential adverse effects on
test workers and recreational or commercial boaters and fishermen,
as well as on marine life and the radio equipment of passing ships
and planes.
   The Foundation on Economic Trends, an environmental group based
in Washington, filed the suit with the Albemarle Commission, a
regional planning and development commission that represents 24
local North Carolina governments.
