<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 0233EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--PhoneReligion     10-25 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Phone Religion,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Religion That Won't Hang Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spiritual telephone recording that
won't let listeners hang up isn't spreading good will to some of
those receiving the five-minute automated calls.
   Art Hage, pastor of the Hurricane Bible Church, brushes aside
any objections to his messages, which ask recipients to join him in
prayer.
   ``There's always irate people,'' Hage said.
   Asked to comment further, Hage declined, said thank you, and
hung up.
   But the recipients of Hage's prerecorded telephone calls can't
do the same. The pastor's message lasts five minutes and even if
recipients hang up, they won't get a dial tone until the tape is
done.
   ``If the other party refuses to let go of your line when you
hang up, that's abusive,'' said Billy Jack Gregg, consumer advocate
director at the state Public Service Commission.
   The commission's consumer regulation director Meyshi Blair said
she has received one written complaint about Hage's phone calls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
