<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 0253EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     10-25 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Stocks Rebound In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed slightly higher against the
Japanese yen Tuesday, while share prices moderately rebounded on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 126.87 yen, up 0.27 yen from Monday's close
of 126.60 yen. Opening at 127.08 yen, the currency moved in a range
of 126.77-127.20 yen.
   Analysts said some investors who have been selling the dollar
recently purchased the currency to adjust their position ahead of
U.S. third-quarter gross national product figures scheduled for
release Wednesday, and that has been keeping the yen from rising
further.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 57.03-point
loser on Monday, regained 139.95 points, or 0.51 percent, to finish
trading at 27,421.49.
   Share prices rebounded mainly due to the $1.20 per barrel
decline of oil prices in New York, said a dealer with Daiwa
Securities in Tokyo.
   It is widely believed that oil prices fell because last
weekend's meeting of key Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries members failed to produce agreeement on members'
production limits. That increased speculation that the current
worldwide oil glut that has been depressing prices would continue
at least over the short term.
</TEXT>
