<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0455 10-25 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0455,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Nominee Pledges Federal Incentives for Education</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new graf after 4th graf pvs, bgng Dukakis was, to
include polling data; picks up 5th graf pvs, The Massachusetts;
First event at 1:15 p.m. EDT; Tops uncertain</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAYWARD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, declaring his uphill
presidential effort ``one for the people of America,'' vowed a
continued assault on Republican campaign tactics and promised to
balance his salvos with discussion of key issues.
   To that end, the Democratic presidential nominee said Monday
night he would improve the nation's secondary schools partly by
tying some federal funding to improved academic performance.
   He offered the plan at a town meeting at Hayward High School,
telling San Francisco Bay area residents, ``I don't know of
anything that cries out more for presidential leadership'' than
education.
   Dukakis was wrapping up a California campaign trip today faced
with a new Los Angeles Times poll that showed him trailing
Republican George Bush by 11 points in the state, which holds the
top Electoral College prize of 47 votes.
   The poll released in today's editions of the Times showed Bush
leading Dukakis 53-42 percent in the state. The Times questioned
1,376 registered voters during the fours days that ended Sunday and
the margin of error was four percentage points.
   The Massachusetts governor arrived in California late Sunday and
campaigned aggressively Monday, beginning in Los Angeles before
traveling to San Diego and then on to San Francisco, Hayward and
San Leandro.
   Dukakis was heading today to Colorado, where he was to campaign
before taping a five-minute network television speech to be aired
tonight. Dukakis also was appearing on ABC's ``Nightline'' and was
spending part of the day preparing for that 90-minute session.
   Many of Dukakis' California events were rallies with precinct
leaders, part of an unprecedented Democratic Party grass roots
effort in this state. He ended his day Monday at one such
gathering, telling cheering supporters that ``either you're all
crazy or we're going to win on the 8th of November.''
   Dukakis saluted the campaign volunteers and promised to close
the campaign with a flourish.
   ``This one is for you,'' he said. ``This one is for the people
of America.''
   For the past week Dukakis has focused on Bush's campaign
tactics, accusing the vice president of distorting Dukakis'
positions and record and using ``outright lies'' as part a
calculated effort to avoid discussion of substantial issues.
   ``I'm bound and determined that over the course of the next two
weeks I'm going to take my case directly to the people of this
country,'' Dukakis told the town meeting in Hayward.
   Dukakis, who trails Bush in national polls as well, acknowledged
his slip was probably fueled by his failure to respond immediately
and aggressively to Bush's attacks.
   ``I'm not going to let him get away with that stuff,'' Dukakis
said. ``I'll see if I can strike a reasonably good balance''
between assailing the Republicans and discussing his proposals.
   His spoke briefly to the meeting about his latest, the secondary
education plan, and aides distributed a position paper outlining
the three-point proposal.
   The plan calls for encouraging improvements in science and
computer teaching by, in part, tying eligibility for certain
federal education funding to progress toward national performance
standards. Also included is a proposal for job placement services
for high school students who decide not to attend college.
   Dukakis issues adviser Thomas Herman said funding levels for the
federal incentives included in the plan would depend on efforts to
reduce the federal budget deficit. Those incentives would include
grants to schools that establish model programs for exceptional and
learning-disabled students.
</TEXT>
