<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--MacArthurFoundation     10-25 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--MacArthur Foundation,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>College President To Head MacArthur Foundation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adele S. Simmons, president of Hampshire College
the past 11 years, will become president of the John D. and
Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation, widely known for its ``genius''
grants.
   Simmons on Monday agreed to lead the 10-year-old organization
starting in May. She is replacing the retiring John Corbally, who
has directed the foundation's philanthropic efforts since 1979.
   Simmons, 47, said she will maintain the kind of challenges she
faced at Hampshire, a small, liberal arts college in Amherst, Mass.
   ``The foundation is about as old as Hampshire was when I came,
and the organizational and institutional problems of the second
decade are different from those of the first,'' she said.
   The foundation has assets of $2.5 billion and annual grants of
$127 million, in fields ranging from health, education and
environmental concerns to international peace and cooperation and
mass communications.
   Its genius grants provide upwards of $250,000 for five years
with no conditions to artists, writers, scientists, community
activists and others.
</TEXT>
