<DOCNO> AP881025-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 0349EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Tibet     10-25 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tibet,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Tibetan, Chinese Talks Scheduled For January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dalai Lama will send representatives
to Geneva in January to hold the Tibetan government-in-exile's
first official talks in four years with Chinese officials, his
office said today.
   Spokesman Lodi Gyari said the exact date has not been set yet.
   The two sides met at Beijing in 1982 and then again in 1984 to
seek to resolve the issue of Tibetan autonomy.
   Gyari said the Dalai Lama would not participate in the talks.
   ``His Holiness will definitely not be present at the talks. He
might be present at a later stage to meet with top Chinese
government officials like Deng Xiao Ping, but not now,'' the
spokesman said.
   The Dalai Lama, god-king of the Tibetans, fled his homeland in
1959 after the Chinese occupation of Tibet and took exile in India,
where he set up a government-in-exile.
   The Tibetan offer of a time and date for official talks came in
response to an offer Sept. 21 by the Chinese government.
   ``The talks will be in early January,'' Sonam Totgyal, a Tibetan
Information Department official. ``We have chosen Geneva,
Switzerland, as the most convenient and neutral venue for the
talks.''
   In the Tibetan capital of Lhasa, monks loyal to the Dalai Lama
led anti-Chinese demonstrations in September and October 1987 and
in March this year. The monks accuse the Chinese government of
undermining Tibetan social and religious customs.
   The human rights group Asia Watch said as many as 50 people died
in the March 5 rioting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
