<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 0533EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VincennesHomecoming     10-25 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vincennes Homecoming,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Captain Denies Crew Stress Led to Downing of Iranian Airliner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The USS Vincennes came home to an emotional
welcome after a six-month deployment marred by the crew's
accidental downing of an Iranian jetliner over the Persian Gulf,
killing the 290 people aboard.
   ``We're glad to be home, I assure you of that,'' Capt. Will C.
Rogers III said after the guided-missile cruiser docked at San
Diego Naval Station on Monday. ``This is a nice place.''
   Rogers' 400-man crew cheered loudly as he walked down the
gangway. The captain got a kiss, a hug and flowers from his wife,
Sharon.
   After a brief welcoming ceremony, the sailors poured off the
ship into a sea of relatives, friends and fellow servicemen.
   ``Hi, daddy. You're home!'' a little girl said as she waved to
her father.
   Petty Officer 3rd Class Steve Hile of Niles, Mich., got a warm
embrace from his girlfriend, Vallita Lawwill.
   ``I don't even know what we were doing there,'' Hile said.
``It's a tragedy that it happened. But I'm glad I'm home and I'm
alive.''
   The Vincennes mistook the Airbus jetliner for an Iranian F-14
fighter jet when it shot the aircraft down July 3, according to the
official Pentagon report on the tragedy.
   The report concluded that the warship's crew misinterpreted
computer and radar data because of the stress of being in combat
for the first time. At the time, the Vincennes was in a firefight
with several Iranian gunboats.
   Rogers disputed that conclusion Monday. ``It's my opinon that
stress was not a factor,'' he said.
   ``Given all of the information available and in view of the
ongoing continuum of violent and aggressive Iranian action, I was
convinced beyond any doubt that the inbound aircraft was in direct
support of the surface engagement in progress,'' Rogers said.
   ``There, of course, were mistakes made and there always are in
an intense combat environment,'' Rogers said. ``But both my crew
and the system performed basically as designed.
   ``I, as well as my crew, will live with the result of the tragic
loss of civilian lives associated with these actions, tempered only
by the belief I had no other course of action and that any prudent
commanding officer would do the same.''
   Rogers said the fate of the USS Stark, on which 37 sailors died
in an Iraqi missile attack in the Persian Gulf, was in the back of
his mind throughout his ship's mission.
   ``No skipper sails in the gulf without the Stark at least in
your subconscious,'' Rogers said. ``Was it a factor during that
decision process? I don't consciously remember.''
   Responding to a question from an Iranian reporter, Rogers said
he regretted the loss of civilian life.
   The captain said he knew within 90 minutes of ordering two
missiles fired that the downed airplane was a civilian airliner. He
said he later assembled the crew to tell them the news, which they
took quietly.
   ``At first we were all devastated,'' Rogers said. ``It goes
without saying. But I have to look at it, and my crew looks at it,
that given the fact that the airliner made no indication that it
was not a hostile craft, we had no other choice.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
