<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Temptation     10-25 0138</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Temptation,0139</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Censors Ban ``Last Temptation of Christ''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government censors today banned
``The Last Temptation of Christ'' from South Africa, saying the
controversial film would offend people's religious convictions.
   Professor Abraham Coetzee, chairman of the publications
directorate, said his censorship committee had been inundated with
letters, telegrams and petitions from church and civic groups
urging that the film be banned.
   Coetzee said the film was found to be undesirable under a
section of the regulations dealing with material that is deemed
blasphemous or ``offensive to the religious convictions or feelings
of any section of the inhabitants of republic.''
   The film, directed by Martin Scorsese and based on a novel by
Nikos Kasantzakis, depicts a troubled Jesus on the cross who at one
point dreams of making love with prostitute Mary Magdalen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881025-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 0613EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CarvingDispute     10-25 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carving Dispute,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thai Group Skeptical Over Museum Decision To Return Relic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Art Institute of Chicago has agreed to return
a 1,000-year-old stone carving that Thailand says disappeared from
a sacred temple two decades ago, in hopes of ending a nine-month
international dispute.
   But a Thai group says it won't be satisfied until its government
approves the plan.
   ``We cannot say that it is resolved until complete agreement is
reached between the Art Institute and the Thai government,'' said
Wutisak Lapcharoensap, spokesman of the Thai Vishnu Lintel
Committee, based in suburban Evanston.
   The institute announced Monday it would return the lintel to
Thailand in exchange for a Thai artifact ``of equal artistic
merit'' to be donated by the Chicago-based Elizabeth F. Cheney
Foundation, a philanthropic group that wanted to help resolve the
dispute.
   The lintel, a 2-by-3 foot stone crosspiece designed to fit above
a door or window, depicts the Hindu god Vishnu reclining on water.
It dates to Cambodia's Khmer dynasty from A.D. 805-1250.
   It disappeared from the Phnom Rung temple, a national monument
in northeastern Thailand during the 1960s, Thai officials say.
   The lintel was first displayed at the institute 21 years ago.
But museum officials said they did not learn until February that
the Thai government wanted it returned for the temple's restoration.
   Thai demonstrators protested outside the museum earlier this
year, hoping to have the lintel returned in time for reopening
ceremonies at the Thai temple in May.
   Museum spokeswoman Virginia Voedisch said Thai officials had
been told of the decision to return the lintel, but she did not
think an official response had been received by the institute.
   Monday's announcement came a day before a Thai representative
and others demanding the lintel were scheduled to testify at a City
Council committee meeting, Lapcharoensap said.
   He said the meeting would be held today despite the announcement.
   Lapcharoensap said the institute had said earlier it wanted to
return the lintel, but nothing was done.
   ``If I have some skepticism, it's justified,''' he said.
   The institute said it got the lintel from the Chicago-based
Alsdorf Foundation, which acquired it in 1967 through a New York
art dealer. The institute said the New York dealer had purchased
the carving from a dealer in Bangkok in 1966, where it was offered
for sale on the open market.
   The museum said it agreed to return the lintel, with the help of
the Cheney foundation, to ``resolve the stalemate in negotiations
and maintain the positive relationship that existed between
Thailand and the United States.''
   ``We are pleased to resolve this issue,'' said James N. Wood,
the institute's director. ``This solution meets our requirement for
just compensation.''
   Ms. Voedisch said museum and Cheney foundation officials would
have to agree on the piece to be donated in exchange for the
lintel, and that a decision was expected soon.
   ``Upon receipt of this gift, the Art Institute will relinquish
all rights and title to the lintel and donate it to Thailand,'' the
museum said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881025-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 0642EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Homeless-Cartoons 1stLd_Writethru a0472 10-25 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Homeless-Cartoons, 1st Ld _ Writethru, a0472,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Comic-strip, Editorial Cartoonists Focus On Plight Of Homeless</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT to B.C. by Hart sted Wizard of ID</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Garfield pined for the comforts of home while outdoors in a
rainstorm, and Marmaduke invited homeless dogs to his house for
breakfast as cartoonists focused on the plight of the needy in
today's comic pages.
   More than 100 comic-strip and editorial cartoonists, including
the creators of ``Garfield'' and ``Marmaduke,'' participated.
   ``The goal of the project is to tug at America's heart strings
through its funny bones. Tomorrow's funny pages are not going to be
so funny,'' Barry Zigas, of the National Low Income Housing
Coalition, said during a news conference Monday in Washington.
   Some of the cartoons had a serious tone. Others found a humorous
tilt to a not-so-funny issue. In ``The Lockhorns'' a suited-man
tells a homeless man cooking over a fire, ``I'd ask you home for a
good home-cooked meal but you're better off here.''
   ``It's not going to change things overnight; it's just one more
expression of the movement,'' said cartoonist Mell Lazarus, who
draws the comic strip ``Momma.''
   In his strip, Momma's son raids her refrigerator because he
doesn't have any food at his apartment. Momma tells him, ``Francis,
do you realize there are people in this country who are totally
homeless, while you have two of them?''
   ``If a kid tells his parents, `Hey look. All the comics are
about homeless people today,' we will at least have raised their
consciousness,'' Lazarus said Monday in Los Angeles.
   In ``The Family Circus'', by Bil Keane, a youngster asks about a
homeless man sleeping on a bench, `But, if he doesn't have a home,
how can his children come for a visit?''
   Paul Conrad, editorial cartoonist for the Los Angeles Times,
said, ``I'm participating because I'm trying to attract attention
to the homeless, but I've been drawing about the homeless for years
and so far it hasn't had any effect.'' His cartoon on the homeless
will appear later this week.
   In the Boston Herald, editorial cartoonist Jerry Holbert showed
a homeless man on a park bench covered with newspapers advertising
expensive houses.
   The Atlanta Constitution's Doug Marlette, winner of this year's
Pulitzer Prize for editorial cartoons, showed a group of street
people with the U.S. Capitol in the distance. The caption reads:
``Land of the Free, Homeless of the Brave.''
   In The Miami Herald, editorial cartoonist Jim Morin drew a
bedraggled man slumped in a doorway flanked by shopping bags
overflowing with clothes. Near the door is a sign with the message:
``Home is where the heart isn't.''
   Bill DeOre, of The Dallas Morning News, fashioned a weather face
formed by the words: mentally ill; jobless; addiction; illiteracy.
   Zigas, noting that there are no official counts of the number of
homeless, said national estimates range from 350,000 to more than 3
million.
   ``Hunger and homelessness are not partisan issues, they are
human tragedies that deserve our immediate attention,'' said Zigas,
an organizer of the cartoonists' effort.
   ``There is a shameful level of hunger in the United States,
although it is not as visible as homelessness,'' added Robert Fersh
of the Food Research Action Center.
   Millions more than that are hungry, Fersh said, adding that
children make up a large share of those without enough to eat.
   Other cartoonists participating included Garry Trudeau, author
of ``Doonesbury;'' Dik Browne, creator of ``Hagar the Horrible;''
``B.C.'' artist Johnny Hart; and Tom Batiuk, developer of
``Crankshaft.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881025-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 0645EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HarvardUnion     10-25 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harvard Union,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NLRB Rejects Harvard's Claims On Union Vote Tactics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union officials at Harvard University
celebrated after a judge dismissed the school's attempt to overturn
a vote to form a 3,400-member union for technical and clerical
workers.
   The Ivy League school, however, insisted it has done nothing
wrong.
   In a harshly worded opinion Monday, a National Labor Relations
Board administrative law judge rejected the university's claim that
labor organizers illegally coerced ``yes'' votes through a
coordinated campaign to assure that union supporters cast ballots.
   The judge, Joel A. Harmatz, certified the Harvard Union of
Clerical and Technical Workers as the winner of the May ballot.
   ``We feel great about it,'' union director Kristine Rondeau
said. ``We knew we were right, but we always were cautious about
predicting the inevitability of our win.''
   The union, an affiliate of the 1 million-member American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees, won the
election on a 1,530-1,486 vote in which more than 90 percent of
eligible workers cast ballots.
   ``The allegations do not suggest that the election was beclouded
by threats, violence, vandalism, reprisals or the traditional forms
of voter intimidation,'' Harmatz wrote. ``Indeed, none of the
conduct subject to litigation in this proceeding would constitute
an unfair labor practice.''
   Harvard's brief in the case, Harmatz said, ``is replete with
misinterpretations of the record'' of eight days of hearings the
NLRB held in August on the university's charges.
   ``Because these references either are not supported by, or
grossly overstate the proven facts, this decision seeks to, at this
level, bring a halt to this approach,'' the judge said.
   Harvard spokeswoman Marjorie Heffron said no decision has been
made on whether to appeal Harmatz's ruling to the full five-member
board. Under the law, it has two weeks to file an appeal.
   ``The university's position is sound, and the union acted
improperly,'' Harvard Vice President for Finance Robert Scott said
in a statement. ``It is plain that the opinion (by Harmatz) does
not accurately reflect the record of the hearings in many
respects.''
   The union drive, which began in 1975, and the university's
challenge had been viewed by several labor leaders as a major test
of their ability to organize educated, white- and gray-collar
technical workers who are assuming a greater proportion of the
workforce.
   AFSCME President Gerald McEntee said Monday that the election,
and the NLRB action upholding the results, was crucial for AFSCME
and as ``a test case for the labor movement as a whole.''
   ``The issues raised in this campaign were the issues that affect
the workforce of today and tomorrow _ job and family issues that
include affordable, quality child care, decent pensions and
benefits and flexibility in hours of work,'' he said.
   In the NLRB hearings, Harvard alleged that union organizers
harassed employees about voting, checked names of employees off a
master list of supporters, paid airline tickets for vacationing
workers to return to Cambridge to vote and ``systematically
interrogated'' workers on their intentions.
   Harmatz said the allegations concerned ``a perfectly legitimate,
apparently successful, tactical maneuver'' by the union to win
maximum support.
   The university ran its own aggressive campaign against
unionization that included appeals from Harvard President Derek Bok.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
