<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SriLanka 2ndLd-Writethru a0460 10-25 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0460,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Curfew In Capital, Bomb Toll Rises To 8; Police Charge Protesters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with police charging
protesters. Raises bomb's death toll to eight. Picks up 9th graf
pvs, `Police said...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strict curfew confined most
residents of this capital to their homes today while, elsewhere on
the island, police fired tear gas and charged with batons into
thousands of anti-government demonstrators.
   Authorities imposed the curfew in Colombo and surrounding areas
after a bomb killed eight people Monday at governing party meeting
in the capital.
   They said the move was necessary because of reports the People's
Liberation Front, an extremist Sinhalese group, was planning an
all-day strike. The government said it feared a strike would
trigger more violence.
   Police initially blamed the front for the Monday night bombing
at a Colombo home where members of President Junius R.
Jayewardene's United National Party, also predominantly Sinhalese,
were meeting.
   But party officials said today they had not ruled out the
possibility the bomb was the work of opposition political parties.
   Violence has escalated with the approach of presidential
elections scheduled for Dec. 19.
   The People's Liberation Front has accused the
Sinhalese-dominated government of making too many concessions to
the Tamil ethnic minority seeking a separate homeland in northern
and eastern Sri Lanka.
   In the town of Medawachchiya, about 90 miles northeast of
Colombo, police today dispersed 3,000 protesters, including many
Buddhist monks and schoolchildren demanding the government's
resignation.
   In Welimada, about 70 miles east of the capital, about 5,000
people sat down on public highways and refused to move, officials
said. Police were unable to disperse them, officials said.
   There were no immediate reports of injuries in the protests.
   Police at Colombo General Hospital said the death toll in the
bombing Monday rose to eight after three more people died of their
wounds today. At least 40 others were injured, they added.
   Police said two men on a motorcycle flung two pipes packed with
explosives into the crowd at Kotehena, 2 miles north of the city
center, but only one of the bombs exploded.
   The victims have not been identified, because the curfew
prevented relatives from going to the hospital morgue to view the
remains. But preliminary reports by police indicated most of the
dead and the most seriously injured were local members of the
United National Party.
   The curfew was imposed at midnight Monday and was to remain in
effect until 6 p.m. today. A senior Defense Ministry official said
the National Security Council would meet in emergency session later
today to decide whether to extend it.
   Streets in the capital were virtually deserted during the day.
Police passes were required for anyone desiring to leave home,
except for people seeking to buy food at shops near their homes,
according to authorities.
   The People's Liberation Front has put up posters in Colombo and
other parts of the country demanding Jayewardene's resignation,
abrogation of a peace accord aimed at ending the Tamil revolt, and
the withdrawal of 47,000 Indian soldiers deployed in Sri Lanka to
enforce the accord.
   Under the Indian-brokered accord, Tamils were to receive a
measure of autonomy if Tamil rebels surrendered their arms and
stopped attacking Sri Lankan troops and Sinhalese civilians. The
rebels refused and have been battling the Indian peacekeepers for
more than a year.
   Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
They claim they are discriminated against in employment, education
and through use of the Sinhalese language. Sinhalese, who account
for 75 percent of the population, control most top government and
military posts.
   India became involved in the internal affairs of its island
neighbor because of India's role as a regional power and the
political clout of its own Tamil minority of 60 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
