<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeltaTrial     10-25 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delta Trial,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pharmacist Testifies About Drug Prescriptions For Pilot In 1985
Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pharmacist testified that he filled
prescriptions for several drugs, including an anti-anxiety drug and
a muscle relaxant, for the pilot of Delta jetliner that crashed in
1985.
   Pharmacist Larry Thomas, testifying in a lawsuit brought by
Delta Air Lines against the government, said he filled
prescriptions for Captain Edward M. Connors from 1983 until shortly
before Delta Flight 191 crashed Aug. 2, 1985 at Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport. Connors was among 137 people who were killed.
   Thomas said Monday that the drugs Connors obtained from his
pharmacy included Stelazine, an anti-anxiety drug, and Robaxin, a
muscle relaxant.
   The pharmacist said his pharmacy filled a prescription for
Stelazine on several occasions between Sept. 21, 1982, and June 24,
1985.
   Delta sued the government contending air traffic controllers and
weather forecasters failed to warn the flight's crew of a severe
thunderstorm in the landing path.
   Miami pharmacist Gerald Warshofsky, in a deposition presented to
U.S. District Judge David O. Belew, said that he filled
prescriptions for Connors for drugs, including the tranquilizer
Valium and the painkiller Percodan.
   Federal Aviation Administration attorney Mark Bury told the
judge the government will attempt to prove that Connors also had
been taking Dalmane, a depressant used to treat insomnia, and
several antihistamines for long periods before the crash.
   Delta attorney John Martin objected to raising the drug issue,
which government lawyers say will take about two weeks to present.
   ``To spend two weeks on an issue that could not possibly have
been the cause of the accident is a waste of the court's time,''
Martin said.
   Lawyers for the airline contend that the drug issue is
irrelevant because the co-pilot, not Connors, was flying the plane
at the time it crashed while attempting to land during a
thunderstorm on a flight from Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
   Bury said the issues raises serious questions about Connors'
judgment. He noted that Connors did not disclose his use of the
drugs to the FAA as required.
   Delta attorney Maureen Murry said Connors had provided the
government with enough information and the government could have
obtained more if it wanted to.
</TEXT>
