<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-SeatBelts     10-25 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Seat Belts,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Loses Suit Because He Failed To Wear Seatbelt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMM, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man paralyzed from the waist down
when his parked car was rammed by another vehicle has lost a
lawsuit because he was not wearing a seat belt when he was injured.
   ``The ruling was a one-time decision due to the insurance policy
clause which mandates wearing a seat belt even if the car is parked
and the motor off. It does not apply to the overall seat belt
law,'' Hamm court spokesman Karl-Heinz Heugemann said today.
   West German law requires all passengers in private cars to wear
seat belts when the motor is running.
   Heugemann said the court decision only involved special daily
insurance payments to the injured man during his stay in the
hospital, ``which amounted to about 5,000 marks ($2,777).''
   His hospital and medical care payments were not affected by the
insurance clause, said Heugemann.
   Heugemann said the man was paralyzed in an accident at a service
station while he was waiting in his parked car with the motor off.
   ``He wasn't wearing a seat belt, and another vehicle hit his car
while he was waiting for the service station to open,'' said
Heugemann.
   He declined to provide the name of the man involved in the case,
or say when he was injured.
</TEXT>
