<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-USArmy     10-25 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-US Army,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Confirms Criminal Probe Of Green Berets In Far East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Army said today it was investigating
members of the Green Berets after a military court convicted a
sergeant of plotting to kill a Green Beret captain in Thailand.
   The U.S. military court on Okinawa convicted Sgt. Maj. Edward J.
Gleason Jr. of solicitation to commit murder and sentenced him
Friday to seven years in prison, reduction in rank to private and
forfeiture of all pay and allowances.
   The general court-martial found Gleason, 45, a Vietnam veteran
with 26 years in uniform, guilty of plotting to kill Capt. Paul
Dumpson, a fellow member of the Okinawa-based First Battalion,
First Special Forces Group.
   The Pacific Stars And Stripes, an army-authorized newspaper,
published the first news of the court-martial and said the case
``fueled rumors here that Special Forces soldiers were smuggling
guns, gold and drugs.''
   Asked to comment on the report, the U.S. Army headquarters in
Japan declined to go into detail.
   ``There is an ongoing investigation into other allegedly
criminal activity,'' said Capt. Don Longfellow, a deputy public
affairs officer. To comment further could prejudice the inquiry, he
said.
   The several hundred Green Beret troops headquartered on Okinawa,
the southern Japanese island where some 30,000 U.S. troops are
based, often go on training exercises in friendly Asian countries
like Thailand, where the murder plot took place.
   The Stars And Stripes account of the trial said Gleason, of New
Orleans, offered James Bonard Fowler, an American in Thailand,
$50,000 to kill Dumpson. It said Gleason called off the plot when
he suspected it had been discovered and, and that he was arrested
in July. Fowler was not further identified.
   The army said Dumpson, whose hometown was unavailable, continued
on duty with his unit.
   Gleason was not given a punitive discharge, so he retained his
retirement benefits.
</TEXT>
