<2ND_LINE>PM-DeSillers,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maria DeSillers Loses Battle Over Final Hospital Payment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maria DeSillers must pay a $235,000 hospital bill
for her late son's three unsuccessful liver transplants, a judge
has ordered.
   Dade Circuit Judge Francis Christie approved a proposed
settlement Monday over the objections of Ms. Desillers, who was
ejected from the hearing after an outburst.
   The settlement, which was reached by the Children's Hospital of
Pittsburgh and Karen Gievers, the court-appointed curator of Ronnie
DeSiller's estate, represented a 10 percent discount on its
original charge of $261,000.
   Ms. DeSillers was thrown out of the courtroom in the second
phase of the hearing, which dealt with a $31,000 bill from the
state.
   The state said it would drop the bill if the balance of the
estate were turned over to the Governor's Transplant Lifeline for
Children, set up to help children in Ronnie's circumstances. The
judge approved the arrangement.
   During state testimony about the TLC program, Ms. DeSillers
slammed her hand down on a notebook and complained that TLC turned
her down when she asked for help for Ronnie.
   ``No more outbursts,'' Christie warned. ``Do you understand me?''
   ``No sir, I don't,'' she said, ``because they did not help me
with my child.''
   ``Get her out of here,'' the judge ordered the bailiff.
   Ms. DeSillers contended that the hospital did not treat the boy
correctly. Her attorney, Frank Johnson, questioned price
discrepancies between allegedly similar items on the 1,700-page
bill.
   The payment will leave Ronnie's estate with $25,000 to $30,000.
Donations of more than $670,000 poured in from around the country
while the 7-year-old endured the futile operations.
   Ms. DeSillers, who paid $162,000 on the original bill of
$424,000, balked on paying the balance last year and sued the
hospital.
   Johnson said Ms. DeSillers' criminal attorney, Roy Black, who
represents her in a pending investigation by the local state
attorney's office, had advised her not to reveal information to the
curator because it would compromise Ms. DeSiller's guarantees
against self-incrimination.
   Edwin K. Zechman Jr., president of Children's Hospital, said the
recommendations of the curator and the judge's decision ``fully
vindicate our position.''
   After the hospital is paid, $25,000 to $30,000 will remain in
the bank account that was set up for contributions on behalf of
children in need of transplant surgery.
</TEXT>
