<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Shark Attack,0140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Surfer Pulls Leg Out of Great White Shark's Mouth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANNON BEACH, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 21-year-old surfer says he was
attacked by a great white shark but was able to pull his leg out of
the attacker's mouth.
   Wyndham Kapan of Cannon Beach received 21 stitches in his right
knee following the Sunday afternoon attack, said his mother, Jan
Kapan.
   ``He's very lucky he didn't lose the leg,'' his mother said
Monday.
   Great white sharks usually are seen off the coast between August
and December, said Bruce Mate, a marine mammologist with the
Hatfield Marine Science Center in Newport. The animals are drawn to
areas with a large numbers of seals and sea lions.
   Surfers are especially vulnerable because a surfboard can look
like a seal to a shark swimming underwater, Mate said.
</TEXT>
