<HEAD>Israeli Troops Wound At Least Six Palestinians</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with army retracting report that 7-year-old died,
other details on violence. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and wounded at least six
Palestinians today in clashes throughout the occupied territories,
Arab hospital officials said.
   The violence occurred a day after soldiers shot and killed a
17-year-old Palestinian in the occupied West Bank. The death
brought the number of Palestinians killed in the 10-month-old
Palestinian uprising to 302. Six Israelis also have died.
   The army, meanwhile, today retracted a report that a 7-year-old
Arab boy died after being shot in the chest with a plastic bullet
during a nighttime clash in the occupied Gaza Strip.
   Two military spokesmen in Tel Aviv and Jerusalem called The
Associated Press to say their earlier report was erroneous and that
the boy was in stable condition at Tel Hashomer Hospital near Tel
Aviv. No explanation was given for the error.
   The boy, Ali Hussein Abu Amra, was hit in the chest by a plastic
bullet after troops fired at stone-throwing protesters in the
Shabura neighborhood of Rafah on Monday night, an official at
Nasser Hospital said.
   Abu Amra was taken intially to Nasser Hospital and later
transferred to Tel Hashomer. A hospital spokesman, Dr. Moshe
Tirosh, said the boy was in intensive care with a bullet wound to
the chest.
   Soldiers today imposed a curfew on the neighborhood where Abu
Amra was shot and troops fired tear gas at high school students who
stoned soldiers elsewhere in Rafah, but there were no injuries,
Arab news reports said.
   Arab reports and witnesses said nine people were wounded today _
two of them seriously _ in confrontations in six cities and refugee
camps in the occupied territories.
   The army said it was checking the reports.
   A 22-year-old man suffered a serious plastic gunshot wound in
the neck when soldiers raided the village of Tamoun near the city
of Nablus, Arab news reports said. He was taken to Rafidiyeh
Hospital in Nablus, the reports said.
   At Ahli Arab Hospital in Gaza City, Mohammed Ali Rweideh, 26, of
Nozeirat refugee camp in Gaza was reported in critical condition
with a bullet wound to the chest.
   Two teen-agers, aged 14 and 15, were struck by plastic bullets
during stoning protests in the Gaza town of Khan Yunis and Deir el
Balah refugee camp, hospital officials said.
   Soldiers later clamped a curfew on parts of Khan Yunis in
response to the protests and detained about a dozen Palestinians,
according to Arab news reports.
   Elsewhere in Gaza, an Israeli oil tanker driver opened fire in a
marketplace after the tire of his truck was hit by a firebomb, Arab
witnesses said. Three Palestinian men were hospitalized with
gunshot wounds, a hospital official said.
   Arab reports said soldiers at scene also opened fire. It was
unclear who fired the bullets that struck the Palestinians.
   Witnesses said a donkey was fatally shot and a horse was wounded
in the incident.
   In the West Bank city of Ramallah, a 15-year-old boy was hit in
the abdomen by a bullet after troops opened fire on Arab
stone-throwers, a local hospital official said.
   Soldiers also shot and wounded a 35-year-old man in the left leg
during a clash with stone-throwers in Nablus, an official at Al
Ittihad Hospital said.
</TEXT>
