<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Election, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0444,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor, Likud Clash Over Hussein's Television Appearance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS three grafs to ADD Arafat urging Arabs to vote to
influence the government; PICKS up 4th pvs, `In a ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Likud and Labor parties clashed over a U.S.
television appearance by King Hussein of Jordan in which the
monarch said he was ready to head a Jordanian-Palestinian
delegation in peace talks with Israel.
   In television commercials Monday, the left-wing Labor Party
claimed Hussein proved the credibility of its peace platform by
announcing he was ready to take an active part in talks with Israel.
   The right-wing Likud Bloc accused Labor of being ready to hand
all the territories Israel captured in the 1967 Middle East war to
Yasser Arafat, head of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Arafat on Sunday urged Arab Israelis to participate in the Nov.
1 election and said Jewish voters should cast ballots for peace.
   By participating in the elections, Arabs can assure themselves
of 14-15 seats in Israel's parliament and influence the government,
Arafat was quoted as telling Egypt's Middle East News Agency.
   Arafat also said Palestinians in the occupied territories would
not take up arms to continue the 10-month uprising against Israeli
rule. More than 300 Palestinians and six Israelis have died in the
uprising, which is a key Israeli election issue.
   In a hard-hitting ad with grim music, the Likud showed a
portrait of Arafat on Labor's ballot slip, indicating a vote for
Labor was a vote for the PLO.
   The Likud also charged Labor with orchestrating Hussein's
television appearance and said it was a cheap ploy to win votes.
   Both parties showed clips of Hussein's interview, which was
broadcast Thursday on ABC's ``Nightline.''
   Labor has campaigned on a peace platform based on direct
negotations with a joint delegation of Jordan and Palestinians who
do not belong to the PLO, which Israel considers a terrorist
organization. The talks would be held under the aegis of an
international peace conference.
   The campaign appeared to lose credibility after Hussein
announced last summer he was giving up all claims to the occupied
territories and acknowledged the PLO's responsibility for them.
   In one segment of the interview, Hussein praised Labor Party
leader and Foreign Minister Shimon Peres. A party spokeswoman said
the interview disproved Likud claims that Labor's peace proposal
was unrealistic.
   In one commercial, Labor screened film clips of Sunday's
television debate between Peres and Likud leader and Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir to support its claim the Likud is intransigent about
peace.
   Labor showed one clip in which Shamir distinguished between the
Sinai desert, which Israel gave back to Egypt in return for peace,
and the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, which, he said, were an
integral part of the biblical land of Israel.
   The Likud rejects the proposal for an international peace
conference and opposes yielding any part of the occupied
territories.
</TEXT>
