<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Round Table, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0518,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks in Doubt as Government Demands Meeting With Walesa</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8 grafs for last graf pvs, `Urban charged ...' to ADD
further Walesa comment, background. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today demanded an immediate
meeting with Lech Walesa to prepare the way for the convening
Friday of talks with the opposition on Poland's future.
   Walesa rejected the demand, leaving prospects for the start to
the round-table talks in doubt.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said Walesa and Interior
Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak must meet Wednesday to clear away
disputes on who can participate in the talks.
   The government objects to two names proposed by Solidarity and
wants clarification on whether the individuals will respect
Poland's constitutional order, he said.
   The talks cannot begin without such a preparatory meeting, Urban
told reporters at his weekly news conference.
   Walesa later reiterated that he would reject any governent
interference in the composition of Solidarity's delegation to the
talks. He said he does not want another preparatory meeting with
Kiszczak. The two men have met three times since Aug. 31.
   ``I will not allow any personnel changes. It could be a
precedent, a dangerous precedent for the future,'' Walesa said.
   He said church mediator Andrzej Stelmachowski was fully
empowered to negotiate any other procedural or technical matters on
his behalf.
   Walesa, who spoke by telephone from his home in Gdansk, said he
still hoped for discussions that would bring about ``understanding
and the implementation of pluralism,'' and said the proposed date
of Friday was acceptable to him for the talks to begin.
   Urban charged that Solidarity's ``stubbornness'' was preventing
the talks from beginning.
   Urban's remarks today were the first time the government has
announced a proposed date for the round-table talks.
   Kiszczak and Walesa agreed to such talks Aug. 31 while strikes
continued around Poland in the country's worst labor unrest in
seven years.
   After begin guaranteed the talks could include the subject of
Solidarity's future, as well as broader questions of economic and
political pluralism in the communist country, Walesa ended the
strikes.
   The opposition demands the talks lead to legalization of
Solidarity, banned in 1982 after the December 1981 martial law
crackdown.
   Solidarity had been the first recognized independent labor
federation in the Soviet bloc.
   On Friday, Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski said the
government opposes legalizing Solidarity until the economy improves
and Poland changes its political system to allow more political
demands outside of trade unions.
</TEXT>
