<1ST_LINE>d a PM-Lites Correction a0470 10-25 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites, Correction, a0470,0295</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS second item in PM-Lites, a0470, to make area code 508
thoughout</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents in this upscale suburb 12 miles
southwest of Boston say three months with the new 508 telephone
area code is three months too long.
   The town's cry to revert back to the greater Boston area code of
617 was being heard today by the Legislature's government
regulations committee, which has received more than 100 letters
from residents upset about the change.
   A bill that would force the change back was filed this summer by
Rep. Ellen Canavan of Needham when the state Department of Public
Utilities rejected the town's request.
   ``It's one of the daily, constant little things that drive you
crazy,'' said Canavan, who lives in neighboring Needham, which
retained its 617 code.
   Dover is one of 193 communities given the new 508 area code by
the New England Telephone Co. in an effort to avoid running out of
telephone numbers in eastern Massachusetts.
   The 508 zone includes Boston's far western suburbs, much of
central Massachusetts, Cape Cod and the islands, southeastern
Massachusetts, Cape Ann and the Merrimack Valley.
   Dover residents say they are oriented toward Boston and not
central Massachusetts. But they acknowledge the town's affluence
makes it liable to charges of seeking special consideration.
   Telephone company officials say the designations were carefully
made, and they fear if Dover's effort is successful, other
municipalities will rebel.
   ``Unfortunately, it's a very emotional issue,'' said Jacqueline
Jung, a New England Telephone spokeswoman.
   ``But for some very real business reasons we had to draw the
line somewhere. It was a long thoughtful process. Dover is no
different from any other community. It just thinks it's different.''
</TEXT>
