<HEAD>Emperor Receives Emergency Transfusion, In Stable Condition</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf ``Hirohito's blood pressure.. '' with one graf
to clarify that emperor's blood pressure had fallen and went up
after transfusion. </NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito received an emergency blood
transfusion today to counter intestinal bleeding, the Imperial
Household Agency said.
   Physicians gave the 87-year-old monarch more than a pint of
blood, bringing the total he has received since becoming ill Sept.
19 to about 26 pints _ more than three times his normal circulation.
   Hirohito's blood pressure _ which had fallen to below 100
systolic before the transfusion _ went up to 118 over 58 and his
pulse was 108 beats a minutes this afternoon, palace spokesman
Kenji Maeda said. A normal blood pressure reading is about 120 over
80.
   The emperor also was running a fever.
   The world's longest-reigning monarch was in stable condition and
was sleeping well late this afternoon, Maeda said.
   Earlier today, doctors said Hirohito's anemia was improving.
   They believe the bleeding originates from Hirohito's intestine,
which underwent surgery in September 1987 to bypass a blockage
caused by an inflamed pancreas.
</TEXT>
