<HEAD>At Least Five Wounded In Car Bomb Explosion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with casualties, other details. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded today in the
Syrian-policed town of Barr Elias in the Bekaa Valley, injuring at
least five people, police said.
   A police spokesman reached by telephone in Zahle, provincial
capital of the Bekaa, said the car blew up at 1:10 p.m. outside a
grocery store on the Beirut-Damascus highway.
   ``Rescuers evacuated at least five wounded civilians from the
scene,'' said the spokesman, who cannot be named in line with
police regulations.
   In Beirut, the Voice of the Nation radio station said Syrian
troops cordoned off Barr Elias after the explosion, the 16th car
bombing in Lebanon this year.
   Ambulances and fire engines were sent from Zahle to Barr Elias,
28 miles southeast of Beirut. The town has a predominantly Sunni
Moslem population of 30,000.
   Like most of the Bekaa region, Barr Elias is controlled by
Syrian troops. Syrian maintains an estimated 40,000 soldiers in the
eastern and northern provinces as well as Moslem west Beirut.
   The force is supported by Lebanon's Moslems and leftists, and
violently opposed by right-wing Christians who regard the Syrians
an occupying power.
   By police count, 104 people were killed and 378 wounded in 15
previous car bombings in Lebanon since April 23.
</TEXT>
