<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShuttleAstronauts 1stLd-Writethru a0418 10-25 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle Astronauts, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0418,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Discovery Astronauts To Thank Shuttle Launch Team</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs with ceremony, picks up graf 5, ``Along
the</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Mid-morning EDT lead expected.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Discovery's five astronauts today
thanked the workers here who launched them into space last month on
the first post-Challenger space shuttle flight.
   ``If there's a heartbeat of America's space program, it's here
at the Kennedy Space Center; we thank you for helping us pull off
this successful mission,'' Discovery pilot Richard O. Covey told a
crowd of several thousand.
   ``What made our vehicle lift off the launch pad was not the
solid fuel booster rockets or the main engines,'' said mission
specialist George D. Nelson. ``What was pushing us was all your
good feelings and the work you put into it.''
   Commander Frederick H. Hauck presented the workers with an
autograph book which he and his crew carried into orbit. It bears
the signatures of more than 15,000 technicians, engineers,
managers, clerical and other sdpace center personnel who signed it
before the launch.
   In accepting the book, center director Forrest S. McCartney said
it would ``become a part of the Kennedy Space Center's history.''
   Hauck also presented McCartney with a picture montage of three
shuttle launchings that included a photograph of the seven
Challenger astronauts kiilled when that shuttle exploded on Jan.
28, 1986.
   Hauck, Covey, Nelson and the other crew members, John M. Lounge
and David C. Hilmers, were honored Monday by thousands of people
who lined the motorcade route in nearby Cocoa Beach, where many of
the space workers live.
   Along the route, which they traveled in convertibles, the
astronauts were greeted by high school bands, congratulatory signs,
American flags and applause.
   The ceremonies continue a busy schedule for the space travelers
since their four-day flight. They have been honored by President
Reagan at the White House, visited Congress and were hailed at
celebrations at the Johnson Space Center in Houston and the
Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Ala.
   Meanwhile, workers here were joining the space shuttle Atlantis
to its two solid fuel boster rockets and external fuel tank,
preparing it for a launch in late November with a classified
Defense Department satellite. Atlantis is scheduled to be
transported to the launch pad next weekend.
</TEXT>
