<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Swindall 1stLd-Writethru a0489 10-25 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Swindall, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0489,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Brings Up Reagan's Faulty Memory in Jury Selection</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Swindall offering to waive
jury trial, judge's refusal. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `Two of...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Pat Swindall today offered to give up his
right to a jury trial on federal perjury charges in order to obtain
a verdict by Election Day, but U.S. District Judge Robert Vining
immediately rejected the idea.
   With jury selection entering its third day, Swindall told
Vining, ``I'm just real concerned as to whether or not we can get
this case tried this week and next week.''
   Swindall added, ``I am prepared to waive my right to be tried by
a jury. It's not something I want to do.''
   Vining would determine a verdict in a non-jury trial, but he
said he would not do so in Swindall's case. He pledged to try to
expedite the trial while safeguarding the congressman's rights.
   ``Mr. Swindall, I understand the importance of the events of
Nov. 8 to you,'' Vining said. ``However, I do think there are
things more important to you than the election of Nov. 8.''
   Swindall, who contends the perjury charges against him are based
on lapses in his memory, cited President Reagan's claims of faulty
memory in the Iran-contra affair as he questioned prospective
jurors Monday.
   Acting as his own attorney, Swindall asked four of 18
prospective jurors about Reagan's claim that he could not remember
the extent of his knowledge regarding the sale of arms to Iran and
diversion of some proceeds to Nicaraguan rebels.
   Two of the prospective jurors seemed sympathetic to Reagan's
claim. Two others indicated they were skeptical.
   Twenty more people were to be questioned today by Swindall,
prosecutor Craig Gillen and Judge Robert Vining. Selection of the
12-member jury was expected to be completed today.
   On Monday, Vining granted Swindall's motion to excuse one
potential juror who said he would lean toward the prosecution.
   Swindall, 38-year-old two-term Republican, said he remained
confident the trial can be completed before the Nov. 8 election, in
which he faces Democrat Ben Jones.
   After Swindall's Oct. 17 indictment on 10 counts, he demanded a
quick start for his trial because of the election.
   He is accused of lying to a grand jury, primarily about a
meeting he held last year with an undercover Internal Revenue
Service agent posing as a money broker.
   The prosecution, which has a tape recording of the meeting, says
Swindall knew the agent was suggesting that illegal drug proceeds
would be used to back an $850,000 mortgage for Swindall's house.
   The loan was never executed, although Swindall did briefly
accept a $150,000 check from another man involved in the
negotiations.
   Swindall has said he was tripped up by a ``memory contest'' and
never intended to deceive the grand jury.
   Vining ruled that Swindall may put himself on the witness stand
without using another attorney to question him.
   Gillen objected, arguing that Swindall would be able to deliver
a monologue without giving the government a chance to object to
improper questions. But Vining said he did not want to interfere
with Swindall's right to represent himself.
   Although recent polls show Jones with a 2-1 lead, Swindall said
he remained confident he can defeat Jones ``as soon as that
acquittal happens.'' He said the end of the trial would allow him
to contrast his conservative record with what he described as
Jones' liberal stands.
</TEXT>
