<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Temptation     10-25 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Temptation,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest 30 In Cinema Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 30 people today for questioning in
a fire that destroyed a movie theater showing ``The Last Temptation
of Christ'' and injured 13 people.
   Police said the arrests came in raids aimed at extremist
right-wing groups, but would not indicate what their searches had
disclosed. Authorities said the fire late Saturday was set.
   Several hundred people, including political and film
personalities, demonstrated Monday night in front of the St. Michel
theater in the Latin Quarter. The theater earlier had been the
scene of protests against the film directed by American Martin
Scorsese.
   Mayor Jacques Chirac ``condemned without reservation'' what he
called the ``absurd attack.''
   Among those participating in the demonstration in support of the
film were directors Claude Lelouch and Francis Girod and writer Max
Gallo, who criticized those who ``condemned the film without having
seen it.''
   Earlier Monday, the extreme right National Front party condemned
the ``criminal fire'' but said ``the first violence was that which
wounded millions of believers in their most sacred convictions.''
   ``Last Temptation'' opened in 17 Paris theaters Sept. 28, but
only one theater is still showing the film. Moviegoers have been
met with fires, stink bombs and tear gas.
   The film, based on a novel by Nikos Kasantzakis, portrays Jesus
Christ as having human passions, including a dream sequence in
which he makes love with prostitute Mary Magdalene.
</TEXT>
