<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Kahane     10-25 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Kahane,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kahane Seeks Return Of U.S. Citizenship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brooklyn-born Rabbi Meir Kahane, the anti-Arab
militant who renounced his U.S. citizenship to run for Israel's
parliament, said today he wants to be an American citizen again.
   Kahane said he planned to fly to the United States on Wednesday
for a fund-raising tour, but U.S. officials said his passport was
no longer valid and he would not be able to use it to gain entry.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman in Tel Aviv said Kahane formally
renounced his citizenship Sept. 16, and on Oct. 7 the State
Department approved the certificate of loss of nationality.
   On Oct. 18, Kahane appeared before a consular officer in
Jerusalem and asked to reverse the move, said the embassy
spokesman, who requested anonymity. ``We are informing him that the
renunciation can't be reversed but that there is a procedure for
appeal,'' said the spokesman.
   He said Kahane has one year to submit an appeal to the State
Department's Board of Appellate Review. He can also appeal in
federal court.
   Kahane, who founded the militant Jewish Defense League in the
United States, said in a telephone interview that he ``was forced''
to give up his U.S. citizenship by a new amendment to Israeli law
that bars dual nationals from running for Knesset, or parliament.
   On Oct. 5, the Election Commission issued a decision barring
Kahane's anti-Arab Kach party, which polls indicated might win
three or more seats in the Nov. 1 election for the 120-seat
parliament.
   On Oct. 18, the Israeli Supreme Court upheld by a unanimous 5-0
vote the exclusion of Kach on grounds the party was racist. Kahane
advocates the expulsion of all Arabs from Israeli-held territory.
   After the court decision, Kahane said he immediately notified
the U.S. State Department and U.S. Consulate that he wanted to
withdraw his renunciation.
   ``It was conditioned clearly in my application on my Knesset
list being approved,'' said Kahane.
   Kahane claimed the U.S. and Israeli governments had a ``common
interest'' in barring him from making a speaking tour in which he
would condemn Israel's banning of his Kach party.
   Kahane, who immigrated to Israel in 1971, was elected to the
Knesset in 1984. Kahane, who has been barred from Canada and
Britain, said that without U.S. citizenship he might be refused a
visa to travel to the United States.
   In refusing him entry, Canadian officials cited Kahane's July
23, 1971, conviction in New York for possession of explosives,
bombs and other weapons. Kahane served one year of a five-year term
in that case.
   Kahane also has served several jail terms in Israel, including a
one-year administrative detention without trial and three months
for defying an army order barring him from a West Bank town. Both
were related to attempts to establish Jewish settlements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
