<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1105EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Italy-Hostages     10-25 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Hostages,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Anderson Photo Appears to Be Copy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said today the photograph of American
hostage Terry Anderson that was found in the bag of a Lebanese
woman appears to be a copy and not an original.
   They said they were still examining a photograph of American
hostage Alann Steen, a photograph of an unidentified man and
several documents, including a letter bearing Steen's name. The
photos and documents were discovered in the woman's luggage when
she arrived in Milan.
   Achille Serra, head of the anti-terrorism unit of Milan police,
told reporters police had to check further before determining
whether the photos and letter were part of an effort to free U.S.
hostages in Lebanon, or part of some sort of swindle.
   ``It depends a lot on (Steen's) handwriting,'' Serra said. ``If
the handwriting (sample) .. shows that this letter wasn't written
by Steen, things change a lot. We would be talking about a fraud.''
   He would not say who might have been the object of a possible
swindle. Police were awaiting a handwriting sample from the United
States.
   The photo of Anderson, the longest-held of the foreign hostages
in Lebanon, appeared similar _ in reverse image _ to one issued by
the pro-Iranian group Islamic Jihad in August.
   Serra said he had not seen the earlier photo, but ``I believe,
at least for the time being, you can say that it (the photo) was
not taken of the person himself, it's a photo of a photo.''
   According to police, the Lebanese woman was to turn the photos
and documents over to Aldo Anghessa, an Italian arms trader with
links to Swiss and Italian intelligence agencies.
   The woman, identified as Aline Ibrahim Rizkallah, 36, said she
was to receive about $4,000 from Anghessa, but the Italian has
denied it, police said. She was arrested Thursday after arriving in
Milan from Beirut.
   Serra refused to speculate Tuesday about who was to ultimately
receive the photos and letter. ``We have our suspicions about the
destination, but I guarantee you on my word of honor that we don't
know who was to get it,'' he told a news conference.
   He refused comment on a suggestion he made Monday that an
American organization was the intended destination.
   Serra said police had identified the man who supplied the
Lebanese woman with photographs, documents, 1.7 ounces of heroin
and $1,000 in counterfeit U.S. bills.
   Italian police were considering traveling to Lebanon to question
the man, he said.
   It was unclear why the woman would endanger herself by carrying
small amounts of fake money and heroin. She was jailed for
possessing them.
   Anghessa was not charged because there was no proof the drugs or
money were destined for him, police said.
   Islamic Jihad denied Monday that it was connected with the woman.
   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, was seized on March 16, 1985.
   Steen, of Boston, was kidnapped Jan. 24, 1987 at Beirut
University College, where he taught.
   Fourteen foreigners, including nine Americans, are missing and
presumed kidnapped in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
