<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AmnestyScam     10-25 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty Scam,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Ordered to Pay $400,000 in Damages in Amnesty Scam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer accused of taking fees from more than
400 aliens seeking legalization, and then failing to file their
federal amnesty applications, has been ordered to pay nearly
$400,000 in damages.
   Edward Triwush, whose law license was suspended by the Illinois
Supreme Court earlier this year, was ordered Monday by Circuit
Judge Anthony Scotillo to pay a total of $395,568 in damages to 417
aliens and 11 employers.
   Manuel Sanchez and John Daniels, the lawyers now representing
the aliens, said Triwush took fees ranging from $40 to $850 from
aliens and employers last year, but did not file applications in
the amnesty program granting legal residency for those who had
lived continuously in the United States since 1982.
   The deadline for applications was May 1.
   During the six months that he was accepting fees, Triwush
continued to work although the Illinois Supreme Court suspended his
license for his failure to file a brief in an unrelated case,
officials said.
   The Supreme Court later ordered Triwush jailed for 30 days, but
suspended the sentence after he agreed to make restitution of
$90,000 to the aliens and employers, representing the amount of
fees accepted during the six-month suspension. He was ordered to
appear Nov. 15 to explain he should not be held in contempt. The
Supreme Court could reimpose the jail sentence at that time.
   None of the $90,000 had been repaid, Daniels said.
   Scotillo imposed the judgment Monday after Triwush failed to
comply with requests for information from Sanchez and Daniels.
   Daniels said Triwush also pleaded guilty to theft in Lake County
Circuit Court for accepting fees from aliens but failing to file
any documents. Triwush was placed on 30 months' probation and
ordered to make resitution in that case, officials said.
   He has an unlisted telephone number in Chicago and could not be
reached.
</TEXT>
