<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Turkey-Flight     10-25 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Turkey-Flight,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistani Jetliner Hits Seagulls, Makes Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pakistani jetliner with 415 passengers
aboard landed safely today after two of its four engines failed
when the plane hit a flock of seagulls, an Istanbul airport
official said.
   The Pakistani International Airlines jet struck the birds as it
was taking off from Istanbul, the source said. The plane dumped 40
tons of fuel into the Marmara Sea and then returned to Ataturk
Airport, the official said.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the jet
landed 57 minutes after hitting the seagulls.
   The plane had been scheduled to fly from Islamabad to London
with stops in Istanbul and Amsterdam.
   The semi-official Anatolia news agency said the passengers were
scheduled to fly to London later today on another Pakistani
jetliner.
   The agency said experts determined the damaged aircraft's two
engines suffered considerable damage and would have to be replaced.
</TEXT>
