<DOCNO> AP881025-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1202EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Steinberg     10-25 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinberg,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steinberg Trial to Begin Today</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lisa Steinberg, whose death last year became a
symbol of child abuse in America, was viciously beaten by the only
father she ever knew, a prosecutor charged this morning as the
murder trial of Joel Steinberg began.
   Lisa died on Nov. 5 when she was removed from a respirator, but
``she was really killed days earlier,'' Assistant District Attorney
Peter Casolaro told the jury. ``Steinberg beat Lisa so severely
that he inflicted those injures which caused her death.''
   Casolaro told the panel that ``graphic and grotesque'' evidence
and testimony will prove Steinberg murdered the child. Six-year-old
Lisa was found unconscious in the Steinberg apartment early Nov. 2,
1987, and died of her injuries three days later.
   Steinberg, a disbarred lawyer who took the child illegally at
birth from an unwed Long Island teen-ager, is charged with
second-degree murder.
   Defense attorney Ira London said the evidence would not support
the prosecution's claim.
   ``It will not be proven in this case that Lisa Steinberg was
murdered, nor will it be prove that Lisa was a battered child,''
London said in a brief opening in which he also attacked Hedda
Nussbaum, Steinberg's longtime live-in companion and an anticipated
key prosecution witness.
   London called Ms. Nussbaum ``delusional,'' mentioned she had
spent the last year in a mental hospital and alluded to her
``romance with Satanic cults.''
   Following the opening statement, a paramedic who arrived at the
Steinberg home to find Lisa unconcious and her brother Mitchell
tethered to a playpen took the stand as the trial's first witness.
   Steinberg denies ever hitting Lisa; he claims she was sickened
by food, and the bruises on her back and chest resulted from his
trying to revive her after she fell unconscious the night of Nov.
1, 1987.
   Justice Harold Rothwax ruled Monday that prosecutors may tell
jurors that Ms. Nussbaum, 46, waited at least 10 hours before she
called for help for the comatose child because she was terrified of
Steinberg.
   No help was called for Lisa until after 6:30 a.m. on Nov. 2,
court records show. When police and medical technicians arrived,
they found the girl unconscious and a 16-month-old boy, called
Mitchell, tethered to his playpen, lying in a soiled diaper and
drinking spoiled milk.
   Lisa was pronounced brain dead at nearby St. Vincent's Hospital
at 8:55 a.m. on Nov. 5.
   The six men and six women who will hear the case, which is
expected to last four to eight weeks, will likely hear testimony
about child abuse, beatings, drug abuse, sadomasochism and illegal
adoptions.
   Ms. Nussbaum was charged along with Steinberg in Lisa's death,
but never indicted. After her arrest, she underwent surgery and
psychiatric treatment for injuries allegedly inflicted by
Steinberg. The prosecution has said all charges against her
probably will be dropped.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
