<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Edwards     10-25 0127</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Edwards,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Blocks Scheduled Mississippi Execution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today blocked Wednesday's
scheduled execution in Mississippi of convicted murderer Leo
Edwards.
   The justices, by an 8-0 vote, granted Edwards the emergency stay
pending further appeals in his case. Justice Antonin Scalia did not
take part in the decision.
   Edwards, 33, was due to be executed at 12:01 a.m. in the gas
chamber at Mississippi State Penitentiary at Parchman.
   He was convicted of murder in the June 1980 robbery-slaying of
Linzy Don Dixon at a Jackson, Miss., convenience store. Dixon, 24,
a store clerk, was gunned down while he was on the telephone. The
robbery netted $111, authorities said.
   Edwards, of New Orleans, had escaped from a Louisiana prison at
the time.
</TEXT>
