<DOCNO> AP881025-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EdwardsAppeal     10-25 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Edwards Appeal,0148</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Stays Mississippi Execution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Supreme Court today stayed the
execution of convicted murderer Leo Edwards, who was to die
Wednesday.
   Edwards, 33, was convicted in April 1981 of capital murder in
the June 1980 murder of a convenience store clerk in Jackson,
during a robbery which netted $111.
   Edwards, of New Orleans, was an escapee from a Louisiana prison
at the time he went on a spree of robberies and killings in Hinds
and Madison counties.
   Edwards' attorney, Kenneth Rose of Jackson, has contended that
prosecutors systematically excluded blacks as potential juros thus
denying Edwards, who is black, a trial by a cross-section of the
community.
   Edwards was convicted by an all-white jury.
   A federal judge in Jackson, and the Fifth U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in New Orleans had rejected that argument.
</TEXT>
