Daylight Savings Time by two weeks each election year and closing
polls at 7 p.m. local time.
   Swift's bill has passed the House twice but died in the Senate.
He said he doesn't know if he'll try again.
   Critics of Swift's proposal say that while election-night
projections might spoil the surprise for Western voters, studies
have failed to show that they discourage significant numbers of
people from voting.
   Swift concedes the lack of such evidence but argues that
Westerners may grow disillusioned even though they vote.
   The importance of an individual's vote ``is the basic building
block of democracy,'' he said. ``When people lose confidence in
that, I think that's dangerous.''
   But Jeff Alderman, ABC director of polling, said the networks
are hardly to blame for voter disillusionment.
   ``We spend a lot of time focusing on the alleged influence of
polling and coverage in general,'' Alderman said. ``But it's not
network television's job to give people a stake in the election.
It's up to the people running, and they're not doing it.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>---</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: David Foster is the AP Northwest regional
reporter based in Seattle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
