<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Nicaragua     10-25 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Nicaragua,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Ups Ante in Diplomatic Tiff with Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua diplomats and other officials will
be denied visas to enter the United States under a proclamation
signed by President Reagan, the White House announced today.
   The action is another step in the diplomatic conflict between
the Sandinista government and the Reagan administration, which
dates back to July 11, when Managua expelled U.S. Ambassador
Richard Melton and seven other diplomats.
   The United States retaliated the next day by expelling
Nicaraguan ambassador Carlos Tunnermann and seven others.
   Since then, the Sandinista government has not acted on U.S.
attempts to replace the expelled U.S. envoy to the Central American
nation.
   Reagan, in his proclamation, says he found ``the unrestricted
... entry of officers and employees of the Nicaraguan government
and the Sandinista National Liberation Front ... to be detrimental
to the interests of the United States.''
   White House spokesman Roman Popadiuk pointed out that the
presidential action comes not only in the wake of the July
explusions, but also in light of further restrictions placed on
U.S. officials in Nicaragua.
   ``We've been trying to get our people replaced, and we haven't
gotten anywhere,'' Popadiuk said.
   He noted that on Sept. 22, the Sandinista government required
that American diplomats based in Nicaragua who leave the country,
for whatever reason, must wait three weeks before they are allowed
to re-enter Nicaragua.
   At the time, the administration said it would take some type of
retaliatory action, but did not state what it would be.
   Diplomats already posted to the Nicaraguan embassy in Washington
are unaffected by the proclamation. Officials assigned now or in
the future to the Nicaraguan U.N. mission in New York or the
mission to the Organization of American States in Washington are
also unaffected.
</TEXT>
