<DOCNO> AP881025-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-WisconsinSenate     10-25 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wisconsin Senate,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proxmire's Successor: Millionaire Businessman or Female State
Senator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD EGGLESTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millionaire businessman Herbert Kohl won
Wisconsin's Democratic Senate primary in the face of charges he was
buying the election with personal wealth _ a far cry from the
penny-pinching campaigns of William Proxmire, the man he hopes to
succeed.
   In the most recent general election polling, Kohl also has been
leading the Republican nominee, state Senate Minority Leader Susan
Engeleiter. But GOP officials say she still can win, and an
appearance by President Reagan on her behalf has been promised
before the election.
   Engeleiter, 36, of Brookfield, would be the first woman
Wisconsin has sent to Congress. She also would be the younger than
any current member of the U.S. Senate.
   Whoever wins, the battle has ended a tradition of low-cost
campaigns that Proxmire established in his 31 years in Washington.
The retirement of Proxmire, who will turn 73 three days after the
election, also ends an era of statewide, personal campaigning that
spurned the use of paid advertising.
   Proxmire, chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, often
focused on issues of what he saw as government waste during his
long political career.
   Kohl, 53, of Milwaukee, already has set a record for election
spending in Wisconsin, contributing $3.84 million of his own money
to his first try at public office. His campaign had raised $4.28
million in all through Sept. 30.
   Engeleiter had raised $1.33 million.
   Proxmire reported spending just $145.10 to win re-election in
1982, down from $177.25 in 1976.
   Kohl's personal wealth and his many personal business dealings
have become an issue in the campaign.
   He had an income of $4.2 million last year, according to his
accountant. Engeleiter and her husband, Gerald, reported an income
of $130,000.
   Kohl's Democratic primary election opponents tried to persuade
voters he was buying the election. And Engeleiter has portrayed
herself as a middle-class candidate in the state's political
mainstream, a ``Wisconsin original.''
   But Engeleiter's family income is above average for Wisconsin
and Kohl lives relatively simply, eating breakfast most mornings at
a working-class diner in his Milwaukee neighborhood.
   He has refused political action committee donations and
campaigned on the theme ``Nobody's senator but yours.''
   In one well-publicized campaign controversy, Engeleiter said
Kohl owned a controlling interest in a San Antonio, Texas, bakery
that did most of its business with the Defense Department.
   Kohl said he began selling Sterling Bakery Inc. when he decided
to run for the Senate, and completed the sale in September.
   The issue backfired on Engeleiter when she hinted Kohl had
overcharged the Pentagon for coffee cake. Kohl showed the price per
pound was lower than the charges for a similar cake at the
supermarket that bears his family name.
   He is the former owner of a chain of supermarkets and department
stores. In 1985, after he sold the stores, he spent $18.5 million
to acquire the Milwaukee Bucks professional basketball team.
   Engeleiter contends Kohl should make more complete financial
disclosure, but interviews and polls indicate the issue has had
little effect on voters.
   ``There are basic issues beneath the surface, but the dynamics
seem to be personal,'' said University of Wisconsin history
professor Margaret Bogue.
   State Historian William F. Thompson suggests that voters seem to
be turned off this election, another departure from the past.
   ``Wisconsin traditionally has taken politics seriously, as
opposed to cynically,'' Thompson said.
   Kohl led Engeleiter 57 percent to 34 percent among likely voters
surveyed Oct. 6 and Oct. 7 by the Milwaukee Journal, but Republican
strategists still contend Engeleiter could prevail.
   ``This is a very winnable race,'' said Sen. Alan Simpson,
R-Wyo., who came to Wisconsin to campaign for Engeleiter last week.
   Still, Kohl's forces seem comfortable with their lead, and other
Democrats are counting on Kohl's coattails to help retain their
majorities in the Legislature.
   Engeleiter tends to support the national Republican ticket and
party platform on defense and budget issues but is more liberal on
social issues. She supports a woman's right to choose abortion,
while the GOP platform opposes abortion.
   Kohl has called for sharp cuts in defense spending, but supports
continued research, although not deployment, of the Strategic
Defense Initiative, known as ``Star Wars.'' He favors increased
spending for social programs, including education.
   Past holders of the Senate seat are a varied lot, including Sen.
Joseph R. McCarthy, censured by colleagues in the 1950s, and Sens.
Robert M. La Follette, father and son, both of whom clashed with
the Republican establishment and played prominent roles in the
Progressive movement.
</TEXT>
