<1ST_LINE>r p AM-GayRights     10-25 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gay Rights,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bitter Battle Over Gay Rights Measure in Colorado City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT COLLINS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed amendment to the city
charter that would ban discrimination against homosexuals has
pitted conservative clergymen against a coalition of advocates for
civil liberties and gay rights.
   The proposal on the Nov. 8 ballot would prohibit discrimination
in jobs, housing or public accommodations because of sexual
orientation.
   ``We believe discrimination is fundamentally wrong. It goes
against the health and well-being of our entire community,'' the
Coalition for Civil Rights, a proponent of the amendment, said in a
statement.
   Opponents argue that anti-discrimination laws should not apply
to homosexuality because it is a chosen lifestyle. Others have
called homosexuality a ``perversion'' and have prominently
mentioned acquired immune deficiency syndrome, for which sexually
active gay men are at high risk.
   One minister who opposes the measure has threatened to go on
radio and television if the amendment is approved and declare that
the northern Colorado city is the place for homosexuals to be.
   The Rev. Pete Peters said his congregation, the LaPorte Church
of Christ, has pledged to spend $4,000 to defeat the amendment.
Last week, he began criticizing the proposal in a series of paid,
two-hour radio broadcasts on a local station that prompted a flurry
of angry calls from listeners. He also plans to buy time on a local
cable television.
   ``I'm going to go on my program and let the homosexuals around
the nation know that Fort Collins is the place to come to'' if the
amendment is passed, said Peters.
   Other clergymen, however, have spoken out in favor of the
proposal.
   Its supporters are conducting a low-key, door-to-door campaign
and have focused on collecting endorsements from groups such as the
Colorado Psychological Association, the American Public Health
Association and the National Organization for Women.
</TEXT>
