<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShuttleAstronauts     10-25 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle Astronauts,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Discovery Astronauts Give Thanks to Their Launch Team</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Discovery's astronauts returned to
the scene of last month's first post-Challenger shuttle launch
Tuesday to thank space workers and praise them as the ``heartbeat of
America's space program.''
   ``What made the vehicle lift off the launch pad was not the solid
fuel booster rockets or the main engines; what was pushing us was
all your good feelings and the work and dedication and care you put
into it,'' astronaut George D. Nelson told a crowd of several
thousand people assembled in a parking lot near the launch control
center.
   ``If there's a heartbeat of America's space program, it's here at
the Kennedy Space Center,'' said Discovery pilot Richard O. Covey.
``We congratulate you for the role you played in helping us pull off
this very successful mission.''
   Frederick H. Hauck, Discovery's commander, presented the workers
with an autograph book which he and his crew carried into orbit. It
contains the signatures of more than 15,000 technicians, engineers,
managers, clerical and other space center staffers who signed it
before launch.
   In accepting the book, center director Forrest S. McCartney said
it would be displayed prominently and ``become part of the Kennedy
Space Center's history.''
   Hauck also presented McCartney with a picture montage that
included shuttle launchings and a photograph of the seven astronauts
killed when the Challenger exploded Jan. 28, 1986. McCartney
presented all five astronauts with a framed picture of Discovery's
liftoff.
   Looking ahead to the next flight, Nelson pointed to the huge
Vehicle Assembly Building across the street and noted that Atlantis
was in there being prepared for a late November liftoff, with a
five-man crew commanded by Robert ``Hoot'' Gibson.
   ``In this building behind me is Hoot's rocket,'' he said.
``Please get Hoot off the planet for awhile.'' And then he added,
``We ain't seen nothing yet.''
   The ceremony was a continuation of celebrations for Hauck,
Nelson, Covey and the other crew members, David C. Hilmers and John
M. Lounge.
   Since their four-day flight ended Oct. 3, they have been honored
by President Reagan at the White House, visited Congress and were
feted at the Johnson Space Center in Houston, at the Marshall Space
Flight Center in Huntsville, Ala., and in a motorcade in Cocoa
Beach, the community south of the Kennedy Space Center.
</TEXT>
