<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Ribbon,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harrah's Reno Employees Suspended For Refusing to Wear Anti-Drug
Ribbon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several Harrah's Reno employees have been
suspended without pay for just saying no to management's order to
wear a ribbon at work proclaiming themselves ``drug free.''
   Ronald Jeffrey, general manager of the club, said five or six
employees were suspended Sunday and Monday, although some workers
claim the number is closer to a dozen.
   The suspensions came because the red ribbons saying ``The choice
for me, Drug Free!'' were made part of the resort's dress, and the
employees were out of uniform by refusing to wear the ribbons,
Jeffrey said Monday.
   But attorney David Houston, who represents four of the suspended
workers, said Harrah's Reno violated the employees' First Amendment
rights by forcing them to wear what amounts to a statement about
drugs.
   ``The issue is: When does the casino recognize the right of
expression of its own employees ... not to adopt the position of the
employer?'' Houston said.
   Houston said he was attempting to negotiate with the casino but
might file suit.
   Dennis Gallagher, general counsel for Harrah's Reno, said the
suspended employees will have to go through an internal grievance
proceeding to be reinstated.
   More than 50,000 ribbons were distributed to schools, government
agencies and businesses in Nevada by the Governor's Alliance for a
Drug Free Nevada in observance of National Drug Free America Week,
which began Sunday.
   The suspended employees, who did not want to be named for fear of
recrimination, said they did not refuse to wear the ribbons because
they use illegal drugs. Instead, many said they consume alcoholic
drinks and coffee and smoke cigarettes so it would have been
hypocritical to say they were drug free.
   Harrah's Reno made the ribbon wearing voluntary Monday afternoon
after officials said they ran out of ribbons.
</TEXT>
