<HEAD>Plane Lands On Interstate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VERONA, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A single-engine airplane that developed engine
trouble shortly after takeoff made a safe landing Tuesday on
Interstate 71. No one was hurt.
   Only pilot Steve Rogers, 34, of Vienna, Va., was aboard the
two-seater Cessna 180. He had taken off from Lunken Airport in
Cincinnati and was on his way to Carrollton when the engine quit
because of a possible fuel leak.
   ``I was pretty close to the expressway, and there wasn't a lot of
traffic so I landed on it'' at 9:29 a.m., he said.
   After touching down on southbound I-71 just north of the Verona
exit, Rogers steered the plane into the concrete turn-around in the
median.
   Boone County Police Sgt. John Johnson said fuel and a mechanic
would be brought to the plane. Barring a mechanical problem, the
plane will take off from the interstate after being checked and
refueled, he said.
   Rogers said he thinks the plane may have a leak because fuel was
spattered on the body. ``I should have had plenty of gas,'' he said.
