<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1315EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CDC--TeenSuicides     10-25 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CDC--Teen Suicides,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen Suicides In Cobb Focus Of CDC Study</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The suicides of 14 Cobb County teen-agers in a
25-month period has triggered a study on teen suicide by the Centers
for Disease Control and the county health department.
   Dr. Virginia Mork, deputy director of the Cobb County Department
of Health, said the goal of the effort is to produce the first
detailed study of suicide based on interviews with those who survive
attempts to kill themselves.
   ``We've got this glaring problem of people killing themselves. We
want to know why,'' she said. ``Who are they? What are they like?
Are their parents middle-class? How old are they? If they are in
school, what school do they go to? What method do they choose?''
   The study, now encompassing 441 case studies of all ages,
indicates at least 900 people may attempt suicide in Cobb County
every year. The county, which borders northwest Atlanta, has about
300,000 residents.
   Fourteen adolescents 19 or younger killed themselves in Cobb
County from September 1986 to October 1988. The county's suicide
rate _ 14.7 deaths for every 100,000 people _ is almost three deaths
higher than the state average and almost two higher than the
national average.
   Dr. Patrick O'Carroll of the Atlanta-based CDC said the Cobb
study may offer insights into the rising number of suicides.
   Researchers eventually want to study 1,000 cases. Interviews with
441 patients between October 1987 and October 1988 show:
   _Only 38 of the 441 who attempted suicide took precautions to
avoid rescue, a much smaller proportion than those who succeed in
committing suicide.
   _More than 240 of the 441 took drug overdoses, while few who
succeed in committing suicide take drugs. Most use guns or hang
themselves.
   _More than 60 percent were women, but women constituted only
one-third of those who succeed.
   _About 254 of the 441 expressed an intent to commit suicide,
either in a note or conversation.
   According to the National Center for Health Statistics, suicide
rates are climbing for teens and adults. The overall national rate
has risen from 11.9 suicides for every 100,000 people in 1980 to
12.8 in 1986. The death toll has risen from 26,869 to 30,904 during
the same six-year period.
</TEXT>
