<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Baltics     10-25 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baltics,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Recommends Patience Toward Baltic Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mauno Koivisto urged patience
for those seeking speedy reforms in the Baltic states of the Soviet
Union, newspapers reported Tuesday.
   Koivisto, speaking to reporters Monday night, refrained from
clearly supporting Baltic groups which have demanded economic
freedom from Moscow, a revival of local languages and cultures, and
a halt to immigration by ethnic Russians.
   ``What qualifications have we, who are warm and on dry land, to
advise others what they should do? It is best to exercise
patience,'' Koivisto was quoted as saying by the Ilta Sanomat daily.
   Koivisto, in an earlier television interview, was even more
cautious about developments in the Baltic republic of Estonia across
the Gulf of Finland.
   ``Finland has an official foreign policy concerning states, not
popular fronts or civic groups,'' he said.
   He denied any need for a Finnish consulate in Estonia.
Neighboring Sweden reportedly has been considering opening an
Estonian consulate.
   Finland traditionally has close but wary ties with the Soviet
Union, which occupied parts of Finland during World War II.
   But the Finns also have an affinity for Estonia, which is 50
miles across the gulf and has a similar in language. Finnish
television is viewed by many Estonians.
   Koivisto's TV interview was his first since being re-elected to a
second six-year term in February.
</TEXT>
