<HEAD>Man Drives Bus Into Theater Showing Scorsese's Controversial Film</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A driver rammed a cross-country bus today
into a theater showing ``The Last Temptation of Christ,'' then asked
police to arrest him.
   The theater was empty and no one was injured, police said.
   Stanley Watin, 49, of Etna, was treated for chest injuries at a
hospital and later arraigned on a charge of second-degree criminal
mischief, said Ithaca Police Sgt. David Barnes. Bail was set at
$15,000.
   Barnes said the damage to Fall Creek Pictures was estensive.
   ``He got into his bus, drove into the thing (theater), flagged
down a patrol car in the neighborhood and said he wanted to be
arrested,'' said Tsvi Bokaer, the theater's owner and manager.
   Watin's bus is ``styled similar to a Greyhound'' bus, according
to Barnes, who said he had not seen the vehicle and did not know why
Watin owned it.
   Barnes said Watin told police he was upset about the film, which
has ignited protests from some Christians because Jesus is presented
as a human struggling to overcome the temptation to forsake his
destiny as Christ.
