<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Spence     10-25 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spence,0735</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Doing Well Five Months After Lung Transplant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year after Rep. Floyd Spence nearly died
of breathing problems, a rare transplant has given him new lungs and
a renewed shot for a 10th term in Congress.
   Five months after he underwent the double-lung transplant,
however, Spence's health remains a central issue in his re-election
campaign.
   The 60-year-old Lexington Republican faces a challenge from
Columbia banker Jim Leventis and has recently begun to step up his
campaigning.
   Spence's surgeon and colleagues say the congressman has made a
strong recovery from the sometimes-fatal operation.
   For six months, while he waited for a lung transplant after being
diagnosed with chronic obstructive lung disease, Spence moved about
in a wheelchair aided by portable oxygen. Others worried about his
future.
   ``Before his operation, he was having trouble breathing,'' said
Chuck Fant, spokesman for Rep. John Spratt, D-S.C., who serves with
Spence on the Armed Services Committee. ``It was pretty obvious he
was having trouble speaking. He was wheezing and coughing a lot and
he looked bad.''
   In May, the wait ended, and doctors at the University of
Mississippi Medical Center successfully transplanted the lungs of an
18-year-old Texas motorcycle accident victim into Spence.
   Spence spent the next few months learning to walk and to hold his
head erect again, before being released July 15.
   His surgeon, Dr. Seshadri Raju of the University of Mississippi,
said Spence has successfully passed the dangerous three months
immediately after surgery and should now be OK.
   ``Right now he is brand new. Right now I think he has the outlook
of any 60-year-old who is healthy,'' Raju said.
   The Mississippi hospital where Spence received his new lungs had
performed only three double-lung transplants before Spence. Two of
the three patients have died.
   Since Spence, two more have had the operation, one of whom died,
and the other remains hospitalized, spokeswoman Janis Quinn said.
   Spence said he feels fine, although he admitted to some tiredness
and swelling in his ankles that at times inhibits walking. The
swelling is a side-effect of the anti-rejection medicine he takes.
   But he said he maintains a 12-hour work day, uses weights for
strength in his upper body and tries to walk the quarter-mile from
his office to the Capitol to increase his fitness.
   ``It's just amazing that I have accommodated myself _ my body has
_ to these new lungs like it has,'' he said. ``Of course, I've got
some tightness in my chest because I've got wire in it and
everything else,'' he said.
   Since Spence returned to Congress Sept. 14, those familiar with
him say they've seen a dramatic change.
   ``I don't think there's any problem about his health at all,''
said U.S. Rep. Charles Bennett, D-Florida, who chairs a House Armed
Services Subcommittee on which Spence is the ranking Republican.
``There are lots of people in Congress weaker than he.''
   But, indirectly, Leventis has raised the issue of Spence's
ability to perform his duties.
   Earlier this month, Leventis released a letter in which Spence's
former doctor urged the congressman to answer Leventis' call for a
debate.
   A Spence spokesman accused Dr. Robert K. Moxon of playing ``fast
and loose with the Hippocratic oath,'' but Moxon denied any
impropriety.
   ``His health has been a public issue and it sounds like they're
hiding behind it,'' he said.
   A poll of 515 district voters conducted by The State newspaper of
Columbia recently found only 30 percent thought health should be an
issue in the campaign. The poll was conducted Oct. 10-12 and
contained a 4.3 percent margin of error.
   That same poll found voters preferring Spence 52 percent to 42
percent over Leventis.
   Leventis has never directly said Spence is unable to represent
the district. He said health should never be a standard by which
public officials are elected.
   ``That's for him to judge,'' Leventis said of Spence. ``He says
he's fine and I accept that.''
   Spence, though, has accused Leventis of less than honorable
intentions in entering the race, which Leventis denies.
   ``I'm sure this one thought I was dead or going to die,'' he said
after the transplant. ``But I was still wiggling out there.''
</TEXT>
