<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeenMother     10-25 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teen Mother,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen Sentenced to Lifetime Birth Control Not Allowed on National
TV</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who sentenced a teen-age mother to
lifetime birth control for neglect of her two young children has
denied her permission to travel to New York to appear on television.
   Maricopa County Superior Court Judge Lindsay Ellis Budzyn ruled
Monday that letting Debra Ann Forster, 18, go to New York next month
to appear on the Phil Donahue talk show ``would be like throwing her
into the mouths of sharks.
   ``She is not ready for it. It could hurt her and it would not be
in her best interest. She's making the kinds of rehabilitatives
strides than an interruption, with this kind of media coverage,
could disrupt.''
   The judge also was invited to appear on the Donahue show but
declined.
   Ms. Forster was sentenced in May to lifetime probation for
leaving her two small sons alone for nearly three days without food
or water in a hot Mesa apartment.
   As a condition of her probation, Ms. Forster was ordered to
remain on birth control for the remainder of her child-bearing years
and was prohibited from leaving Arizona without court approval.
   The birth control restriction was lifted as unenforceable in
August when Ms. Budzyn learned that Ms. Forster was pregnant again.
   Ms. Forster's attorney, Garrett Simpson, had asked the judge to
permit the woman to go to New York, arguing that her appearance on
the show ``would serve the public interest, would serve
rehabilitation and will enhance the reputation of the bench.''
   The judge, in refusing the request, noted that she has carefully
monitored Ms. Forster's activities and that the woman is receiving
pre-natal care, intensive counseling, is studying for her high
school diploma, is learning to cook and is staying drug-free.
   Ms. Forster was pregnant in May 1987 when she left her sons, then
7 months old and 18 months old, in her Mesa apartment. When the
boys' father found them, they were severely dehydrated and one was
near death, according to court testimony.
   The boys were taken into custody of Child Protective Services and
their mother has been barred from seeing them again.
   A daughter born while Ms. Forster was in jail awaiting resolution
of her case was immediately put up for adoption.
   Ms. Forster, who has reconciled with her husband, said that the
baby she now carries ``is the most important thing in her life,''
the judge said.
   ``She said this is the first time in her life that she has people
who care for her,'' Ms. Budzyn said. ``I felt pretty good after
talking with her.''
</TEXT>
