<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Peru-PlaneCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0602 10-25 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peru-Plane Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0602,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Peruvian Plane Crashes in Andes; One Dead, 25 Injured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with reports of injuries, details</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Peruvian state-owned airliner carrying about
50 passengers crashed today high in the Andes, killing at least one
person and injuring at least 25, officials said.
   But a pilots' association spokesman in Lima said four people were
killed.
   Victor Urbiola, prefect of Puno state, said Aeroperu's flight 772
from Juliaca, near the Bolivian border, to Arequipa, Peru's second
largest city, crashed about 10:45 a.m.
   Urbiola, whose position is equivalent to a governor in the United
States, said the plane went down about a mile from the airport
shortly after takeoff.
   Juliaca police said one person was killed and at least 25 people
were injured, many of them seriously.
   But a spokesman for the Association of Pilots of Aeroperu said
four people were killed. He spoke on condition of anonymity and
would not elaborate.
   Freddy Chirinos, press spokesman for Aeroperu, said the
Dutch-made Fokker aircraft has a capacity for 60 passengers but
``there were only about 50'' aboard the plane. He said he had no
information on identities or nationalities of the passengers.
   Chirinos an Aeroperu plane carrying company officials and
government investigators had left for Juliaca to determine the cause
of the crash.
   A spokesman for the Arequipa airport told The Associated Press
that the plane crashed on a broad pasture more than two miles above
sea level.
   Juliaca is located in Puno state, 540 miles southeast of Lima.
   The flight from Juliaca often carries foreign tourists from Lake
Titicaca, on the border with Bolivia.
</TEXT>
