<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Soviet     10-25 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviet Officials To Meet On Cambodia, Asia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top U.S. and Soviet officials will meet in
Paris next week on efforts to reach a settlement in Cambodia as well
as other topics of mutual concern in East Asia and the Pacific, the
State Department said Tuesday.
   Assistant Secretary of State Gaston Sigur will confer with Soviet
Deputy Foreign Minister Igor Rogachev on Nov. 2 and 3 as part of
periodic superpower talks on regional issues, said spokesman Charles
Redman.
   ``The Cambodia issue is one of the most important'' on the
agenda, although not the only one, he added. Other topics are
expected to include the recent rapprochement between North and South
Korea.
   Before seeing Rogachev, Sigur will meet in Paris on Nov. 1 with
exiled Cambodian leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk. That session comes
one week before Sihanouk's scheduled meeting with Cambodia's Prime
Minister Hun Sen, who was installed by Vietnamese forces that occupy
his country.
   Sihanouk and Hun Sen are expected to discuss attempts to form a
coalition government composed of three opposition groups and
representatives of the government set up in Phnom Penh by Vietnam 10
years ago.
   Both the United States and the Soviet Union back such an
arrangement.
   Rogachev held talks in August with Chinese officials in Beijing
on the Cambodian question, which is one of the few remaining
obstacles to normalizing relations between Moscow and Beijing.
   China wants the Soviet Union to pressure its Vietnamese ally to
withdraw from Cambodia as soon as possible. Vietnam has agreed to
pull out all its forces by 1990.
</TEXT>
