<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1443EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     10-25 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Curfew Ends; 4 Killed In Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police firing tear gas charged
thousands of protesters in three anti-government demonstrations
Tuesday, a day after a bomb attack killed eight people at a
governing party meeting.
   Police initially blamed Sinhalese extremists for the Monday
evening bombing in Colombo, but party officials did not rule out
that opposing political parties were behind the explosion.
   Military officials suspected Sinhalese extremists in the killings
of four people Monday night and Tuesday.
   No casualties were reported in Tuesday's demonstrations in
central and south Sri Lanka.
   The government placed an 18-hour curfew on the capital after
reports the People's Liberation Front, a radical Sinhalese group,
was planning a daylong strike. The government said it feared a
strike would lead to more violence.
   The curfew lapsed late Tuesday, and police guarded intersections
as thousands of residents went out to buy provisions.
   Violence in Sri Lanka has escalated with the approach of
presidential elections scheduled for Dec. 19.
   The People's Liberation Front opposes the government's peace
overtures to minority Tamils fighting for an independent homeland on
the north and east of the island.
   The front has been blamed for more than 500 killings since India
and Sri Lanka signed a July 1987 peace accord aimed at ending the
5-year-old Tamil separatist war. Many have been politicians with the
United National Party, also predominantly Sinhalese.
   In central Welimada province, about 70 miles east of Colombo,
police fired tear gas and charged with batons into an estimated
5,000 anti-government demonstrators.
   The demonstrators sat on public highways and refused to move,
officials said. Police were unable to disperse them, officials said.
State-run television said there were no casulties.
   In the town of Medawachchiya, about 90 miles northeast of
Colombo, police were called to disperse 3,000 protesters, including
many Buddhist monks and schoolchildren, who were demanding the
government's resignation.
   In the southern Uva Paranagama province similar demonstrations
were held, but details were not immediately available.
   Police said three people were killed in the town of Welimada late
Monday by suspected members of the front. In Kandy, Sinhalese gunmen
killed a postmaster Tuesday, police said.
   Police in Colombo said the death toll in the bombing Monday rose
to eight after three more people died of their wounds Tuesday. At
least 40 others were injured, they added.
   Sinhalese extremists say the peace accord grants too many
concessions to the Tamils, who form 18 percent of the country's 16
million people.
   Sinhalese make up 75 percent of the population.
   The front has put up posters in Colombo and others parts of Sri
Lanka demanding President Junius R. Jayewardene's resignation, the
rejection of the peace accord and the withdrawal of 47,000 Indian
troops in Sri Lanka to quell the Tamil rebellion.
   The Tamils claim they were discriminated against by the
Sinhalese, who control Sri Lanka's military and government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
