<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--TylenolSuit     10-25 0138</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Tylenol Suit,0139</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Rejects Widow's $6.5 Billion Suit Against Tylenol</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Billion cq in lead</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal court jury has rejected a $6.5
billion lawsuit filed by a widow who claimed her husband died of
liver damage from taking two Tylenol products at the same time.
   ``We're gratified at the jury's verdict,'' said Robert E.
Christiansen, an attorney for Johnson & Johnson, the parent company
of McNeil Consumer Products Co., which makes Tylenol.
   The U.S. District Court jury deliberated about an hour Monday
before rejecting the negligence suit filed by Silvia Jauchler, whose
husband Maurice died last year. She said labels should warn people
against taking the maximum dose of two different acetaminophen
products at the same time.
   ``We didn't cause this man's problem. We're grateful the jury
believed us,'' Christiansen said.
</TEXT>
