<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     10-25 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Urges Prosecution Of Former President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Kim Dae-jung on
Tuesday urged President Roh Tae-woo to accelerate reforms and
recover fortunes allegedly amassed by a former leader.
   Kim, who addressed the National Assembly as head of South Korea's
main opposition party, also proposed changes in relations with the
United States that would give South Korea more independence and
check anti-U.S. sentiment.
   The leader of the Party for Peace and Democracy said the time had
come ``to open sincere discussions about the strict enforcement of
jurisdiction over U.S. troops, nuclear weapons and the transfer of
U.S. commandership over South Korean troops.''
   Under treaties signed during the 1950-53 Korean War, South Korea
has no jurisdiction over U.S. soldiers stationed in the country.
   At the Hankook University of Foreign Studies, about 100 students
armed with firebombs and rocks battled riot police on Tuesday,
demanding the withdrawl of about 42,000 U.S. troops stationed in
South Korea.
   Also on Tuesday, about 40 students staged a peaceful anti-U.S.
protest in front of the U.S. Embassy.
   A majority of South Koreans support the presence of U.S. troops,
but dissidents contend the United States has hampered reunification
of the divided peninsula.
   Kim attributed the growing anti-Americanism to nationalism
brought by rapid political and economic changes, as well as the
country's pride as the host of the Olympics.
   The opposition leader urged Roh to take a courageous stand
against former President Chun Doo-hwan, whom opponents accuse of
amassing wealth through corruption.
   During a parliamentary investigation of state affairs that began
Oct. 5, opposition lawmakers found evidence of widespread
corruption, irregularities and violation of human rights by Chun and
his followers.
   Kim charged Chun and his family with amassing hundreds of
millions of dollars during his seven years in office and demanded
the money be returned to help the poor.
   Kim also called for an end to alleged wiretapping, torture and
political surveillance of students and dissidents by police and
other security organs.
   Roh, a former general who succeeded Chun in February, is gaining
popularity with his proposed reforms and efforts to improve
relations with East bloc nations, some of whom have exchanged trade
offices with South Korea.
   Dissidents and radical students have vowed to launch a nationwide
campaign next week to press for the arrest of Chun and his family.
</TEXT>
