<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle     10-25 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle,510,</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Defends Bush, Says Democrats Dish ``Sludge''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STONE MOUNTAIN, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle on Tuesday defended
GOP presidential nominee George Bush's campaign against charges of
distortion and lying, and he said the Democrats were the ones
dishing ``political sludge.''
   His remarks on a campaign swing through Georgia came about a week
after Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis called GOP
campaign literature ``political garbage.''
   Quayle said George Bush was a 25-year public servant who ``has
built a career resting on unshakable integrity and fairness.''
   ``The personal attacks now being made on him by a desperate
opponent are outrageous,'' Quayle said in a luncheon address to a
Rotary Club in Stone Mountain.
   ``The political sludge that is being dished out by Mr. Dukakis'
surrogates and which I believe the governor is actively encouraging
is despicable,'' Quayle said.
   He also accused Dukakis of shifts of position that ``tell us
something about how steady that candidate would be if elected.''
   Quayle listed issues on which the Republicans have attacked
Dukakis _ tax increases in Massachusetts, borrowing from that
state's pension fund, pollution of Boston Harbor, gun control, and
Dukakis' defense positions _ and rejected Dukakis' complaint that
his positions have been distorted.
   After Stone Mountain event, Quayle flew to Augusta, Ga., and was
to campaign Wednesday in Tampa, Miami and Fort Lauderdale in Florida.
   The foray into Florida, a state considered safely in Bush's hands
in the general election, was geared to help Rep. Connie Mack in his
GOP Senate race against Rep. Buddy McKay, GOP advisers said.
   One of the advisers brought in to oversee Quayle's campaign,
Mitch Daniels, said the strategy from now until the election is for
Quayle to keep a low profile nationally while hitting regionally
significant areas.
   Quayle, who has generally steered clear of major cities, will
continue making campaign appearances in rural or suburban
communities where the visit of a candidate is a big deal, Daniels
said.
   ``He's very effective in midsize and smaller communities,''
Daniels said, adding that if Quayle can make an impact on 5,000 to
10,000 votes at a given appearance, with ``a few days in a row of
that you can swing a state like Ohio.''
   Marilyn Quayle, according to her husband, phoned to tell him,
``You must be making great speeches, drawing tremendous crowds,
really getting them on their feet and saying all the right things
... because I haven't heard one thing about you this week.'
   That, said Quayle, is the ``typical role of the vice presidential
candidate and we're glad to fill that role.''
   The senator has seemed to settle into a pattern of ease in his
campaign that contrasts with the restrained style he showed early on.
   Quayle and his advisers say that his selection by Bush eventually
will be seen as having little impact on the outcome of the election.
   There are some voters who have a negative reaction to him and
feel he is not qualified, but other voters may be drawn by his youth
and conservatism, Daniels said.
</TEXT>
