<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Mozambique-SAfrica     10-25 0142</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Mozambique-SAfrica,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South African Officials Honor White Pioneer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa's foreign minister, Pik
Botha, and other officials attended a memorial service Tuesday for a
white pioneer who died here 150 years ago.
   Botha spoke at a monument in Maputo honoring Louis Trichardt, one
of the leaders of the ``Great Trek'' by ethnic Dutch South Africans
who sought new land in the 1830s to escape British domination.
   Most set up communities in South Africa, but Trichardt and 52
others continued into what is now Mozambique, where he died of
malaria in 1838.
   The monument was built in the 1960s when Mozambique was a
Portuguese colony.
   Botha described Trichardt as ``our first diplomat,'' saying he
maintained good relations with African tribal chiefs.
   ``We can find peaceful solutions to our problems, concentrating
on matters that bind us together,'' Botha said.
</TEXT>
