<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0619 10-25 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0619,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Civilians Wounded In Car Bomb Explosion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with 10 Syrians injured; picks
up
5th graf pvs, ``The injured ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A remote-controlled car bomb exploded
Tuesday in the in the Bekaa Valley as a Syrian armored personnel
carrier was passing, injuring 10 Syrian soldiers and five Lebanese
civilians, police said.
   No one claimed responsibility for the 1:30 p.m. blast outside a
grocery store in the Syrian-policed town of Barr Elias, the 16th car
bombing in Lebanon this year.
   The car was packed with 88 pounds of explosives when it blew up
in the town about 30 miles southeast of Beirut, said a police
spokesman reached by telephone in Zahle, provincial capital of the
Bekaa.
   ``It was detonated by remote control as the (Syrian vehicle) was
rolling past the grocery. But it seems the vehicle and its occupants
escaped unharmed,'' said the spokesman, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Initial reports only mentioned the civilian casualties, but a
police statement later reported the 10 Syrians wounded.
   The injured were taken by ambulances to a Zahle hospital.
   The Voice of the Nation radio station said Syrian troops cordoned
off Barr Elias for an hour after the blast.
   The town has a predominantly Sunni Moslem population of 30,000.
   Syria maintains an estimated 40,000 soldiers in the eastern and
northern provinces as well as Moslem west Beirut.
   The force is supported by Lebanon's Moslems and leftists, and
violently opposed by right-wing Christians who regard the Syrians an
occupying power.
   By police count, 104 people were killed and 378 wounded in 15
previous car bombings in Lebanon since April 23.
</TEXT>
