<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     10-25 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black cat has turned up 10 miles from home nearly
three years after it disappeared.
   ``It's like he has been resurrected,'' Eleanor Kilgore said
Monday. ``This is one cat that really has nine lives, I guess.''
   A telephone call from a woman across town Sunday afternoon sent
Ms. Kilgore racing over to see if the animal wearing her cat's worn
leather collar and metal identification tag was really her lost cat,
Winston.
   ``I hopped in the car, with tears streaming down my face,'' Ms.
Kilgore said.
   The woman who found the cat said Winston emitted a meow of relief
as Ms. Kilgore picked him up for the first time since Feb. 16, 1986.
   ``I think he was as surprised and happy to see me as I was to see
him,'' Ms. Kilgore said.
   She said Winston looks no worse for wear and still weighs about
14 pounds and has a shiny, bushy coat, but he has a few white hairs.
   Sandy Odean said she and her family had been feeding the black
cat since they moved into their home in July. She had not been able
until Sunday to get close enough to the skittish cat to read its tag.
   Ms. Odean said she called Ms. Kilgore and asked, ``Do you own a
big black cat with yellow eyes?''
   It took a few seconds for the question to register, Ms. Kilgore
said.
   ``Then I realized it couldn't be anybody but Winston,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WEST LEBANON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 4-month-old colt was rescued from an
abandoned well with a rope, a tow-truck winch and the help of a
tranquilzing shot from a veterinarian.
   ``He has a little scratch on one of his back legs,'' Leslie
Ricketts said Tuesday. ``We pulled him out of there and he's doing
fine.''
   The young quarter horse leaped a fence Monday, walked on a tent
covering the 75-foot well, but broke his fall on some pipes 7 feet
into the shaft, said Ricketts, father of the colt's owner.
   ``He was in there approximately an hour before we started moving
him,'' said Deputy Don Hensley of the Warren County Sheriff's
Department. ``It took 15 minutes to get him out.''
   Ricketts said the 350-pound colt was up and around the next day,
but added, ``He's a little bit sore.''
   __
   FREMONT, Neb. (AP) _ Bill Lowther Jr. bowled a perfect game at
the Plaza Lanes and considers the bowling alley his ``second home,''
so he decided there was no better place to strike up a marriage.
   Dressed in a gray suit and white bowling shoes, Lowther tied the
wedding knot with Billie Mueller Saturday night in the middle of
lanes 11 and 12.
   ``This is what I do,'' said Lowther, 32, waving his hand about
the alley where he has bowled since the age of 5.
   ``I shot a 300 on 11 and 12 and that's where I'm going to get
married. I feel it's lucky,'' he said prior to the 5-minute ceremony.
   Ms. Mueller admitted the wedding spot was ``different _ something
unusual.''
   ``He bowled his 300 there. He got lucky that one time. We felt it
would be lucky for us,'' she said.
   About 50 people were on hand to watch the ceremony, including
Lowther's new mother-in-law, Charlene Schwanke of Ames.
   ``I'm just glad he isn't a sky diver,'' Mrs. Schwanke said.
</TEXT>
