<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--Reagan-Antietam     10-25 0109</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Reagan-Antietam,90</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs Battlefield Protection Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has signed legislation
designed to help protect the Antietam Civil War battlefield in
northern Maryland, the White House announced on Tuesday.
   The measure gives the government the authority to purchase lands
within the existing boundaries of the battlefield that have historic
or scenic value.
   The Antietam National Battlefield was established in Aug. 30,
1890, to commemorate the Sept. 17, 1862, confrontation that occurred
within an 8,000-acre area of Washington County, Md.
   Currently, the battlefield site consists of 3,246 acres. Prior to
the bill signing, the government was limited to acquiring 600 acres
within the battlefield's boundary.
</TEXT>
