<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1624EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BeringFishery     10-25 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bering Fishery,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Soviet Negotiators Call For Halt To Overfishing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top state department official said Tuesday he
was encouraged by the outcome of talks in Moscow last week in which
Soviet and U.S. officials recommended that ``immediate measures'' be
taken to halt overfishing for pollock in the Bering Sea.
   Ed Wolfe, the department's ambassador for oceans and fisheries
who led the U.S. delegation, also said that both countries are
``increasingly concerned'' about reports of possible illegal salmon
fishing by the Japanese and the Taiwanese in the North Pacific and
agreed to cooperate in enforcement activities.
   ``The Soviets are equally as concerned about possible illegal
salmon fishing as we are,'' Wolfe said in an interview. ``All of
these things are related because they all deal with Bering Sea
fishing.''
   Wolfe said he was ``quite satisfied'' with the Moscow talks and
he expected a plan for managing pollock stocks in the Bering Sea to
emerge from another round of talks either late this year or in early
1989.
   In a joint statement, negotiators meeting in Moscow said
scientists from both countries agreed that unregulated fishing was
``clearly detrimental'' to pollock stocks in U.S. and Soviet zones
that surround the international portion of the Bering Sea.
   ``In light of the urgent nature of this problem, the two
delegations agreed that ... immediate measures are necessary to
conserve fishery resources throughout the Bering Sea ecosystem,''
the statement said.
   The statement gave no indication what measures the two countries
might consider to halt the overfishing, but simply said, ``It is
essential that all countries fishing in the central Bering Sea meet
their obligations under international law to conserve these
threatened fishery resources.''
   Some State Department officials have said one possibility is for
the United States and Soviet Union to declare a moratorium on
fishing in the ``doughnut hole'' _ a 45,000-square-mile area of
international waters in the middle of the Bering Sea.
   Fishing vessels must pass through U.S. and Soviet waters to enter
the ``doughnut hole,'' one of the richest fishing grounds in the
world.
   Wolfe will be in Tokyo next week for talks with Japanese about
Bering Sea fishing.
   ``We need to see if we can turn things around,'' said Wolfe.
   Relations between Japan and the United States over fisheries
issues have deteriorated since January when seven Japanese trawlers
were videotaped fishing illegally in U.S. waters off Alaska.
   American fishermen say the annual catch of groundfish in the
``doughnut hole'' has grown from about 200,000 metric tons to more
than 1 million metric tons over the past four years.
   They also claim foreign trawlers use the ``doughnut hole'' as a
staging ground for illegal fishing forays into the 200-mile American
zone under cover of darkness or in bad weather.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
