<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile     10-25 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet Says He's Like Christ Spurned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Augusto Pinochet on Tuesday
compared his referendum defeat to the spurning of Christ, and an
opposition leader said he was ``abusing the people's patience'' by
refusing calls for democratic reform.
   In a speech to about 3,000 women volunteers, a solemn Pinochet
declared: ``We were defeated in a plebiscite, defeated but not
vanquished.''
   ``Don't forget that in world history there was a plebiscite in
which the people chose between Christ and Barabbas. And the people
chose Barabbas,'' the general said.
   ``The people sometimes make mistakes,'' Pinochet added. According
to the Bible, the Romans offered to set free either Christ or
Barabbas, a common criminal, just before their crucifixion. The
crowd chose Barabbas.
   The audience _ a private woman's organization headed by
Pinochet's wife, Lucia _ applauded loudly.
   On Oct. 5, voters rejected a proposal by the country's military
commanders that Pinochet, who seized power in a bloody 1973 coup,
remain president until 1997.
   As a result he was obliged to call an open election, planned for
December 1989, and hand power over to the winner in March 1990.
   ``We are going to keep working until the last day,'' Pinochet
vowed in his speech, ``and then hand over the government to whom you
yourselves elect.''
   Opposition groups have called for Pinochet to step down early,
and to agree to talks on reforming the 8-year-old constitution that
was drafted and pushed through by his administration. They maintain
that changes are needed to give future elected government full
democratic powers.
   Pinochet has vowed to keep the constitution intact, and Patricio
Aylwin, president of the centrist Christian Democratic Party, on
Tuesday accused the 72-year-old authoritarian ruler of trying to
provoke disorders by his intransigence.
   Aylwin said Pinochet want to ``push people into taking to the
streets, to create a pretext for unleashing violence and
repression.''
   ``He is abusing the people's patience,'' Aylwin said.
   Aylwin, a 69-year-old lawyer, is widely expected to be nominated
for president by a 16-party opposition coalition that led the
campaign for Pinochet's defeat in the referendum. His party is the
country's largest.
   The coalition has avoided calling street demonstrations or other
provocative actions, fearing they could lead to a harder government
line and hurt chances for talks on the reforms. But Aylwin said
opposition leaders, who have been calling for patience among the
ranks, ``will lose their credibility if things don't advance.''
   He said a Cabinet shakeup by Pinochet last week, in which a
U.S.-trained economist, Carlos Caceres, was named to head the
powerful Interior Ministry, did not reveal ``any readiness to
respond to the opposition parties' calls for a dialog.''
   Aylwin also complained the government had failed to heed appeals
for ``goodwill gestures'' such as the release of two labor leaders
in internal exile.
</TEXT>
