<2ND_LINE>AM-Gay Protest,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gay Activists Disrupt City Council Over Congressional Mandates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several gay rights advocates were dragged from
the District of Columbia Council chambers Tuesday after protesting a
bill that would allow insurance companies to require AIDS testing of
applicants for health insurance.
   ``Just say no to the rule changes,'' eight protesters chanted,
referring to congressional amendments attached to the city's $3.2
billion spending package for the fiscal year which began Oct. 1.
   ``You're not in the chamber of the legislature that caused the
problem,'' council chairman David Clarke said in appealing for
order. After the protesters refused to honor Clarke's request that
they allow the council session to continue, they were dragged from
the chamber by city police officers. None was arrested.
   ``It is the belief of many in the gay community that the German
people took a number of small steps back to Hell as Hitler came to
power,'' said Gerald Green, who organized the protest. ``We are here
to remind everyone that the council is now doing the same thing by
doing what Congress ordered.''
   Washington's gay community is upset over several amendments
attached to the city's spending bill by Congress.
   One amendment orders the city to change its human rights law to
allow Catholic universities to deny certain rights to homosexual
student groups, while another requires the city to allow insurance
companies to conduct tests for the AIDS virus on all persons seeking
insurance policies.
   In both cases, Congress would freeze all local funds and the $539
million in federal money the city receives in lieu of tax payments
on government-owned buildings if the amendments are not acted upon.
</TEXT>
