<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Noor cut the tape to open a new
Japanese-funded elementary and preparatory school at a Palestinian
refugee camp in Jordan Tuesday.
   The Japanese Embassy said the boys' school at the Jerash camp, 20
miles north of Amman, was financed with part of a $1 million grant
from the Japanese government.
   The money also will be used to build a girls' school. Each
three-story complex will have 18 classrooms for 1,600 students.
   Japan's $20 million annual contribution makes it second only to
the United States as a donor to the United Nations Relief and Works
Agency, which administers the refugee camps.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jimmy Smits, who plays Victor Sifuentes on ``L.A.
Law,'' says he doesn't want to be typecast as the kind of upwardly
mobile Hispanic he plays on the popular series.
   ``I'm not waving a role-model flag,'' the Brooklyn-born actor
said in an interview with GQ magazine, which profiled him in its
November issue. ``I want to think of myself as versatile.''
   Smits offered this view of his television character, a young
Hispanic lawyer: ``Victor is typical of so many Latinos in the
United States _ second or third-generation, educated, in the
professional mainstream. That's created a change, somewhat, in terms
of the way people view Hispanics in the media.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rolling Stones, the Temptations, Stevie
Wonder, Dion and Otis Redding have been elected to the Rock and Roll
Hall of Fame.
   This year, the Hall of Fame also will honor three early
influences on rock 'n' roll: the blues singer Bessie Smith, the
vocal quartet the Ink Spots and the gospel group the Soul Stirrers,
of which the late Sam Cooke _ himself an icon of soul music _ was
once a member.
   The Rolling Stones, the ``bad boys'' of the British rock
invasion, began by recording American blues and soul in the early
1960s before turning to original compositions by Mick Jagger and
Keith Richards.
   The Temptations, famous for ``My Girl,'' and Stevie Wonder, a
child star, both recorded for Motown Records.
   Dion was one of the leading talents to emerge from the New York
vocal harmony scene of the late '50s and Otis Redding, who was
inspired by Cooke, became one of the great singers to emerge from
the Stax-Volt Studio in Memphis in the early 1960s.
   The annoucement of the latest inductees to the rock industry's
honor roll was made this week by Atlantic Records' Ahmet Ertegun,
who is chairman of the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame Foundation.
Induction ceremonies are planned in New York for Jan. 18.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Ole Opry humorist Jerry Clower has
been chosen grand marshal for the Mardi Gras parade in New Orleans,
his manager said Tuesday.
   Clower, of Yazoo City, Miss., will lead the Jan. 21 Krewe of
Saturn parade consisting of 24 bands and 16 floats, manager Tandy
Rice said.
   ``You've got to give the Krewe of Saturn committee credit for
being adventurous, daring, courageous and bold to have the foresight
to select a teetotaler and lay Baptist minister to head up their
parade,'' he said.
   Clower, a lay leader of the Southern Baptist Convention, has
recorded 19 humor albums and written three books in addition to
making regular appearances on the Opry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He ate hamburgers with Marilyn Monroe and
stood up Ava Gardner and ``It Wasn't All Velvet,'' according to the
title of singer Mel Torme's just-out autobiography.
   Torme, known to earlier generations of jazz aficionados as the
Velvet Fog, is now enjoying a new audience he refers to as ``a gang
of yuppies'' who've learned about him through appearances on TV's
``Night Court.''
   On the musical scene he was pals with the likes of Benny Goodman,
Duke Ellington, Frank Sinatra, Judy Garland, Bing Crosby and others.
   ``We began to meet late at night,'' he wrote of Monroe, following
the actress' divorce in the 1950s from baseball great Joe DiMaggio.
``She loved Dolores' Drive-In for hamburgers. Several nights we sat
in my car, eating those tasty burgers and talking _ about
everything. ... We went to the movies. A few times we met at the
home of a friend. ... She told me she liked me because I made her
laugh.''
   Of his tiff with Gardner, he said when he asked the actress why
she was in a slinky black dress, she replied: ``I was at the studio
today, doing some stills for `The Hucksters' and I ran into Marilyn
Maxwell in the commissary.'' It was Maxwell, Torme had escorted to a
screening giving Gardner some other story.
   Miss Gardner smiled and said: ``We're through, Melvin. Finished.
Kaput. You lied to me and I won't take that from anyone. Out!'''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GLENDALE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housewife Micky Sadoff says she's ready for
the challenge that awaits her as new president of the 1.1
million-member Mothers Against Drunk Driving.
   Mrs. Sadoff, 44, founded the Milwaukee area's MADD chapter in
1982, the year after her husband, Ronald, nearly died from injuries
suffered when a drunken driver crashed into their car.
   She stepped down last year as head of MADD's southeastern
Wisconsin chapter, then was elected in Atlanta last week as
president of the national organization.
   For Mrs. Sadoff, who has had what she calls a ``24-hours-a-day,
7-days-a-week commitment'' as a volunteer, the post is her first
full-time paying job, with an annual salary of $48,000.
   ``My children are grown,'' she said Monday. ``Now it's my turn.''
   Mrs. Sadoff said she plans to push on with efforts she began in
the voluntary post of MADD's vice president for victims' issues.
   ``And the victims, after all, are why we're doing this.''
</TEXT>
