<1ST_LINE>u w AM-HomeSales     10-25 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Home Sales,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Existing-Home Sales Down 2.2 Percent in September</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY25</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite a housing boom in California, sales of
existing homes fell 2.2 percent in September after a surprisingly
strong summer, a real estate trade group said Tuesday.
   The National Association of Realtors said sales of existing homes
declined to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.63 million units
last month, following a 2.2 percent increase in August.
   But last month's level was still higher than most economists
would have predicted this spring, when mortgage interest rates began
to creep higher.
   Fixed-rate mortgages on average hit a low of 9.84 percent in
February and rose to 10.71 percent by early August. Since then, they
have eased back to 10.28 percent, but many analysts expect them to
start rising again by year's end.
   Existing-home sales in the late spring and early summer were
strong, in part because many buyers apparently purchased homes
sooner than planned in an attempt to beat rising interest rates.
   ``The decline ... in September is a hangover from the buying
spree of the summer,'' said John A. Tuccillo, chief economist of the
Realtors. ``The extraordinary increase'' of the summer was ``in part
borrowed from September.''
   Tuccillo predicted sales rates will continue to lag in the fourth
quarter and by year's end would total 3.47 million units, down only
slightly from 3.53 million in 1987.
   The West was the only region of the nation showing an increase of
sales last month. They rose 6.0 percent to an annual rate of 710,000
units, the highest level since December 1986, following a 3.1
percent increase in August.
   Sales fell 5.8 percent in the Northeast to 650,000 units on an
annual basis, the lowest since January. They fell 3.2 percent in the
Midwest to 900,000 units and were off 2.8 percent in the South to
1.38 million units.
   John Savacool, an economist with The Wefa Group, a forecasting
firm in Bala Cynwyd, Pa., said California's strong economy and
growing population are supporting the housing market.
   ``People have been moving into California in droves, and that
provides a lot of support for the housing market there even though
the rest of the nation looks weak,'' Savacool said. He noted that
400,000 people moved to California last year, more than to any other
state.
   The main reason for sluggish sales in the Northeast is high
prices, he said.
   Over the past year, existing-home prices have risen most steeply
in the West. The median was $124,300 in September, up 7.1 percent.
   However, the Northeast remained the most costly area with a
median of $141,400, up 6.3 percent from a year earlier.
   The median in the South was $82,400, up 3.6 percent from
September 1987. In the Midwest, the price was $67,100, up 1.5
percent. The national appreciation rate over 12 months was 3.5
percent to a median of $88,500, meaning half of the homes sold for
more and half for less.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
