<DOCNO> AP881025-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1626EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HeartDrugs     10-25 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heart Drugs,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>47 New Heart Drugs In Works</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pharmaceutical Manufacturers Association
said Tuesday that 47 of its members companies are working on a total
of 87 new drugs for cardiovascular diseases, including heart
disease, hypertension and stroke.
   ``No other disease is targeted by so many drugs in development or
so much investment in research,'' said association president Gerald
J. Mossinghoff.
   Each of the 87 drugs is either in human clinical trials or
awaiting final approval by the Food and Drug Administration.
   He acknowledged at a news conference that one of the reasons the
companies are pouring so much investment into cardiovascular
diseases is that there remains a huge market for such therapies even
though doctors now realize they are among the most preventable
illnesses for people who adopt healthy lifestyles in their early and
middle years.
   Dr. John F. Beary III, senior vice president for science and
technology for the trade association, noted that heart disease
remains the nation's No. 1 killer and stroke No. 3.
   Even though the population is generally healthier, as well as
older, than in years past, Beary said, ``At some point these
diseases catch up with everyone.''
   The PMA survey of its more than 100 members was designed to
provide an overview of the scope of new drug development in various
categories, rather than highlight any particularly promising
``breakthrough'' drugs.
   In fact, there are already a number of drugs on the market for
cardiovascular diseases _ unlike for many other diseases that
afflict mostly the elderly, such as Alzheimer's.
   Mossinghoff acknowledged that ``a subliminal purpose (for the
press conference) is to let elder Americans know that it is
important for the FDA to have adequate funding'' to review these new
drugs.
   ``This puts a little bit of pressure on the system,'' he said.
   Mossinghoff said it is likely some of the companies developing
new cardiovascular disease drugs will take advantage of new FDA
guidelines announced last week that holds out the prospect of
quicker approval of new drugs if companies work closely with the
agency in early clinical trials and make a larger research
investment to accumulate more test data earlier than is often the
current practice.
   The trade association plans similar surveys in December for
cancer drugs under development and in January for arthritis,
Alzheimer's and other aging diseases.
   The cardiovascular disease survey found more medicines being
developed for hypertension, or high blood pressure, than any other
condition with all but three of the 38 drugs in that category in the
final stages of testing.
   The PMA said the second largest category is congestive heart
failure, the final and often fatal phase of heart disease, with 28
drugs under development.
</TEXT>
