<DOCNO> AP881025-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1627EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Gulf     10-25 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Perez de Cuellar Invites Iran, Iraq to Resume Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
on Tuesday invited Iran and Iraq to resume their peace talks, and
members of the Security Council called on the nations to be more
cooperative in the new talks.
   Perez de Cuellar said his invitation to resume talks on Monday in
Geneva has been sent, but it was too early for a reply. Officials of
both countries had expressed their willingness to resume talks
before the end of the month in Geneva.
   Perez de Cuellar gave the members of the council a report Tuesday
that brought out the urgency of a rapid troop withdrawal from the
Iran-Iraq border, said the council's president, Alexander Count York
von Wartenburg.
   The 15 Security Council members unanimously adopted a statement
expressing their concern over the slow pace of the talks in
September and early October, he said.
   The members ``express their expectation that substantive progress
will be made in Geneva in order to achieve a full and rapid
implementation of Resolution 598 as an integral whole,'' said von
Wartenburg, referring to the council's peace plan.
   Observers interpreted the stress on implementing Resolution 598
as an ``integral whole'' as pressure on Iraq to give up its
insistence that the Shatt-al-Arab waterway that form the southern
border between the two nations must be cleared before the peace
talks take up other issues.
   The waterway is Iraq's only navigable outlet to the Persian Gulf,
but it has been clogged with sunken ships and silt since the war
broke out in 1980.
   Perez de Cuellar said that he and his special mediator for the
talks, Swedish Ambassador Jan K. Eliasson, will go to Geneva, but
the secretary-general expects to stay only for four or five days.
   ``I am encouraged by the fact that both sides appear ready to
show their goodwill by proceeding with some repatraition (of
prisoners of war) in the near future,'' he said.
   Iraq has suggested that all POWs could be sent home as a
humanitarian gesture outside of the peace negotiations.
   Iran said the POW issue is one of the terms of the resolution and
cannot be separated from it, but Iranian Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar
Mahallati said last week his country is ready to reciprocate
humanitarian gestures.
   Mahallati suggested that sick and injured prisoners and those
held the longest might be the first to be repatriated.
   Iranian and Iraqi sources have said both sides have accepted a
compromise from the secretary-general to break the stalemate over
the Shatt-al-Arab by postponing discussions of the issue until a
later stage of the talks.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, also said Iran
has accepted Iraq's demand to stop searching ships for war material
bound for Iraq.
   The compromises would allow both sides to concentrate on
negotiating the withdrawal of their troops to an internationally
recognized border and the repatriation of POWs.
   Iran has not stopped any ships since Aug. 20, the day the
U.N.-mediated cease-fire began.
