<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1628EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HarvardBlacks     10-25 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Harvard Blacks,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Harvard Faculty, Administrators Call For Greater Affirmative
Action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IAN DONNIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harvard University cannot foster the ideal of
racial equality given the underrepresentation of blacks among its
faculty and administrators, says a report issued Tuesday by an
organization of black staffers.
   Blacks make up 3 percent of the Ivy League school's instructors
and administrators, and the Association of Black Faculty and
Administrators called for increasing that figure to 10 percent.
   ``The challenge of overcoming the attachment to the beliefs and
benefits of white supremacy remains,'' the association said in its
report.
   The authors of the paper, titled ``The Final Report,'' used an
unusual story-telling technique, hypothesizing what would happen if
Harvard President Derek Bok and all of the school's black faculty
and administrators were killed in an explosion.
   The outpouring of sympathy, they concluded, would mean that
Harvard ``would adopt a much more effective program for recruiting
blacks to the school than now exists.''
   Lawrence Watson, assistant dean of the Harvard Graduate School of
Design and an association co-chair, said framing the report this way
was intended to dramatize the group's message.
   ``The use of stories to make a point is a well-known African
tradition, one that is increasingly used as a medium for scholarly
discourse,'' Watson said. ``It is our hope that the report's unusual
character will prevent its becoming another forgotten report on
affirmative action, a subject about which much more has been written
than accomplished.''
   The association said 17 of Harvard's present 957 tenured faculty,
or 1.8 percent, are black. Twenty-six of the 2,265 tenure-line
faculty, or 1.1. percent, are black, and 155 of 3,205
administrators, or 4.8 percent, are black, it said.
   In the imaginary scenario, an unnamed president would increase
minority hiring by vigorous effort and, when those positions could
not be filled, fund fellowships to help promising black students
gain the credentials to teach at Harvard or other elite schools.
   ``We view this report as an incentive for a more detailed
discussion and review with the deans of the university's 1988
Affirmative Action Plan,'' said association co-chair Derrick Bell, a
Harvard Law School professor.
   In noting that release of ``The Final Report'' comes 100 years
after black educator and historian W.E.B. Du Bois' admission to
Harvard College, the association said blacks still face prejudice at
Harvard.
   ``The association's report noted that today, Dr. Du Bois would
find a substantial number of black students at Harvard. Most are
spared the overt hostility that barred Du Bois from every social
activity except the philosophy club.
   ``Even so, contemporary black students encounter color-based
discrimination in many subtle and debilitating forms, and they
suffer the no-less hurtful slights and disparaging assumptions about
their abilities that Du Bois endured,'' it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881025-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1709EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ClubRules     10-25 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Club Rules,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Handbook Tries to Put Order Into the Night</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new 45-page handbook governing Boston's bustling
nightclubs has been adopted by the city's Licensing Board, with
provisions including bans on discriminatory admission practices and
display of ``improper'' material.
   While some of the rules are good ideas, the restriction about
what can be displayed could interfere with owners' rights to free
expression, one civil liberties advocate said.
   Boston's bustling and sometimes rowdy night scene prompted
officials to draw up the compilation of rules and regulations,
Licensing Board Chairwoman Andrea Gargiulo said Tuesday.
   The handbook, which clubs will be required to show to patrons on
request, is easier to read than the fine print regulations on
individual licenses issued to owners and will fit into police
officers' pockets, Ms. Gargiulo said.
   The new rules prohibit signs such as ``Proper Dress Required,'' a
vague stipulation that sometimes led to selective discrimination,
Ms. Gargiulo said.
   Also banned are VIP passes on any basis that ``invidiously
discriminates.''
   ``We had cases where a white male with no tie was allowed in and
a black male was told at the door that he couldn't come in without a
tie,'' Ms. Gargiulo said. ``We don't want to leave it up to the
doorman.''
   New signs will have to spell out what constitutes proper dress,
such as jacket and tie required for men, she said.
   Other new rules require that bouncers not strike customers unless
hit first and makes nightclub owners responsible for the actions of
valet parking companies they may hire.
   Waiting lines at popular nightspots will have to be limited and
supervised.
   Penalties for violations include a wide variety of license
restrictions, ranging from limits on the hours liquor can be served
to outright suspension of a club's license.
   The ban on displaying material of an ``improper or objectionable
nature'' in clubs outside the Combat Zone, the adult entertainment
district, came under criticism from the Civil Liberties Union of
Massachusetts.
   ``This is kind of a classic, so-called obscenity issue,'' said
John Roberts, the organization's executive director. ``We know that
in this society, standards obviously differ between what's
acceptable and not acceptable. Somehow, female nudity in a lot of
places is just sort of accepted, but now males is not.''
   John Reinstein, a lawyer with the CLU, said the ban on improper
material could be difficult to enforce. ``If I'm a restaurant owner
with a statue of Michelangelo's David in my place, is that covered
because it's nudity?'' he said.
   Ms. Gargiulo said the rule is not intended to ban nude prints
that hang inside some restaurants, but is aimed at material that is
``way out of line.''
   The guideline on objectionable material will be whether it would
be deemed unsuitable for view by members of the public if it were
located in areas such as public parks or government and business
offices.
   Enforcing the rules may be difficult, but not impossible, Ms.
Gargiulo said. ``They're very subjective and that's why we hold
hearings.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
