<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hirohito     10-25 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor Receives New Transfusion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito, suffering from internal bleeding,
received more than a pint of blood Tuesday in his first transfusion
in two days, the Imperial Household Agency said.
   Before his transfusion, the 87-year-old monarch's blood pressure
fell below 100, as it did Oct. 1, said agency spokesman Kenji Maeda.
   Maeda said Hirohito's blood pressure later recovered to 118 over
58 and his pulse declined to 108 beats a minute some 90 minutes
later. His temperature was 100.4, compared with his normal reading
of 95.9.
   The spokesman said the monarch was in stable condition and was
sleeping well in the evening.
   The blood transfusion Tuesday brought to about 25 pints the total
amount the emperor has received since his condition worsened Sept.
19.
   Court physicians believe the emperor has been bleeding from where
he was operated on in September 1987 to bypass an intestinal
blockage caused by an inflamed pancreas.
   The physicians have neither confirmed nor denied news reports
that the emperor has cancer in his upper digestive system.
   Palace officials said Hirohito was visited separately by several
members of the royal family, including Prince Akihito and his wife,
Princess Michiko, and in the afternoon by Akihito again.
</TEXT>
