<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1757EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HustlerSuit     10-25 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hustler Suit,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Porn Leader's Suit Dismissed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Oregon anti-pornography activist who was
attacked in Hustler Magazine as a sex-fearing ``crackpot'' and
``deluded busybody'' cannot sue for libel because the statements
were matters of opinion, a federal appeals court ruled Tuesday.
   Though the 1985 article about Peggy Ault of Milwaukie, Ore., was
``disgusting and distasteful abuse'' and ``a grievous assault to her
human dignity,'' it contained no statements of fact that could be
the basis of a libel suit, said the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals.
   The 3-0 ruling also rejected claims of invasion of privacy and
intentional infliction of emotional distress. It reversed a federal
judge's order to Ms. Ault to pay Hustler $5,365 in legal fees for a
frivolous suit, saying the legal claims were ``not wholly
unreasonable.''
   ``This case is a good sign for us,'' said David Carson, a lawyer
for the magazine. He said several similar suits are pending, mostly
filed by lawyer Gerry Spence of Jackson, Wyo., whose law firm
represented Ms. Ault. Spence has also sued Hustler for libel because
of the magazine's satiric attack on him for his other suits, Carson
said.
   ``We're hopeful that in light of this ruling, some of the other
lawsuits that Mr. Spence has filed with similar claims might be
thrown out of court,'' Carson said.
   He also cited last year's Supreme Court ruling rejecting a suit
against Hustler by television preacher Jerry Falwell, who was the
subject of a sexual parody in the magazine.
   Lawyers for Ms. Ault did not return phone calls Tuesday.
   Ms. Ault founded a group called Citizens in Action for Clackamas
County, to protest a sex video store in Milwaukie, and has lobbied
for anti-pornography legislation through another group.
   Her suit involved an April 1985 Hustler article that was
illustrated by her photograph superimposed over the rear end of a
bent-over naked man.
   In the article, the magazine called Ms. Ault's local organization
a ``wacko group'' engaged in censorship and intimidation. It also
described her as ``frustrated,'' ``threatened by sex,'' a
``fanatic'' and ``crackpot,'' and a ``deluded busybody'' in need of
professional help.
</TEXT>
