<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Radon-Builders 1stLd-Writethru a0641 10-25 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Radon-Builders, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0641,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Builders' Group Say Energy Efficient Homes Won't Add to Radon
Buildup</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS new 2nd graf to RESTORE dropped matter</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major builders' association on Tuesday said
it has found no evidence that energy-efficient homes increase radon
concentrations and that it is advising its members to build homes as
tight as possible.
   ``Our practices recommend good air sealing techniques,'' just as
would be used in trying to save energy, said John Spears, program
manager for the National Research Center, which is affiliated with
the National Home Builders Association.
   Some analysts have suggested that the increasing importance being
placed on energy efficiency also may be increasing the tendency of
radon, an odorless, radioactive gas given off by all soils, to
concentrate indoors.
   The Environmental Protection Agency has warned that although
increased ventilation may help particular radon-rich homes, as a
general rule well-ventilated homes appear to have no exemption from
radon buildup.
   EPA estimates that radon could be causing as many as 20,000
deaths from lung cancer each year. In September, the Public Health
Service issued a national health advisory warning of radon dangers
and the two agencies urged testing of every home where people live
on the second floor or below.
   As for home sealing, ``We're finding it has little to do with
radon,'' Spears said at a news conference. As a result, the
association is recommending ``the same practices we have recommended
for years for energy conservation. In fact, we've found that energy
conservation has little to do with radon concentration in the house.
We've measured houses all over the country.''
   The association recommended many techniques for reducing radon
buildup, such as carefully sealing off the basement _ often the same
techniques used for keeping water out.
   William H. Ethier, litigation counsel for the association, said
members were being advised that ``if they make a reasoned judgment
that there may be high radon levels,'' that they should ``rough in''
mitigation techniques such as under-slab ventilation pipes that may
be ignored later if appropriate, or connected to a fan to divert
radon-laden air around the basement.
   In states such as Pennsylvania and New Jersey with
well-publicized instances of radon buildup, Ethier said he has found
``universal'' adoption of such precautions by builders.
   Builders report that the techniques may add as little as $100 to
the cost of a home, if water barriers are already being used, but as
much as $600 if they are not, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
