<2ND_LINE>AM-Anti-Drug Rally, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0671,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Olympian Joins HHS Secretary At Anti-Drug Rally</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: CORRECTS name in lead to Norman, sted Normal</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Olympic kayak gold medalist Norman Bellingham
joined Health and Human Services Secretary Otis R. Bowen on Tuesday
at a rally for National Drug Free America Week.
   Similar rallies were held in 20 other cities. Drug Free America
Week is a Cabinet initiative designed to spur town meetings,
conferences and fund-raising activities across the nation to support
community drug prevention projects.
   ``Americans now have a deeper understanding of the health dangers
of illicit drug use,'' Bowen said. ``People have come to understand
that illicit drug use can mean addiction or death.''
   The health chief cited the special danger of injecting drugs
intravenously.
   ``Sharing contaminated needles is like playing Russian Roulette
with the AIDS virus,'' said Bowen. ``Intravenous drug abusers now
make up more than a quarter of all cases of AIDS diagnosed thus
far.''
   Bowen called on parents to take the lead in fighting drugs with
some specific advice:
   _``Education your children about the dangers of illicit drug use.
Share with them information about the health impact of drug use and
teach them how to just say no.
   _``Watch for the early warning signs _ dropping grades, behavior
change, stolen money or missing items of value.
   -``Provide positive alternatives for your children. When children
have nothing interesting to motivate them, then they may be tempted
to turn to drugs.
   _``Personally remain drug free. Many children learn about drug
use from their parents. If you have a problem, find treatment.
   _``Help make your neighborhood and work-site drug free. If you
know someone who has a problem, whether in your neighborhood or at
work, help them to get help. You may be their last, best hope.''
</TEXT>
