<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1634EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a BC-KlanTrial     10-25 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Klan Trial,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plaintiffs Get $1 Million In Suit Against KKK</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMer planned by 5 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ku Klux Klan and 12 individuals must pay about
$1 million to 53 civil rights marchers who were pelted with rocks
and bottles during a demonstration in virtually all-white Forsyth
County, according to a verdict unsealed Tuesday.
   The activists marched into the county north of Atlanta on Jan.
17, 1987, and were attacked by counter-demonstrators, many of them
KKK members or sympathizers.
   Named as defendants in the U.S. District Court lawsuit were the
Southern White Knights of the KKK, the Invisible Empire Knights of
the KK and 12 individuals.
   The jury reached its verdict Oct. 5, but Judge Charles A. Moye
Jr. ordered it sealed to give marchers who brought the lawsuit time
to decide whether to join Atlanta City Councilman Hosea Williams,
who wanted to drop the lawsuit.
   Williams, who helped organize the march and was among those who
filed suit, urged toward the end of the trial that the lawsuit be
dropped because it would impoverish the families of KKK members.
   In a letter to those who filed with him, Williams said he had
talked to slain civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr. and that
King told him ``Jesus wanted him not to sue the Klan.'' He and three
other defendants dropped out.
   State Rep. William McKinney, who had opposed Williams' move to
drop the lawsuit, said Williams' ``religion and communication with
the dead should not interfere with our constitutional rights and
justice.''
   The award gave $50 each to the marchers in general damages. The
rest was in punitive damages. The lawsuit had sought $1.5 million.
   The two Klan organizations were fined $400,000 each. David
Holland, Grand Dragon of the White Knights, was fined $50,000.
Individual fines ranged from $30,000 to $1,000, except for Harold
Palmour, who was judged not to be liable and was not fined.
   The ``brotherhood march'' was a forerunner to a larger
demonstration a week later in which an estimated 24,000 persons
turned out. State, local, county and federal troops were called out
to protect the marchers and to prevent violence.
   A march into the county a year ago commemorating the anniversary
of the 1987 marches was peaceful.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
