<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Bush,0135</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Still Favorite at Top Bookmaker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush remained a favorite to
win the Nov. 8 presidential election at very short odds of 1-7,
bookmakers said Tuesday.
   The figures mean a bettor has to pay $7 dollars to win $1, plus
his stake back.
   The odds on Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis winning were 7-2,
meaning $7 dollars plus the returned stake would be won for a $2 bet.
   ``The odds have not changed in the past week,'' said Sandy
Wilkinson, a spokesman for the Ladbrokes bookmakers.
   ``Quite a bit of money has gone on Bush in Britain and we have
had some big bets telephoned from the United States, some of them
from famous people,'' she said. She would not disclose their names.
