<DOCNO> AP881025-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1903EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Oil     10-25 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Oil,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Largest Iranian Oil Port To Be Opened To Foreign Ships</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran will open its main oil port to
foreign vessels as it pulls its own tankers out of service from the
Persian Gulf route heavily attacked during its war with Iraq,
shipping sources said Tuesday.
   Iran will eliminate service by Iranian-operated tankers from
Kharg Island in the northeastern gulf to the Sirri terminal in the
south by the end of the year, according to the London-based Lloyd's
Shipping Intelligence Unit, which monitors maritime traffic.
   It quoted Mohammad Souri, chairman and managing director of the
National Iranian Tanker Co., as saying he expected foreign tankers
to take over the transport of half of Iran's oil exports from Kharg
within a month and all of it within two months.
   Iraq imposed an air and sea blockade around Kharg in 1984, a move
that triggered the tanker war in which more than 500 ships were
attacked by both countries.
   Iran is exporting an estimated 1.4 million barrels of oil a day.
Officials have said they plan to increase their long-term export
capacity to around 4.5 million barrels a day.
   The Lloyd's report underlined Iranian efforts to restore normal
oil export operations following the Aug. 20 cease-fire in the
8-year-old war between Iran and Iraq.
   Gulf-based shipping officials reported earlier this month the
Iranians had stopped exercising their legal right to stop vessels
suspected of carrying war-related cargoes to Iraq.
   They also reported that Iran has withdrawn all its armed
speedboats from the southern gulf island of Abu Musa island, which
was used as a base from which to attack neutral ships in reprisal
for Iraqi air raids on tankers carrying Iranian oil. The last
Iranian attack was a speedboat raid on a Norwegian tanker on Aug.4.
   Japan's shipowners and maritime union Tuesday lifted a ban it
imposed last year to keep its ships from sailing to Kharg.
   A shipping source who requested anonymity said there were
unconfirmed reports that a Japanese tanker had already loaded at
Kharg and left the gulf. Shipments from Kharg account for 90 percent
of Iran's oil exports, which made the port a target of repeated
Iraqi air raids aimed at strangling the oil sales that financed
Tehran's war effort.
   Lloyd's quoted Souri as saying negotiations are under way to
return some of Iran's 17 chartered oil vessels to international
service, a move expected to depress the tanker market.
   At the peak of the war, the Iranians had a shuttle fleet of more
than 30 tankers, many of them charters, because foreign vessels
would not risk Iraqi attacks to reach Kharg.
   Gulf-based shipping executives said the 547,841-ton Burmah
Endeavor, which was used as a storage vessel for crude oil shipped
from Kharg, was in the southern gulf port of Dubai for reconversion
to sea duty. The British-flagged supertanker was damaged in an Iraqi
air raid in May.
   Lloyd's said that disbanding Iran's tanker service would save
Iran an estimated $300 million a year.
   Kharg and its tankers were bombed scores of times by Iraq's air
force and the port was heavily fortified with anti-aircraft and
missile batteries.
   The Iranians tried to circumvent the Iraqi blockade by installing
a makeshift terminal at Sirri Island, about 350 miles south.
   Foreign tankers loaded there until the Iraqis raided Sirri in
1986. Loading operations were then moved another 120 miles south to
Larak island in the Strait of Hormuz, the gateway to the gulf.
   But Iraqi warplanes began hitting Larak as well, culminating in a
May 14 strike in which several supertankers were sunk or crippled.
   The U.S. Navy severely damaged the Sirri platform on April 18 in
retaliatory raids for the mining of a U.S. warship.
   Since the cease-fire, Sirri's terminal has reopened, shipping
officials said, while Larak has ceased to function as an oil
terminal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
