<2ND_LINE>AM-Lotto Winners, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0667,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Factory-Working Sisters Split $31 Million Jackpot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Louis to Lewis in 3rd-from-last graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two sisters who work on an assembly line
produced the winning ticket Tuesday to a Lotto jackpot worth more
than $31.5 million and said they would split the prize.
   ``We always go in together,'' said Mary Ellen Snipes.
   She and her sister, Maxine Johnson, both of the southeast Florida
farming community of Indiantown, took the day off from work to file
their claim.
   The women will share $1,576,743 a year before taxes for the next
20 years.
   Mrs. Snipes, who said her ex-husband picked the winning numbers
from her pay-check stub, said she plans to keep working and would
build a ``dream house'' with her newfound wealth.
   But Mrs. Johnson said she wasn't sure yet if she would keep
working and said she didn't know what she would do with her half of
the money. But she said she would stay on the job at least until
next Wednesday, when the first check is expected to arrive.
   The sisters are assembly line leaders at Solitron Devices, an
electronic components firm in Riviera Beach.
   Both declined to give their ages or the ages of their children,
but said all were grown. Mrs. Johnson said she has four children and
Mrs. Snipes said she had three. Both women said they were
grandmothers, but did not say how many grandchildren they have.
   Mrs. Johnson and Mrs. Snipes have two other sisters, one in
Jacksonville and one in West Palm Beach.
   The two sisters, regular Lotto players, bought 10 of the $1
tickets last week.
   But Mrs. Snipes said she almost didn't play. After working
Saturday, she was tired and had decided she wasn't going to bother
with it. Her ex-husband, Lewis Snipes, came over and prodded her
into it, she said.
   Snipes, who was at the press conference, was asked if he was
going to get any of the money.
   ``That's still in question,'' he said.
</TEXT>
