<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FreedDad     10-25 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Freed Dad,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dad Freed After Son Returns, Says `I Did Right Thing'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER MUNNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iowa State University student who
served a seven-month jail term for contempt of court was freed
Tuesday after the son he sent away to Jordan was returned to the
boy's mother.
   ``I think I did the right thing,'' said Ahmed Amro, of the
decision two years ago to send the child away. His son and ex-wife
were reunited Monday night.
   Amro was sentenced to an indefinite jail term by District Judge
M.L. Seiser last March when Amro did not comply with a divorce
decree awarding custody of his 4-year-old son, Mujahid, to Amro's
ex-wife, Souad Mejdouli.
   The boy was greeted by his mother at the Des Moines International
Airport late Monday after the journey from Jordan, and Amro was
released about 10 hours later.
   ``I didn't believe it, I'm still in shock,'' said Ms. Mejdouli,
who lives in Ames, north of here. ``I think my son was in shock,
too, but I'm awfully glad to have him back. We have a lot of things
to catch up on, a lot of hugging and kissing.''
   Amro at first demanded that the issue of child custody be decided
by Islamic laws rather than Iowa courts, and he later said he should
be freed from jail because there was nothing he could do to gain
return of the child.
   Amro sent his son to Jordan two years ago to live with Amro's
sister after Amro was convicted of beating his wife. Ms. Mejdouli
later divorced him and won custody of the child.
   Amro, a computer engineering student at Iowa State, contended
that his father, a devout Moslem, refused to allow the boy to
return, but his plea to overturn the indefinite jail confinement was
denied by the Iowa Supreme Court.
   ``It's no place for a human being,'' Amro said Tuesday of his
jail stay, but said he made the right decision about his son.
   ``I wanted him to be away while there was a dispute between
myself and his mother. He probably would have been psychologically
ruined'' if he had witnessed the dispute, Amro said. He said he
intended for the boy to be away only for a month or two.
   He said the grandfather changed his mind when he was told of the
Supreme Court's decision.
   Amro said he has been a permanent U.S. resident for five years
and has applied for citizenship.
   Amro said he wants to finish the semester of school needed for
his bachelor's degree, and will seek visitation rights.
   ``I don't want to be a part-time dad. I want to always be there
for my son when he needs me,'' Amro said. ``I want to see him as
much as I can. I want to be involved in his life.''
   ``Oh, yeah,'' retorted Ms. Mejdouli in a separate interview.
``That's why he sent him overseas for two years. We don't trust him.
That's the same game he played with us two years ago.''
   A visitation hearing has been set in Seiser's court for Thursday
morning.
</TEXT>
