<1ST_LINE>r a BC-MarineDisastersList     10-25 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Marine Disasters List,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>List Of Worst Marine Disasters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Ruby Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of major marine disasters in the 20th century:
   1. Jan. 30, 1945: 6,000 Germans die in the icy Baltic Sea when
the Nazi transport Wilhelm Gustloff, packed with Germans fleeing
Poland, is torpedoed by a Soviet submarine. Only 903 people are
saved.
   2. November 1948: A Chinese merchant ship with as many as 6,000
people aboard explodes and sinks off southern Manchuria, killing all
aboard, during the government evacuation of Yingkow.
   3. Dec. 3, 1948: 3,920 die when the refugee ship Kiangya explodes
and sinks near Shanghai.
   4. Feb. 26, 1916: 3,100 killed when the French cruiser Provence
sinks in the Mediterranean.
   5. Dec. 20, 1987: MV Dona Paz, loaded with Christmas travelers,
collides with the tanker MT Victor in the Philippines. At least
1,749 people are confirmed drowned but, because of overcrowding, the
toll could have been more than 3,000.
   6. Dec. 6, 1917: 1,600 killed when French ammunition ship Mont
Blanc and Belgian steamer collide in Halifax Harbor.
   7. April 14-15, 1912: 1,503 killed when British steamer Titanic
hits iceberg in North Atlantic.
   8. May 7, 1915: 1,198 killed when British steamer Lusitania sunk
by German submarine off Ireland.
   9. Sept. 26, 1954: 1,172 killed when Japanese ferry Toya Maru
sinks in Tsugaru Strait, Japan.
   10. June 15, 1904: 1,030 killed when excursion steamer General
Slocum burns in East River, New York City.
   11. May 29, 1914: 1,014 killed when British steamer Empress of
Ireland is sunk in collision with Norwegian collier in St. Lawrence
River.
   12. Aug. 29, 1916: 1,000 killed when Chinese steamer Hsin Yu
sinks off Chinese coast.
   13. March 18, 1921: 1,000 killed when steamer Hong Kong wrecks in
South China Sea.
   14. Sept. 28, 1912: 1,000 killed when Japanese steamer Kichemaru
sinks off Japanese coast.
   15. July 24, 1915: 812 killed when excursion steamer Eastland
capsizes in Chicago River.
   16. August 8, 1988: As many as 400 are drowned in India when an
overcrowded ferry capsizes in the Ganges River.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
