<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SovietShips     10-25 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Ships,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Task Force Headed for Cuba</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small task force of Soviet warships is making
its way toward Cuba in what appears to be a routine deployment, the
Pentagon said Tuesday.
   The task force is led by a Udaloy-class guided-missile destroyer
and includes at least two other vessels _ a Krivak-class
guided-missile frigate and an Olekma-class replenishment oiler, a
Pentagon statement said.
   If normal procedures are being followed, however, those three
surface ships are being accompanied by a diesel-powered submarine,
it added.
   The group, now steaming in the Atlantic south of Bermuda, should
arrive in Cuba before the end of the week.
   ``Two Soviet Bear-D reconnaissance aircraft and two Bear-F
anti-submarine warfare aircraft arrived in Cuba last week, and may
participate in exercises with the Soviet surface ships,'' the
Pentagon said.
   The deployment of Soviet warships to the Caribbean is not
unusual, although this is the first such movement in two years.
According to the Navy, it is the 27th such operation conducted by
the Soviets since 1969.
   U.S. forces will maintain surveillance of the ships, particularly
if they move into the Gulf of Mexico for exercises, the Pentagon
said.
</TEXT>
