<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TenantAgreement     10-25 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tenant Agreement,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Public Housing Tenants to Buy Own Apartments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tenants of a public housing development in
a poverty-stricken, drug-laden neighborhood took the first step
Tuesday toward buying the housing project.
   ``This is a dream becoming reality,'' said community activist
Kimi Gray, chairman of the Kenilworth-Parkside Management Corp.,
which received final approval for its bid to purchase the 464
apartments from the District of Columbia city government for $1.
``We've worked six years for this.''
   After the complex is renovated, in several years, residents will
be able to buy their apartments for as little as $10,000 each.
   The occasion marked the first instance in history in which public
housing tenants arranged to buy their own apartments.
   Gray organized the tenant corporation, which took over management
of the project in 1982, reducing administrative costs by 60 percent.
   Before that, when it had been managed by a private firm under
contract to the city, it was rat-infested and run down. Apartments
had no heat or hot water; the chain link fence was squashed and
rusted.
   ``We have a vested interest,'' explained Gray in an interview at
the time. ``We live here, so we really care. We're supersensitive.''
   The sale to the tenants was made possible through a 1987 law
authorizing the conversion of several public housing projects across
the country to tenant ownership to demonstrate whether the idea was
feasible.
   The actual sale will not take effect until after the completion
of a $23 million federally financed renovation of the 33-building
complex. The Department of Housing and Urban Development also will
provide $6 million in rental assistance over the next five years.
   The tenants corporation plans to help tenants increase their
incomes so they can afford to buy their apartments, said Alphonso
Jackson, director of the city's Department of Public and Assisted
Housing.
   So far, 132 residents have been removed from welfare rolls as
result of the corporation's ``entrepreneurial ventures,'' such as a
day care center and janitorial service, he said.
</TEXT>
