<DOCNO> AP881025-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1916EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugTesting     10-25 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Testing,0691</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NY Court Rules Random Urine Testing of Elite Police Force Legal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Random urine testing for drugs among an elite
corps of New York City police officers is legal because of the
dangerous and sensitive nature of their work, a divided New York
state Court of Appeals ruled Tuesday.
   The 5-2 decision by the state's top court not only overturns two
lower court rulings, it constitutes an ``about face'' for a court
which only last year ruled that a drug-testing plan for Long Island
teachers was an unreasonable invasion of their privacy, the
dissenting judges said.
   The court decision upholds New York City Police Commissioner
Benjamin Ward's 1986 order that members of the department's
Organized Crime Control Bureau must undergo random urinalysis for
drugs. Approximately 1,100 of the city's 27,000 police officers
volunteer for duty in the special unit. Up to 90 percent are
involved in narcotics-related work.
   ``The terror-filled world they are working in requires the
sternest precautionary safeguards to weed out drug abusers from
their own ranks,'' wrote Judge Joseph Bellacosa for the majority.
   The court ruled unanimously last year in a case involving
Patchogue teachers that governments couldn't force public employees
to take drug tests unless there is a ``reasonable suspicion'' that
workers are using drugs.
   Much of Bellacosa's 14-page ruling was taken up with an
explanation of why the police officers should be held to stricter
standards than the teachers. The lower courts incorrectly gave an
``absolutist reading'' to the Court of Appeals' decision in the
teachers' case, he said.
   The ``direct correlation'' between an organized crime officer's
work and drugs should be considered in evaluating the extent of
their constitutional rights to privacy, Bellacosa wrote.
   ``The officers agree to undergo microscopic examinations of their
personal lives, their financial affairs and their professional
judgment calls,'' Bellacosa said. ``Realistically, the proposed
random drug testing in these narrow circumstances is just another
layer of an already heightened, persistent and employee-expected
scrutiny.''
   Judge Judith Kaye, in a dissenting opinion, said the government
hasn't established why the testing is needed or why the officers
should be held to such special standards.
   ``The public clearly has an interest in the integrity of every
employee who serves it,'' Kaye wrote. ``Equally clearly, that alone
does not give the state the power to conduct intrusive searches of
their person.''
   According to court papers, all city police recruits are tested
for drugs when they apply to the department, again during their
five-month police academy training and at the end of their 18-month
probation. Tenured officers are subject to testing if there's a
reasonable suspicion of drug use.
   Officers applying to the organized crime unit were required by
Ward in 1986 to sign a form acknowledging that periodic drug testing
was a condition of employment.
   The policemen's union, the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association,
sued to overturn the order two days after it was announced.
   Raymond Kerno, the union's lawyer, said he was surprised at the
decision.
   He called the drug testing an ``excessive attempt'' to solve a
problem that doesn't really exist.
   The decision gives new life to municipalities who hope to start
drug testing programs, said Michael Adler, a lawyer in New York
City's corporation counsel's office.
   The city in late 1987 tried to institute random drug testing for
all corrections officers, he said. But lower courts have struck down
the program, citing the Patchogue case, he said.
   ``I think certainly those who might favor drug testing are
probably better equipped to make a legal argument justifying the
testing than they had before this decision came down,'' Adler said.
   According to police department records, narcotics-related
disciplinary charges have been filed against 10 police officers in
the crime unit in four years.
   Kaye said these statistics show there's no indication of a drug
abuse problem within this unit. ``The important goal of deterrence
... is not, without evidence of a pervasive problem among the
persons to be tested, justification for this search,'' she said.
</TEXT>
