<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Children'sHome     10-25 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children's Home,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leader Of Bethel Home And Assistants Indicted On State Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUCEDALE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defiant director of a fundamentalist
children's home and two assistants were indicted by a state grand
jury Tuesday in connection with a June confrontation with law
enforcement officers.
   The Rev. Herman Fountain, 38, and Michael Baldino, 25, were
indicted on three counts each of felonious assault on a law
enforcement officer, while two counts were lodged against
18-year-old Phil Reining. A Friday arraignment hearing in George
County Circuit Court was set for the three.
   Fountain and his assistants are accused of assaulting law
officers who stormed the Bethel Home for Children on June 13 and
took custody of allegedly abused and neglected youth. The unlicensed
school is operated by the independent Bethel Baptist Church.
   The indictments were handed down by a George County grand jury
that went into session Monday. Fountain and the two assistants drove
to the George County Courthouse after they were notified by Circuit
Clerk Wilbur Ward about the indictments and they were allowed to
remain free on bonds that were posted after the confrontation.
   Fountain has been free on $40,000 bond, Baldino on $20,000 bond
and Reining on $10,000 bond.
   ``I don't feel like they're after me, I feel like they're after
the church,'' Fountain said when he arrived at the courthouse.
   County Prosecutor Mark Maples was in court Tuesday and
unavailable for comment.
   Fountain, who has claimed to be a former heroin addict and
witchcraft practitioner, has said he had as many as 120 children
living at his 28-acre compound outside Lucedale.
   He claims his right to freedom of religion exempts him from any
state oversight, but a George County Youth Court judge, looking into
allegations of beatings and other abuse, ordered the state
Department of Public Welfare last June to take custody of the Bethel
residents.
   Some state law officers have accused Fountain of ordering the
children to flee the compound. Fountain denies the allegation. It
took officials several days to round up the children.
   The minister is accused of punching law officers after they
stormed the locked church in search of the children. Several
witnesses, including reporters, saw Fountain swing at lawmen.
   The minister has appealed a separate disorderly conduct
conviction in justice court. He has been fined $200 for the charge,
which also stems from the June 13 incident. His initial circuit
court appearance in the appeal is scheduled for Oct. 31.
</TEXT>
