<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CornedBeefRecall     10-25 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Corned Beef Recall,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Castleberry's Recalls Hash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Castleberry's Food Co., Augusta, Ga., is
voluntarily recalling 51,985 cans of corned beef hash in six states
because 912 cans did not go through the required heat processing,
the Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   The recall affects suspected products in Alabama, Georgia, North
Carolina, South Carolina, Michigan and New Jersey. Officials said
the suspected corn beef could contain food poisoning organisms,
including some that could cause botulism, a deadly form of poisoning.
   The product, Castleberry's Single Serve Canned Corned Beef Hash,
is packaged in 7{-ounce cans with pull tabs and is sold mostly in
vending machines. A small percentage of the product is sold also in
convenience and grocery stores.
   The products are identified by the code numbers 2J81CBV3 or
2J81CBV4 on the bottom of the cans. The USDA inspection mark shows
Est. 195.
   ``Although no illnesses have been reported, we strongly urge
consumers to avoid tasting the products and to return them
immediately to the establishment where they were purchased,'' said
Lester M. Crawford, administrator of the department's Food Safety
and Inspection Service.
   Vending machine operators and other distributors were advised to
remove the product from sale and hold it for pickup by the company.
   Crawford said that Castleberry's discovered that part of one
day's production is not sterile and will allow the growth of any
food spoilage organisms that may be present.
   Among these organisms may be Clostridium botulinum, which causes
botulism, which was described in the announcement as ``a serious
form of food poisoning.'' Other literature published by USDA,
however, calls botulism ``an extremely deadly form of food
poisoning.''
</TEXT>
