<DOCNO> AP881025-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1926EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina 1stLd-Writethru a0612 10-25 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0612,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-President Makes Surprise Visit to Homeland</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT airport name to Ezeiza, sted Ezeira;
INSERTS graf after 5th pvs `But her ...'' UPDATING with reax from
labor leader. PICKS up 6th pvs: `The Peronist Party...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By OSCAR SERRAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Isabel Peron made
a surprise visit to her homeland Tuesday.
   ``I wanted to be in Argentina and here I am,'' she told reporters
at Ezeiza International Airport.
   Mrs. Peron's arrival from Spain, where she has lived since 1981,
comes at the beginning of what promises to be a bitter political
campaign that will culminate in national elections next May.
   Mrs. Person, 57, has stayed out of politics since she was
overthrown in 1976 by the military and held under house arrest for
five years. She succeeded her husband, Juan Peron, when he died in
1974.
   But her sympathies appear to lie more with President Raul
Alfonsin of the Radical Civic Union than with the opposition
Peronist Party.
   Lesio Romero, secretary of the Meatpackers Union, said, ``The
unexpected arrival of Mrs. Peron is very strange. We understand she
was invited by the national government. I hope she doesn't intend to
involve herself with our (Peronist) movement.''
   The Peronist Party is divided among supporters of presidential
candidate Carlos Menem, the front-runner and governor of the poor
province of La Rioja, and Buenos Aires Gov. Antonio Cafiero.
   Last weekend, Menem said his party might try to impeach Alfonsin
``because of the perverse political economy applied by the national
government.''
   Alfonsin is barred by the constitution from seeking re-election.
   The Radical Civic Union candidate for president is Eduardo
Angeloz, the governor of prosperous Cordoba province.
   Mrs. Peron's visit is her third since Alfonsin was inaugurated
president in December 1983. The previous two visits were at
Alfonsin's invitation.
   Mrs. Peron's turbulent 20 months in office were marked by
kidnappings and assassinations conducted by left- and right-wing
political extremists, and an economic collapse.
   Mrs. Peron was elected vice-president in the 1973 election her
husband won by a landslide after returning to Argentine politics
from an eighteen-year exile in Madrid.
   Peron was elected president in 1946 and re-elected in 1951. He
was overthrown by the military in 1955.
   He met Maria Estela Martinez, known as Isabel, at a night club in
Panama after the 1955 coup. She became his secretary and followed
him to Venezuela and Spain, where she became his third wife.
</TEXT>
