<2ND_LINE>AM-Wife Shot,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Says Being Shot By Husband Has Strengthened Relationship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARGO, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who shot his wife last summer in a
struggle over whether to kill the family dog received a suspended
jail sentence after his spouse said the incident had strengthened
their marriage.
   Danelle Dickelman, 27, of rural Horace, asked East Central
District Judge Cynthia Rothe for leniency for her husband, Paul,
during Dickelman's sentencing Tuesday on a conviction for reckless
endangerment.
   Dickelman, 31, who spent five days in jail after the shooting
last June, had suffered enough, Mrs. Dickelman told the judge.
   Dickelman had been drinking and was intent on shooting the family
dog when the incident occurred, said John Goff, an assistant Cass
County state's attorney. The dog had angered Dickelman because of
its habit of urinating on the carpet in their home, the prosecutor
said.
   Mrs. Dickelman struggled with her husband before he shot her with
a .22-caliber pistol, Goff said. Mrs. Dickelman told the judge at
Tuesday's sentencing that the shooting was an accident.
   The pistol was loaded with birdshot, and Mrs. Dickelman suffered
pellet wounds in her mouth. She has since recovered, according to
Goff.
   Mrs. Dickelman said the incident had prompted her husband to seek
help for a drinking problem, and that the couple ``were trying to
turn this ... into a positive thing,'' Goff said.
   Rothe sentenced Dickelman to a year in jail for the misdemeanor
and then suspended all but the five days he had served and placed
him on two years' probation.
   The judge said Dickelman must refrain from drinking, using drugs
or handling firearms during his probation and also must perform 200
hours of community service work.
</TEXT>
