<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CoachBias     10-25 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coach Bias,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commission Finds Firing of Coach Racially Motivated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Massachusetts Commission Against
Discrimination has found that the 1985 firing of the only black
coach in the Pittsfield West Little League was racially motivated.
   David Williams filed a complaint with the state commission after
he was dismissed as coach of the Connor Pharmacy team in June 1985
following a series of disputes with league officials. Among other
things, Williams contended that league Umpire-In-Chief Ralph
Stannard had called him ``boy'' in a ``racially and personally
derogatory manner in the course of a game.''
   At the time, the league of six teams had no black players,
according to the commission. Each team has at least one coach, all
of whom serve for free, according to league Secretary-Treasurer John
Marchesi.
   Following its finding, the state commission attempted to mediate
the dispute between Williams and the league, but no conclusion was
reached in a three-hour meeting Monday, said Rosemary Nevins,
commission staff council.
   She said that if no agreement could be worked out privately
between the parties, the commission could hold public hearings.
After that the issue could be decided by the courts.
   The main sticking point, according to Williams was the wording of
an apology he sought from league officials. He said that he had
never sought monetary compensation from the league but wanted the
apology to boost his chances of seeking other coaching jobs.
   ``If there is a statement to be issued,'' he said. ``I just want
it to clarify that I'm not the troublemaker some people might make
me out to be. This isn't a situation I created.''
   Williams, who works as a wireman at General Electric Co., had
previously coached junior varsity baseball at Lee High School and
junior varsity girls basketball at Taconic High School in
Pittsfield. He had initially filed a civil suit against the league
over his dismissal in 1985, but withdrew the action in favor of
pursuing a complaint through the commission.
   ``I couldn't afford to co through the courts,'' Williams said. He
said the cost of the complaint was about half that of a civil suit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
