<HEAD>White House Domestic Policy Adviser Gary Bauer Leaving Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary Bauer, a top-ranking domestic policy
adviser to President Reagan, is resigning effective Oct. 31 to head
a private foundation that will focus on family issues.
   Bauer, 42, who worked for then-Education Secretary William
Bennett before coming to the White House in 1986, was a principal
advocate within the White House for such conservative social agenda
causes as school prayer and abolition of legal abortions.
   Reagan attended a private farewell party for Bauer on Tuesday
afternoon in the White House, telling Bauer he was sad to see him
leave but happy that he would continue to push the conservative
agenda.
