<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1735EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Homeless-Cartoons     10-25 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless-Cartoons,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nation's Cartoonists Mount Comic-Page Campaign for the Homeless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA BARNAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   America's cartoonists used their pens to skewer disdain and
apathy toward the homeless in a concerted campaign on the comic
pages Tuesday. Nancy and Sluggo played ``homeless couple,'' a
homeless man offered to share his meal of popcorn with Ziggy, and
Marmaduke befriended homeless dogs.
   ``The whole purpose of this is to draw attention to the plight of
the homeless, to make people aware that something needs to be
done,'' said Bill Day, a syndicated Detroit Free Press cartoonist
who was one of more than 100 comic-strip and editorial cartoonists
to participate in the project.
   ``The wealthy can afford lobbying groups. I feel the purpose of
the cartoonist is to help those who can't afford a lobby,'' said
Day, who drew a prosperous, well-fed Uncle Sam gazing in the mirror
and seeing a gaunt-faced version of himself labeled the homeless,
holding his coat together at the neck. There are no official counts
of the number of homeless, but national estimates range from 350,000
to more than 3 million, according to the National Low Income Housing
Coalition, an organizer of the project.
   Some of the artists got their messages across through humor,
others used irony or exaggeration. Some of the cartoons were
political: taking aim at the presidential campaign or Washington
posturing.
   Garry Trudeau's ``Doonesbury'' simply focused on the humanity of
a panhandling couple, Alice and Elmont. When a tired Elmont mistakes
his wife for a rival on his corner, he apologizes by explaining he
mistook her for ``some gorgeous hooker,'' and she goes off pleased.
   Other cartoonists relied on the naivete of outsiders, be they
children or observers from a different time like Hagar the Viking.
Dik Browne, Hagar's creator, has his hero and his wife in front of a
fortune teller, who predicts, ``One day, millions of people will be
homeless, and millions of others who could easily help will just
turn away.''
   Responds the fierce Viking: ``And they call ME horrible.''
   In the ``Middletons,'' by Ralph Bunagin and Dana Summers, a child
watches as his mother puts change in a street person's cup. After
she explains the man is homeless and the money is for food, the
youngster says, ``Gosh, he'd get more to eat if I gave him my
trick-or-treat bag.''
   Some of the cartoons had a distinctly political cast, partisan or
not.
   In Cathy Guisewaite's ``Cathy,'' her mom is shown listening to a
campaign speech and getting more and more agitated at the
politician's rhetoric. Finally, when he declares that he'll invest
in a strong defense to keep the country safe for the homeless, she
explodes, telling him to go to bed without dinner and announcing:
``This country doesn't need a president. It needs a mother.''
   The Arizona Republic's Steve Bensen contributed an editorial
cartoon showing a Dukakis figure sitting on a heating grate in
sidewalk in front of the White House with a shopping cart filled
with Dukakis, Jackson and other campaign signs. Above the drawing it
says: ``Cartoonist Homeless Prject. He's a painful reminder of
what's wrong with America _ abandoned, homeless, living on the
streets. Let's keep him that way.'' Below the drawing, it says,
``Vote Bush Nov. 8th.''
   But some cartoonists were able to find a touch of humor, like
Mell Lazarus of ``Momma.'' In that strip, Momma's son raids her
refrigerator because he doesn't have any food at his apartment.
Momma tells him, ``Francis, do you realize there are people in this
country who are totally homeless, while you have two of them?''
   ``If a kid tells his parents, `Hey look. All the comics are about
homeless people today,' we will at least have raised their
consciousness,'' Lazarus said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881025-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1747EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Recovery     10-25 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Recovery,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Help Pours Into Hurricane-Hit Nicaragua; Death Toll At 123</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Ruby, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua struggled Tuesday to recover
from a hurricane that killed at least 60 people and left 300,000
homeless in this Central American nation. Help poured in from a
dozen countries.
   Floods and strong winds heavily damaged crops throughout
Nicaragua.
   Hurricane Joan killed another 63 people elsewhere in Latin
America _ 23 in Costa Rica, four in Panama, 25 in Colombia and 11 in
Venezuela _ before it crossed Central America and was reborn Monday
in the Pacific as Tropical Storm Miriam.
   At 5 p.m. EDT Tuesday, an advisory from the U.S. National
Hurricane Center in Coral Gables, Fla., said the storm had weakened
to a tropical depression with maximum sustained winds of about 35
mph.
   It said the storm was centered near latitude 13.8 north,
longitude 94.3 west, or about 180 miles south-southeast of Salina
Cruz, Mexico. It said the storm was moving west at about 9 mph.
   Public Safety Minister Reynaldo Antonio Tefel, head of
Nicaragua's national emergency committee, told diplomats in Managua
that the hurricane death toll had risen by 10, to 60, in a country
already battered by seven years of civil war.
   Officials worked to restore power and water in the capital.
Public buses and trucks were pressed into service to take evacuees
home. No public transport was operating between Managua and the rest
of the country. Nationwide, only about 40 percent of public
transport was running.
   The official Voice of Nicaragua radio broadcast pleas for money
and goods for the 38,000 residents of storm-wrecked Bluefields and
other hard-hit Atlantic areas such as nearby Corn Island.
   ``Paradise in Ruins,'' the official Sandinista newspaper
Barricada said in a headline over the first photographs from the
island.
   Britain said it was giving $17,000 to Nicaragua's national
emergency committee. West Germany donated $140,000 and offered
$500,000 worth of technical assistance.
   The European Economic Community offered $100,000 to help the
homeless. The French medical group, Doctors Without Borders, said a
16-member medical team and 17 tons of supplies would arrive in
Bluefields on Wednesday.
   Spain, Austria, Norway and Switzerland and private humanitarian
groups in Europe and the United States promised to send medical
personnel and supplies.
   Relief supplies from Cuba and Mexico were already being
distributed.
   The White House said Monday it didn't expect a request for help.
When specifically asked, however, President Daniel Ortega of
Nicaragua said this country would accept U.S. hurricane aid if it
were offered without conditions.
   Ortega previously said the best aid the United States could offer
would be to stop supporting the rebels, known as Contras. The
government estimates its 7-year-old war with the Contras has caused
damage worth $12 billion.
   In Costa Rica, President Oscar Arias said the discovery of two
drowning victims near the border with Panama pushed the storm death
toll there to 23. He reckoned damage at $62 million and said the
hurricane flooded 75 towns, destroyed 1,500 homes, damaged six
hospitals and ruined banana, coffee, rice and bean crops.
   Arias told a news conference that Costa Rica, a nation of 2.5
million people, would need international help to recover.
   ``Places like Neilly, Cortes, Perez Zeledon, Palmar Norte,
Dominical and Parrita are cut off,'' he reported.
   In Guatemala, El Salvador and southern Mexico, states of alert
were canceled as Miriam moved away.
   No damage or injuries were reported in Guatemala, Mexico or El
Salvador and a two-week cycling tour resumed Tuesday in Guatemala
after being cut short by 10 miles Monday because of rain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
