<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1946EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Drinking     10-25 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Drinking,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Party Admits Sober-Up Campaign Has Faults</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party admitted Tuesday that its
3-year-old anti-alcoholism campaign has created long lines at liquor
stores and led to a moonshining business that has left sugar and
candy in short supply.
   Tass, the official news agency, said the party's policy-making
Central Committee adopted a resolution reviewing President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev's drive to sober up this nation of 284 million people.
   None of the Soviet media said when the resolution was approved.
   According to Tass, the resolution said the campaign has reduced
drinking on the job and in public places, improved family life and
cut alcohol-related crime.
   But it added that ``radical changes have not yet been achieved.''
   Sugar and candy shortages developed as moonshiners hoarded sugar
to make what they call in Russian ``samogon.''
   The anti-alcoholism campaign has caused nationwide disgruntlement
and rationing of sugar in many areas.
   Radio Moscow said the ``rush to curtail sales'' of alcohol led to
profiteering, poisonings and drug addiction.
   The Soviet press has been full of reports of these problems but
the resolution was one of the frankest official admissions of the
program's faults.
   While saying drunkenness must still be fought vigorously, the
Central Committee ordered ministries to ``stamp out alcoholic
queues,'' according to Radio Moscow.
   Lines stretching for blocks are common at liquor stores and other
shops where alcohol is sold throughout the Soviet Union.
   The reports did not say how the long lines would be eliminated
but said alcohol sales would not be permitted near schools,
factories, recreation areas or on public transport.
   The Trud labor daily said on Oct. 6 that the Kremlin plans next
year to produce more beer, wine, cognac and champagne to meet
popular demand. It said vodka and other strong drinks would continue
to be manufactured in limited quantities.
   In May 1985, Gorbachev ordered a cut in production of alcoholic
beverages, an increase in their price, an increase in the minimum
drinking age to 21 and cuts in the hours and number of stores that
could sell the products.
</TEXT>
