<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1950EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GreatPlains     10-25 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Great Plains,300</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department should value its planned
sale of a synthetic gas plant in North Dakota as worth $200 million
instead of the $600 million figure it has advertised, according to
congressional auditors.
   Even so, the sale of the Great Plains coal gasification plant
near Beulah, N.D., will still yield more than the government could
expect by operating it over the next 21 years, said analysts from
the General Accounting Office.
   In a report dated Oct. 21 and received Tuesday, GAO analysts said
the Energy Department should not count about $300 million in tax
credits that the prospective buyer, Basin Electric Power
Cooperative, has agreed to forgo.
   Bob Porter, an Energy Department spokesman, said the department
had not seen the GAO report but as a general matter believes it is
legitimate to count the value of the tax credits that will not be
used.
   ``That's cash the government would not have had; that's quite
legitimate,'' Porter said.
   Using figures to calculate the loss of future income from the
sale of the plant's gas at prices forecast by the Energy Department,
GAO calculated the sale as yielding the equivalent of $203 million
to the government.
   That is midway between the respective $284 million and $128
million figures that two consultants, Wharton Econometrics and Data
Resources Inc., calculated using their forecasts of future energy
prices.
   The value to the government of the future revenues under
government ownership would be $166 million using department
projections, $230 million using Data Resources' estimates and a loss
of $54 million using Wharton's estimates, GAO said.
   The plant cost $2.1 billion to build and was a technical success
at turning lignite into pipeline-quality gas. Its builders, though,
defaulted on $1.5 billion in government guaranteed loans, leaving
the Energy Department to pay off the loans and take over the plant.
</TEXT>
