<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Nancy     10-25 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Nancy,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Lady Wants No Exceptions to Punishment for Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY26</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street bankers who buy ``cocaine on
their lunch break'' should be punished along with drug dealers,
smugglers and Colombian narcotics barons, Nancy Reagan said Tuesday.
   The U.S. first lady told a U.N. committee on social affairs the
United States is responsible for its own drug problem and every
American drug user ``is an accomplice to every criminal act, every
murder, every terrorist attack carried out by the narcotics
syndicates.''
   ``To get serious about stopping illegal drugs ... that means
confronting all those citizens who use drugs,'' Mrs. Reagan said,
and if the United States cannot conquer the demand for narcotics
there is little hope of halting production and smuggling.
   Her advice to all drug users, from poor children to affluent
adults both here and abroad, was ``Just Say `No','' the slogan of
the anti-drug program she sponsors.
   ``It is often easier to make strong speeches about foreign drug
lords or drug smugglers than to arrest a pair of Wall Street
investment bankers buying cocaine on their lunch break,'' she said
in her address to the U.N. Third Committee on Social and
Humanitarian Affairs.
   During his eight years in office, President Reagan has advocated
a war on drug producers in Latin America and elsewhere, along with
interdiction of drugs being smuggled into the United States.
   His wife said Tuesday stopping drug use in the United States is
as important as halting the production and smuggling of illegal
narcotics.
   ``While most of the illegal drugs are imported, the drug users
are home-grown,'' she said.
   ``If we lack the will to fully mobilize the forces of law in our
own country to arrest and punish drug users, if we cannot stem the
American demand for drugs, then there will be little hope of
preventing foreign drug producers from fulfilling that demand.
   ``Drugs must remain illegal at every step in the chain.''
</TEXT>
