<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BrockAdams     10-25 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brock Adams,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Adams To Campaign Little in Light of Sexual Assault Allegations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Sen. Brock Adams, who was accused by an aide
of sexually assaulting her, was back on the campaign trail for
fellow Democrats Tuesday, but is limiting appearances so he doesn't
hurt their chances, an assistant said.
   ``We are aware there are people out there who want to exploit the
situation and we don't want to play into their hands,'' said Steve
Elmendorf, Adams' executive assistant.
   Prosecutors have declined to charge Adams, D-Wash., with any
crimes because of a lack of physical evidence and problems with the
credibility of Kari Tupper, 26, the woman who accused him, police
records have shown.
   Tupper, a former secretary for the House Aging Committee who now
lives in Seattle, claimed that Adams drugged her by putting
something in her drink at his home on March 27, 1987, and then took
her to bed.
   Adams accused Ms. Tupper, whose parents had been close friends of
his, of trying to blackmail him for $400,000 in ``hush money.''
Adams denied making any sexual advances, but said he made a mistake
letting the woman stay at his home.
   Elmendorf said no candidates have asked Adams to stay away, but
that Adams doesn't want to put them in an uncomfortable situation.
   ``Brock is realistic and he knows what the situation is,'' said
Elmendorf. ``His overriding interest is to elect Democrats from one
end of the ticket to the other, and to allow extraneous side issues
to become part of the campaign is in no one's interest. We won't let
it happen.''
   Adams has declined to join a six-city tour planned by Democratic
candidates.
   Adams, who was transportation secretary under President Carter,
in 1986 unseated Republican Slade Gorton, who is making a comeback
bid for the Senate seat being vacated by Republican Dan Evans.
Gorton's race against Rep. Mike Lowry is one of the closest in the
country, according to recent polls.
</TEXT>
