<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia     10-25 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Says Nine Police, Four Election Officials Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas dynamited a bus
carrying police and election officials in the remote Andes mountains
of northwest Colombia Tuesday, killing 13 people and wounding 14,
officials reported.
   The casualties brought to 51 the number of people killed in
guerrilla attacks since Sunday night.
   An added blow to the government was the collapse of negotiations
aimed at averting a one-day general strike set for Thursday.
   The Simon Bolivar Front, an umbrella group for all six leftist
rebel factions in Colombia, urged President Virgilio Barco to start
peace talks with the guerrillas.
   Cesar Gaviria, minister of government, issued a statement Tuesday
said the proposal was made in a message sent to the president a day
earlier.
   Guerrillas, who support the strike call, blew up the bus Tuesday
morning near Peque, a town of 7,000 people about 200 miles northwest
of the capital of Bogota.
   The guerrillas set off dynamite in the road as the bus was going
by, the army's 4th Brigade said in a communique from its
headquarters in Medellin.
   An election for mayor was held last Sunday in Peque. The police
had been guarding the town against guerrilla attack and the election
officials had supervised voting there.
   Results of the election were not yet known.
   The military communique said nine policemen and four civilian
election officials were killed and 12 policemen and two election
officials wounded in the dynamating.
   Talks broke off Monday between labor unions and government
officials. Little hope was seen of avoiding the general strike,
Gaviria said in the statement.
   The unions want pay increases, a price freeze and an end to death
squad attacks that have killed 180 union members in the last two
years.
   The unions are the Workers' Unitary Central, the General
Confederation of Labor and the Colombian Confederation of Workers.
   The unions, with about 800,000 members, represent about 10
percent of the work force in this nation of 30 million people.
   All schools and many businesses and transport companies close
during general strikes in fear of violence.
   The Defense Ministry said last week it discovered guerrilla plans
to provoke violence during the strike.
   Guerrillas in a speeding car threw a bomb Tuesday at the offices
of a bus company in Medellin, but no one was hurt, a national police
communique said.
</TEXT>
