<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AfghanFighting     10-25 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan Fighting,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Government Claims U.S., ``Arab'' Advisers Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan's Soviet-backed government
claimed that 69 American and ``Arabian'' advisers were killed
Tuesday as they helped Islamic guerrillas in the eastern part of the
country.
   A half-hour later, it lowered the number to six.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman in Islamabad called the reports
``unbelievable'' and ``ridiculous.''
   The official Afghan radio also announced that Kabul authorities
decided to release two West German medical personnel _ Dr. Benno
Spliet and nurse Lea Hochstalt _ captured on Sept. 8 after treating
civilian war wounded.
   The radio said in its main 7:30 p.m. newscast that government
security forces inflicted heavy losses on ``criminals,'' its term
for Mujahedeen fighters, in Paktia province which borders Pakistan.
   It said it received a report Tuesday that 43 ``criminals'' were
killed and 24 wounded.
   ``The report adds that 69 American and Arabian advisers who had a
direct hand in the criminals' activities and are helping the
criminals also were killed today,'' according to the broadcast.
   In the next broadcast a half-hour later, it revised the number to
six without explanation.
   It did not specify the nationality of the Arabs. Afghanistan's
official news media began claiming the death and capture of
Americans in Afghan territory on Oct. 16.
   The United States, which backs the Mujahedeen, denies it has any
U.S. military personnel in Afghanistan.
   ``No, I wouldn't believe the reports at all,'' said an embassy
spokesman, speaking on condition his name not be used. ``It's
unbelievable. It's a ridiculous allegation.''
   U.S. and other Western diplomats said earlier Tuesday that the
communists' claims of killing and capturing U.S. advisers was false
propaganda aimed at inflating the communists' image.
   Afghanistan's official news agency, Bakhtar, and national
television reported three ``American advisers'' were killed and four
captured inside the country between Oct. 16-22. The Soviet news
agency Tass ran the stories later.
   U.S. embassies in Kabul and Islamabad challenged the Afghans for
proof.
   ``Since there are no U.S. advisers whatsoever in Afghanistan, all
of these stories are fabrications,'' the embassy in Islamabad stated
Tuesday.
   U.S. arming and training of Mujahedeen guerrillas on Pakistani
soil is well documented but Washington refuses to discuss details.
It has always denied the presence of U.S. military personnel in
Afghanistan itself.
   Western diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
series of Afghan reports appeared to be propaganda from a government
whose security is treatened by increasing rebel pressure.
   About half of more than 100,000 Soviet troops withdrew from
Afghanistan between May 15 and Aug. 15 under a U.N.-sponsored accord
signed last April. The rest are to be out by next Feb. 15.
   Mujahedeen claimed the capture of five of about 30 provincial
capitals since May and the siege of others. Kabul suffers rocket
attacks almost daily.
   Najib, head of state and leader of the ruling People's Democratic
Party of Afghanistan, has issued repeated appeals for peace talks
and national reconciliation.
</TEXT>
