<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Egypt     10-25 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Egypt,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitterrand Noncommittal on Palestinian State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISMAILIYA, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt and France held their second summit
in less than a month Tuesday and discussed the Palestinian problem,
but President Francois Mitterrand of France was noncommittal on an
independent state.
   Egypt's official Middle East News Agency carried some of the
comments Mitterrand and President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt made to
reporters before the French leader left for home. Mitterrand arrived
earlier in the day.
   Asked whether France would accept the idea of a Palestinian state
based on U.N. Resolution 181, Mitterrand replied: ``I think we
should know much more about this subject before making statements.''
   Mubarak cautioned leaders of the Palestine Liberation
Organization against concentrating on Resolution 181 as the key to
legitimatizing a Palestinian state established in Israeli-occupied
Arab territories.
   ``If we talk about Resolution 181, and we concentrate on it only,
this will arouse Israeli suspicion,'' he said, and added about any
such state: ``We must know the borders, or else the Israelis will
fear that it is a state engulfing the whole of Israel and matters
will get more complicated.''
   Resolution 181, passed in 1947 by the General Assembly, called
for division of Palestine into Arab and Jewish states and the
internationalization of Jeruslaem. Israel was created in 1948.
   Yasser Arafat's PLO has been studying possible plans for the
future of Palestinians, including three choices: declaration of an
independent Palestinian state in the Israeli-occupied territories,
declaration of a provisional government or a combination of the two.
   Israel captured West Bank and Gaza Strip, now home to about 1.5
million Palestinians, from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East
war. Egypt, the only Arab nation ever to do so, signed a peace
treaty with Israel in 1979.
   Mubarak and Mitterrand last conferred in Paris on Sept. 27,
during a European tour by the Egyptian president that included
visits to Britain, West Germany and Yugoslavia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
