<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 2018EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MyersonTrial     10-25 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Myerson Trial,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Tries to Shake Witness's Story</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief witness against Bess Myerson admitted
Tuesday that there were numerous differences between her previous
sworn statements and what she has told the jury at the former Miss
America's divorce-fixing trial.
   Miss Myerson's attorney got Sukhreet Gabel to concede that 10
things she told the jury last week about a conversation she had with
Miss Myerson in 1986 were not in a detailed memo she wrote shortly
after the meeting.
   Ms. Gabel is the daughter of former state Supreme Court Justice
Hortense Gabel, 75, who is on trial with Miss Myerson, 64, and Miss
Myerson's boyfriend, Carl ``Andy'' Capasso, 43.
   They are charged with conspiracy, mail fraud and bribe-related
charges.
   In later testimony, Ms. Gabel said her mother once described Miss
Myerson as ``a delightful cuckoo.''
   Miss Myerson, once the city's cultural affairs commissioner, is
accused of giving Ms. Gabel, 39, a $19,000-a-year city job to
influence her mother's decisions in Capasso's divorce.
   Under questioning by the prosecution last week, Ms. Gabel
testified that while a grand jury was investigating the
circumstances of how she got her job, Miss Myerson appeared at her
apartment, invited her for a walk and told her: ``Keep your mouth
shut.''
   Prosecutors charge that Miss Myerson obstructed justice in
allegedly trying to keep Ms. Gabel from testifying truthfully to the
grand jury.
   But Myerson attorney Frederick Hafetz underscored numerous
inconsistencies in Ms. Gabel's most damaging testimony against Miss
Myerson.
   In a sworn statement she gave last year, Ms. Gabel, who left the
Department of Cultural Affairs in 1984, said Miss Myerson's
appearance at her apartment on June 18, 1986, was ``out of the
blue'' and added: ``I didn't want to have anything to do with her.''
   But Hafetz noted that a week before the night Ms. Gabel said she
talked with her old boss, she had written Miss Myerson seeking a
recommendation to law school.
   When Hafetz asked if that was a change from her testimony that
she didn't want to have anything to do with Miss Myerson, the
witness said, ``No,'' and then blurted out, ``I would characterize
it as politics makes strange bedfellows.''
   U.S. District Judge John Keenan warned Ms. Gabel against
volunteering information under oath.
   ``Stop volunteering answers,'' he lectured. ``If you do it one
more time, I'm going to get a little angry. Now stop it!''
   Hafetz also got Ms. Gabel to admit that she wrote a detailed memo
to her lawyer shortly after the alleged walk and talk with Miss
Myerson but 10 of the statements she attributed to Miss Myerson in
her trial testimony such as: ``You can make a lot of trouble;''
``We've got to get our stories straight,'' and ``You've got to keep
your mouth shut'' were not included in the memo.
   At the time she submitted the memo, Ms. Gabel conceded, she told
her lawyer that she had not ``left out anything substantive.''
   And Ms. Gabel admitted that in an interview with defense lawyers
before the trial she said, ``There was no attempt by Miss Myerson to
subvert governmental processes'' and agreed that Miss Myerson did
not ask her to change her memory.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
