<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-25 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most of Nation Dry, With Rain, Snow Around Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the nation enjoyed dry and seasonal weather Tuesday
except the Great Lakes region, where a cold front produced clouds,
rain and scattered snow showers.
   West and southwest winds off Lake Erie dumped almost
three-quarters of an inch of rain on Buffalo, N.Y.
   Four to 6 inches of snow fell along the western tip of Michigan
and across the border in Hurley, Wis. Snow showers also were
reported in the Grand Rapids and Muskegon areas of Michigan. Mixed
rain and snow showers occurred in northwest Pennsylvania and lower
Michigan.
   Gale warnings were in effect for lakes Erie and Ontario. Lake
snow advisories were posted for portions of western New York.
   Patches of dense fog at mid-day covered portions of the
California coast, and visibilities were below a mile in fog in the
Willamette Valley of Oregon.
   Clear skies prevailed from Virginia to Florida and Alabama. Skies
were also bright and sunny over Oklahoma, northwest Texas, New
Mexico and the desert Southwest.
   Early afternoon temperatures were in the 30s and 40s from New
York state and northern Pennsylvania across the Great Lakes region
and Minnesota to the Northern Plains.
   Readings in the 70s were posted across the Gulf Coastal states
and the lower Mississippi Valley. Readings were in the 80s in Texas
with a few locations in the lower Rio Grande Valley near 90 degrees.
Temperatures were also in the 80s to near 90 degrees in the desert
Southwest with 70s across interior valleys of California.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 28
degrees at Bemidji, Minn., and Park Rapids, Minn., to 92 degrees at
Palm Springs, Calif. The low in the nation Tuesday morning was 8
degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   The forecast for Wednesday called for rain and snow showers to
continue near the Canadian border from Maine to Michigan. Widely
scattered showers were expected from the southern Appalachians to
eastern North Carolina. Showers were also forecast in Mississippi
and southern Alabama, with scattered showers and thunderstorms
across Louisiana and eastern Texas. Widely scattered showers were to
develop over the mountains of western Montana, northern Idaho and
eastern Washington.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 40s and 50s from the
northern and middle Atlantic Coastal states across the Appalachians,
the Ohio Valley, the southern Great Lakes and the middle Mississippi
Valley to North Dakota. Highs in the 30s were forecast over the
northern Great Lakes. Florida, the southern half of Texas and
interior valleys of California could expect readings in the 80s, and
temperatures from 85 to 95 degrees were predicted in the desert
Southwest.
</TEXT>
