<HEAD>Grammy-Winning Country Star Waylon Jennings Hospitalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSTIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grammy-winning country music singer Waylon
Jennings was hospitalized after he complained of chest pains during
a performance, and tests performed Tuesday ruled out a heart attack,
a spokeswoman said.
   ``He's strong as an ox. He's fine, resting well and in good
spirits,'' Marylou Hyatt said from Jennings' office in Nashville,
Tenn.
   ``The best news is the heart attack was ruled out,'' she said.
   Jennings became ill during the first of two performances Monday
night at a club in nearby Santa Ana, 30 miles south of downtown Los
Angeles.
   ``He was unable to perform due to chest pains and he had a hard
time breathing,'' said Dino Lint, manager of the Crazy Horse Saloon.
   Jennings was taken to the cardiac care unit at Health Care
Medical Center and later transferred to an undisclosed location.
   Jennings, whose work on 13 million-selling albums has won him two
Grammy Awards and four Country Music Association Awards, is probably
best known for his duet with Willie Nelson on ``Mamas Don't Let Your
Babies Grow Up to Be Cowboys.''
   He also recorded ``Ladies Love Outlaws,'' ``Amanda'' and the
theme song for the television show ``The Dukes of Hazzard.''
