<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 2121EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0625 10-25 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0625,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-Age Girl Killed in Clash With Troops, 15 Wounded</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-4 with two grafs UPDATING injury toll, army
confirming three Palestinians wounded; PICK up 5th pvs: The dead
girl... ADDS 1 graf with high school in east Jerusalem closed for
one week because of protest.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops opened fire Tuesday on
stone-throwing Palestinian demonstrators in the occupied Gaza Strip,
killing a 14-year-old girl, hospital officials said.
   The driver of an Israeli oil tanker fired into a crowded Gaza
City vegetable market and wounded three Palestinians after his
vehicle was hit by a firebomb, according to Arab witnesses. They
said the bomb hit a tire and did not cause serious damage.
   Another 16 Palestinians were wounded in clashes between troops
and demonstrators in seven towns and refugee camps in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip, Arab hospital officials said.
   The army confirmed three wounded in the occupied lands and said
it was checking the other casualty reports.
   The dead girl was identified as Manal Samour of the Shati refugee
camp on the edge of Gaza City. She was dead on arrival at the city's
Ahli Arab Hospital with a single bullet wound in the chest, said the
hospital officials, who insisted on anonymity.
   Doctors said the family removed the body for immediate burial.
   Witnesses in Shati said the girl apparently was struck when
soldiers fired on demonstrators from a rooftop. The witnesses,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said anti-Israeli protests
erupted in the camp after news of the girl's death spread. The camp
later was put under curfew, witnesses said.
   An army spokesman said he was checking the report of the girl's
death and the curfew.
   The death raised to 303 the number of Palestinians killed since
the start of the uprising against Israeli rule in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip on Dec. 8. Six Israelis also have died.
   Also Tuesday, an army spokesman confirmed that soldiers fatally
shot a 17-year-old Palestinian during a clash Monday in the Faraa
refugee camp near Nablus.
   The spokesman said troops fired rubber bullets after being
attacked by youths throwing bottles and rocks. ``The soldiers found
their lives endangered, and an officer fired one bullet which hit
one of the youths. He died later,'' the spokesman said.
   In the incident involving the tanker driver, three Palestinians
were wounded, including a 50-year-old Palestinian hit in the chest,
Arab witnesses said. They said soldiers rushed to the scene, but
fired only in the air to disperse the crowd.
   In Jerusalem, two people were injured slightly when the buses in
which they were riding were struck with stones, police said.
   Israel's Itim news agency reported authorities shut down the
Rashidiyeh high school in Arab east Jerusalem until Oct. 31 because
of a demonstration Tuesday by students protesting the suspensions of
58 classmates. It said the the 58 were suspended because they
repeatedly skipped classes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
