<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-WesternSahara     10-25 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Western Sahara,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Panel Calls For Direct Peace Talks Between Morocco and
Polisario</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. decolonization committee on
Tuesday called on Morocco and the Polisario independence movement to
start direct peace talks to settle their war for sovereignty over
the Western Sahara.
   The committee, officially known as the Fourth Committee, voted
87-0 with 53 abstentions in favor of the motion sponsored by
Algeria, an ally of the Marxist-led Polisario movement.
   Polisario has been fighting for independence for the former
Spanish colony since 1975, when the colonial administration left and
Moroccan troops and settlers took over the sparsely populated,
110,000-square-mile territory in northwest Africa.
   Morocco opposes direct talks with Polisario, saying that
negotiating with the movement as an equal before the Saharans have
chosen them as their representative would grant Poliario a status
they have not earned.
   Most of the sponsors of Tuesday's motion were socialist and
developing nations. Spain voted in favor of the motion; the United
States, Britain, France, West Germany and most other Western nations
abstained. Morocco did not vote.
   The motion calls on Morocco and Polisario to begin direct
negotiations for a cease-fire and for holding a referendum on
seld-determination for the Saharan people.
   It also welcomed the acceptance by both sides in principle of
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar's proposal that they honor
a truce and hold the referendum.
   Polisario spokesmen say that so far in indirect talks through the
secretary-general, the two parties have only agreed on the wording
of the referendum, which will be for either independence or
affiliation with Morocco, and that only people counted as Saharans
in the last colonial census in 1974 will be eligible to vote.
   That census put the population at 76,000.
   The United Nations plans to send about 2,000 peacekeeping troops
to Western Sahara to monitor the referendum and see that Moroccan
troops and Polisario fighters remain in their barracks and camps.
   Polisario says it has about 7,000 fighters in Western Sahara, and
that Morocco has 185,000 soldiers there. The independence movement
says that all except 7,000 Moroccan troops should withdraw to their
homeland before the referendum is conducted.
</TEXT>
