<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen-Homeless, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0648,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Office Calm as Teen Protesters Camp on Rug</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with arrests.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten demonstrators for the homeless were
arrested Tuesday and charged with unlawful entry after staging a
sit-in in the office of Democratic vice presidential candidate Lloyd
Bentsen, Capitol police said.
   The 10, all from Amherst, Mass., were among a group ranging in
number from 15 to 25 who entered the offices at noon. Police said
the demonstrators refused to leave after meeting with Bentsen's
staff but weren't arrested until the close of business.
   Bentsen aides declined to call police to remove the peaceable
demonstrators, most of whom appeared to be in their mid-teens.
   The sit-in marked the latest in a series of Capitol Hill
demonstrations staged by the Washington-based Community for Creative
Nonviolence in a drive that began Sept. 26 and apparently is slated
to continue through election eve.
   The group, whose leader Mitch Snyder has fought a duel with the
Reagan administration over homeless aid, is demanding $25 billion in
housing funds.
   Capitol police spokesman Dan Nichols said 171 people have been
arrested thus far in the daily demonstrations.
   Bentsen spokesman Chris Peacock said the demonstrators initially
asked to speak with the Texas senator but were told he was on the
campaign trail.
   Peacock said Bentsen's legislative aide, Ray Bonilla, did chat
with them about housing problems and what could be done to help the
homeless.
   Other lawmakers whose offices have been visited, including
Republican vice presidential candidate Dan Quayle, have had police
remove the demonstrators within minutes of their arrival.
   Those arrested were being held overnight at the District of
Columbia jail and faced arraigment Wednesday in Superior Court. The
charge of unlawful entry carries a maximum penalty of six months in
jail and a $500 fine.
