<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ZZZZBest     10-25 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ZZZZ Best,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Barry Minkow Takes Stand In Securities Fraud Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A one-time whiz kid of carpet cleaning took
the witness stand in his securities fraud trial Tuesday and admitted
he manipulated stocks and defrauded investors in a
multimillion-dollar swindle.
   Barry Minkow, 22, assuming an embarrassed, shy demeanor, also
began laying out for jurors a defense of duress in which he claims
that organized crime figures dictated his every move.
   Minkow told jurors he was threatened with broken limbs or death
if he didn't run his business according to the dictates of two men _
one who he said tried to sexually molest him and the other ``a
Nazi'' who defamed Minkow's Jewish heritage.
   ``I felt like I was taking money from the devil,'' he said of his
alliance with the second man.
   Minkow described how he came under the sway of the first man,
Daniel Krowpman, a 230-pound weight lifter, tool salesman and
reputed loan shark who befriended Minkow at a gym where he exercised
in his early teens.
   ``He was my idol,'' said Minkow. ``He was everything because he
had money; he had build. He had everything I didn't have. ... He was
nice to me. He was like the father I never had. I loved him.''
   But he indicated Krowpman had a cruel side that surfaced when he
would arrive at the gym with a 6-foot-9, 330-pound weight lifter he
introduced as ``Big Steve.''
   ``When him and Steve were together it was like night and day,''
said Minkow. ``They would tease me about being puny and not able to
lift weights. They would throw me in the pool with my clothes on. It
wasn't the same.''
   Later, he said, Krowpman gave him $1,600 to set up his carpet
cleaning business but began demanding payments of $200 a month plus
50 per cent of the profits.
   He also blurted out that Krowpman once tried to molest him and
said he began paying him ``after the attempted rape.''
   Minkow's lawyer has said Minkow, who launched his ZZZZ Best
carpet cleaning company at 16 in his parents garage, was beaten and
threatened by mobsters who used him to perpetuate a $25 million
stock fraud.
   But prosecutors have portrayed Minkow as a shrewd con man who
bilked investors for his own benefit, selling them on the future of
a business that for the most part did not exist.
   Minkow is charged with 57 counts of securities fraud, credit card
fraud and mail fraud. Ten of his 12 co-defendants, including
Krowpman, have pleaded guilty to various charges related to the ZZZZ
Best operation. Accountant Norman Rothberg is on trial with Minkow,
accused of taking a bribe to cover up ZZZZ Best's frauds.
   The husky, dark-haired Minkow appeared nervous in his initial
moments on the stand. As his lawyer, David Kenner, asked him to
admit he had done the acts charged in the indictment, there were
long pauses and he bowed his head as if ashamed before he answered.
   Asked if he had made false claims for his business, Minkow
replied softly: ``It's true. I made those claims and they were all
lies.''
   The case is being heard by U.S. District Judge Dickran Tavrizian.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
