<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 2312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Hostages     10-25 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Hostages,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hostage Photos Seized in Italy All Copies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two photographs of U.S. hostages found in the
luggage of a Lebanese woman at Milan's airport are reproductions,
police said Tuesday.
   U.S. officials said they doubted that photos and documents
carried by the woman were part of an effort to free Americans held
in Lebanon.
   ``It might be prudent to view this with a certain degree of
skepticism,'' said one American official, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Police released a third photo the woman was carrying, saying it
also was a reproduction. They could not identify the subject, a
thin-faced man with a dark, curly beard. The other two photos were
of hostages Terry Anderson and Alann Steen.
   Authorities said the woman was to give the pictures and several
documents _ including a letter bearing Steen's name _ to Aldo
Anghessa, an Italian arms trader with links to Swiss and Italian
intelligence agencies.
   He was to deliver them to a third party, but authorities would
not say who that might be.
   The woman, identified as Aline Ibrahim Rizkallah, 36, was
arrested at Milan's Linate Airport last Thursday after arriving from
Beirut. Police reported also finding $1,000 in counterfeit U.S.
bills and 1.7 ounces of heroin on her.
   U.S. officials, including an FBI representative, were en route to
Milan to investigate.
   The U.S. official, who saw a photocopy of the letter, said it was
``not in normal English that a native English-speaker would use,''
but said that did not necessarily mean it was a fake.
   Achille Serra, head of the anti-terrorism unit of Milan's police,
told reporters that if the handwriting turns out not to be Steen's,
``things change a lot. We would be talking about a fraud.''
   It was not clear who would have been the target of a possible
swindle.
   The photo of Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The
Associated Press, appeared to be a copy of one issued in August by
the pro-Iranian Islamic Jihad. The picture of Steen, who is believed
held by Islamic Jihad for the Liberation of Palestine, was the same
as one released last February.
   The woman carried letters for Anghessa and an Italian prisoner in
Massa, Italy, Serra said. Both were in coded Italian which police
were trying to decipher, he said.
   The woman, apparently a courier, said she was to receive about
$4,000 from Anghessa, police said. He denied it.
   Serra said police had identified the man who supplied the woman
with the pictures and documents and were considering going to
Lebanon to question him.
   Islamic Jihad denied Monday it was connected with the woman.
   Anderson and Steen are among nine Americans held by pro-Iranian
extremist factions linked to Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   Anderson was seized in Beirut on March 16, 1985.
   Steen, of Boston, was kidnapped Jan. 24, 1987 at Beirut
University College, where he taught.
   Three Britons, and Irishman and an Italian also are missing and
believed held hostage in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
