<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Barbie     10-25 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Barbie,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Nazi Questioned By West German Authorities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYON, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Nazi SS officer Klaus Barbie, once
known as the ``Butcher of Lyon,'' was questioned Tuesday by West
German authorities in connection with an investigation of a German
count accused of war crimes.
   Barbie, the onetime Gestapo chief of Lyon, was sentenced to life
imprisonment on July 4, 1987 for crimes against humanity.
   West German investigating judges Host Shneider, Josef Jansen and
Martin Licksett questioned Barbie in his cell at St. Josephs prison
about the World War II activities of Count Leonhard von Korff.
   Von Korff served as a ministerial counselor in Bonn until French
Nazi- hunter Serge Klarfeld unmasked him as the former Gestapo chief
in the Chalons-sur-Marne region of northeastern France during the
Nazi occupation.
   The West Germans are looking into allegations that von Korff
deported 185 Jews to Drancy transit camp near Paris, from which they
were then sent to Nazi death camps.
   A French judge and Barbie's lawyer, Jacques Verges, accompanied
the judges in their interview.
</TEXT>
