<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MedellinIndictment     10-25 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medellin Indictment,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reputed Colombian Drug Leader Indicted In U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five men, including one believed to be a leader
in a multibillion-dollar Colombian drug cartel, were indicted
Tuesday on charges they conspired to import more than a ton of
cocaine a week.
   A federal grand jury in Brooklyn issued the indictment despite
reported death threats, officials said.
   Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha and four alleged underlings in the
Medellin cartel were charged with conspiring with undercover agents,
who posed as brokers, to import 2,200 pounds of cocaine every eight
days into the New York area, authorities said.
   Since Gacha, 47, lives in Colombia, federal authorities said his
prosecution is unlikely because there is no extradition treaty
between the United States and Colombia.
   ``Only by taking off the leadership of these cartels can we hope
to put a crimp into these organizations,'' said U.S. Attorney Andrew
Maloney.
   Maloney said he was optimistic that an extradition treaty between
the two countries would be negotiated in the future so Gacha could
be brought to New York to face the charges.
   Three of the defendants, who were identified as employees of the
cartel's New York distribution operation, were arrested in July when
federal agents seized 1,350 pounds of cocaine near La Guardia
Airport, the first shipment in the sting operation.
   The fifth defendant, Oscar Vegas, who was identified as a
lieutenant in the Medellin cartel, also lives in Colombia and
remains unapprehended.
   The men were charged with operating a continuing criminal
enterprise, conspiracy to import cocaine and conspiracy to
distribute cocaine.
   The criminal enterprise and the possession charges carry a
maximum penalty of up to life in prison upon conviction. The
defendants could be fined up to $6 million.
   Gacha also was named Tuesday in a separate indictment filed in
Miami's federal court that charged him and six others with one count
of conspiracy to import cocaine.
   He was identified as one of three leaders of the cartel, which is
named for the Colombian city in which it is based.
   Robert Stutman, the head of the federal Drug Enforcement
Administration's New York office, described Gacha as ``the most
active member'' of the Medellin cartel, which he said dominates the
cocaine market in Miami, Los Angeles and several European cities.
   Stutman said his agency had received intelligence reports from
Colombia that Gacha had issued death threats against Stutman, Mayor
Edward I. Koch and other law enforcement officials for actions taken
against the Medellin organization.
   ``The more they threaten, the more we'll go after them,'' Stutman
said.
</TEXT>
