<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 4-6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Charles Haid Plays Australian Tunnel Digger in `Great Escape'</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Haid's longtime hobby of doing accents
came in handy when he was cast as an Australian soldier in the NBC
miniseries ``The Great Escape: Return With a Vengeance.''
   He plays Sgt. Mac MacKenzie in the four-hour, two-part series
that is a sequel to the blockbuster 1963 movie about the true story
of a huge escape of Allied airmen from a German prisoner-of-war camp
in World War II.
   ``He's a combination of a couple of guys,'' said Haid. ``Mostly a
Scot, who's still alive but was conveniently changed to an Aussie
for television. My character was a tunnel digger. Moles, they called
them.
   ``We filmed in Yugoslavia with a lot of British actors. My
biggest challenge was fitting in with their dialects. My hobby is
doing accents. I've been fascinated by accents since I was a kid. I
have a kind of parrot ear. Mostly what I did was listen to tapes.
Then all of a sudden,'' slipping into an Australian accent, ``you're
talkin' like that.''
   ``The Great Escape'' sequel will be broadcast by NBC on Sunday
and Monday, Nov. 6-7.
   Besides Haid, who starred as Officer Andy Renko for seven years
on ``Hill Street Blues,'' the movie also features Christopher Reeved Fields
to about
29.6 percent.
   Minorco issued a statement saying it was considering its position
in the light of the British government's decision.
   Trade Secretary Lord Young asked the monopolies commission to
report to him within the three months.
   The British investigation will center on the proposed takeover's
impact on strategic metals, in particular titanium and zircon, a
spokesman at the Department of Trade and Industry said.
   Titanium, a metal largely used as a whitener in paints, also is
used in jet engines, a Consolidated Gold Fields metallurgist said.
Zircon is mainly used as a refracting agent in glass and steel
furnaces, but is also a critical substance in nuclear submarines and
power plants, and in rocket nose cones, he said.
   Consolidated Gold Fields says that Australian-based Renison
Goldfields Consolidated Ltd., in which it has a 49 percent stake, is
the world's largest producer of mineral sands that serve as raw
materials for titanium and zircon.
   Consolidated Gold Fields' shares plummeted on news of the
investigation, while Minorco's shares rose.
</TEXT>
