<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   10-25 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0577</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. says it plans to
mount a record $20.28 billion tender offer for RJR Nabisco Inc.
   Monday's announcement by Kohlberg Kravis came four days after
Nabisco's managers stunned Wall Street by saying they were
considering offering $17 billion to buy the company from
stockholders.
   Kohlberg Kravis said it would offer $90 a share in cash for
about 87 percent of RJR Nabisco's 225.3 million outstanding shares
and would exchange securities valued at the same amount for the
remainder of the company's stock.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board Options Exchange says it is
investigating a sharp rise in trading of RJR Nabisco Inc. stock
options in the two days prior to the company's announcement that
management was considering making a $17 billion offer to take the
company private.
   CBOE spokesman Warren Moulds said Monday that the average daily
trading volume in RJR Nabisco options in September was 1,039
contracts.
   Last Tuesday, 4,079 contracts were traded, he said; on
Wednesday, the day preceding the announcement, 7,050 contracts were
traded.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kraft Inc. says it will give advance notice if
it decides to proceed with any part of its $13.6 billion defensive
restructuring without the approval of its directors and
shareholders.
   Kraft's statement in federal court in Chicago on Monday marked a
victory for the company pursuing Kraft, Philip Morris Cos. Inc.,
which had sought a temporary restraining order requiring three
days' notice of any restructuring moves.
   U.S. District Judge James B. Moran rejected Philip Morris's
request for a temporary restraining order, saying it was unneeded
because of Kraft's agreement to give advance notice to the court.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farley Inc., parent of the Fruit of the Loom
underwear company, has announced a $1.4 billion takeover bid for
West Point-Pepperell Inc., a Georgia-based maker of sheets and
towels.
   Farley, one of the nation's largest privately-owned
conglomerates, said Monday it would pay $48 a share in cash for
each of Pepperell's 29.4 million outstanding shares, but industry
analysts characterized the bid as low.
   Pepperell advised its stockholders not to take any action on the
offer until its board of directors reviewed Farley's bid and made a
recommendation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the best known names in household
appliances, Maytag and Hoover, will soon be under one roof
following the $1 billion merger of Maytag Corp. and Chicago Pacific
Corp.
   Maytag announced Monday it plans to use the European connections
of Hoover to power its own sales overseas.
   Investors initially drove Maytag's value down at the news of the
deal, but several analysts praised the combination as a long-term
plus for the company.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the United Food & Commercial
Workers Union have sued John Morrell & Co. for $35 million, seeking
unpaid wages and overtime over the past three years.
   Monday's federal court filing said Morrell, the nation's
fifth-largest meatpacker, failed to pay production workers for
about 20 to 30 minutes of time spent each day putting on, taking
off and cleaning required safety equipment at its plants in Sioux
City, Sioux Falls, S.D., and Arkansas City, Kan.
   The suit could affect about 5,000 workers at Morrell plants, the
union said.
</TEXT>
