<DOCNO> AP881025-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 0031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-RJRNabisco Bjt   10-25 0696</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-RJR Nabisco, Bjt,0724</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kohlberg Makes Stunning $20.28 Billion Bid for RJR Nabisco</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fevered pitch of Wall Street's bidding for
giant food companies could go even higher following Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts & Co.'s record $20.28 billion offer for RJR Nabisco Inc.
   Kohlberg Kravis' announcement Monday of a $90-a-share leveraged
buyout offer for RJR Nabisco came four days after Nabisco's
management said it might offer $17 billion, or $75 a share, to buy
the company from stockholders.
   ``Our offer is a better one,'' stated Henry Kravis, a partner in
the New York-based investment firm.
   Securities analysts said the Kohlberg Kravis offer was more in
line with Nabisco's worth than the proposal presented by
management, and say higher offers still may emerge.
   ``There's a possibility this will be the final bid, but it could
go as high as $100,'' said Jay Nelson, an analyst with Brown
Brothers Harriman Inc. ``It's feasible, but not at all certain.''
   New York-based Kohlberg Kravis said it would offer $90 a share
in cash for about 87 percent of RJR Nabisco's 225.3 million
outstanding shares, and would exchange securities valued at the
same amount for the rest of the company's stock.
   The offer was was conditioned on support from Nabisco's board.
   The investment firm, known for its big, successful leveraged
buyout bids, said it would begin the tender offer formally later
this week. At more than $20 billion, the offer would surpass the
biggest corporate acquisition of any type, the $13.4 billion
purchase of Gulf Corp. by Chevron Corp. in 1984.
   There was no comment from RJR Nabisco or the managers who on
Thursday announced they were considering a $75-a-share cash bid for
the food and tobacco company.
   On Wall Street, investors reacted enthusastically to Kohlberg
Kravis's offer. Nabisco stock shot up $7.25 a share to $84 in New
York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   Ronald B. Morrow, who tracks Nabisco for the investment firm
Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co., said he doubted the management
group, led by Nabisco President F. Ross Johnson, would be disturbed
by the Kohlberg Kravis bid.
   ``They were definitely inviting offers,'' he said.
   Clinton Mayer, an analyst with Bear Stearns & Co. Inc., said of
the Johnson group, ``They're in a no-lose situation.''
   ``I think if they could buy at $75, they would have been
happy,'' Mayer said, but also said ``they would be very happy if
someone else bid a higher price.''
   Kohlberg Kravis had been expected to enter the whirlwind of bids
for food companies that began Oct. 4 with a $5.23 billion bid for
Pillsbury Co. by Grand Metropolitan PLC, a British company.
   But many thought the investment firm was considering a bid for
Kraft Inc., which late Sunday rejected a more than $11 billion bid
from Philip Morris Cos. Inc. and announced its own $13.59 billion
recapitalization plan.
   A successful buyout of Nabisco would be the biggest leveraged
buyout of an American corporation by far. The largest LBO was
Kohlberg Kravis' $6.1 billion buyout of Beatrice Cos. in 1986.
   In a leveraged buyout, a company is acquired mainly with
borrowed funds that are repaid either with company revenue or money
raised by selling parts of the operation.
   Henry Kravis, a partner in the investment firm, said in a
statement his company had raised an equity pool of $5.6 billion for
buyouts. Experts say that amount could be used to ``leverage'' as
much as $40 billion in loans for acquisitions.
   Kohlberg Kravis also is leading a group attempting to acquire
the publishing giant Macmillan Inc. for $2.5 billion. British
publisher Robert Maxwell, who also seeks to buy Macmillan, is
fighting that bid in a Delaware court.
   The investment firm recently withdrew a $5.03 billion bid for
supermarket operator Kroger Co. after Kroger's board rejected the
offer in favor of a financial restructuring.
   Past Kohlberg leveraged buyouts also include the 1986 purchase
of Safeway Stores Inc. for $4.2 billion, the 1987 buyout of
Owens-Illinois Inc. for $3.7 billion, the purchase of Storer
Communications Inc. for $2.5 billion in 1985, and the buyout of
Stop & Shop Cos. earlier this year for $1.23 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
