<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Resorts-Griffin     10-25 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Resorts-Griffin,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Griffin To Hire Harrah's President To Head Resorts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sale of Resorts International
Inc. to Merv Griffin could conclude within the week, according to
the multimillionaire businessman and entertainer.
   Also on Monday, Griffin announced he had hired the president of
rival Harrah's Marina Hotel and Casino to run Resorts.
   Griffin said he expects to complete the purchase of the gaming
and real estate company from developer Donald Trump on or around
Nov. 3.
   Griffin will acquire Resorts International's casinos in Atlantic
City and the Bahamas, and will sell Resorts' unfinished Taj Majal
casino project in Atlantic City back to Trump.
   This week, Griffin is visiting several cities around the country
to raise investor interest in a $325 million bond issue needed to
finance his purchase of Resorts.
   Trump said Monday that the financing ``really is the only
obstacle to closing the deal.''
   But Thomas E. Gallagher, the New York attorney representing
Griffin, said the only roadblocks were final approval from Bahamian
gaming regulators and ``a lot of documentation on the actual
closing...''
   The New Jersey Casino Control Commission has granted Griffin
interim authorization to own and operate Resorts International's
Atlantic City gaming hall until he can get a plenary license. The
commission also approved Griffin's plans to split the company with
Trump.
   Trump would be paid $63 million to break his lucrative
management contract with the casino company. He then would pay
Griffin $273 million to buy back the Taj Mahal.
   Griffin will pay the Resorts Class A stockholders $36 a share _
or about $205 million. He will pay Trump $135 a share for his
controlling block of Class B shares, which have 100 times the
voting power of the Class A stock _ a total of $96 million.
   To run the new Resorts operation, Griffin announced Monday he
would hire David Hanlon.
   Hanlon, 43, has been president of Harrah's East, a subsidiary of
the Holiday Corp., for the past four years. Before that, he worked
for Caesar's World Inc. He could not be reached for comment Monday.
   Nina Andro, a spokeswoman for Griffin's operations in Los
Angeles, said Monday that Hanlon ``has consistently been one of the
top three operators in Atlantic City. Harrah's has been called the
most successful bottom-line operation on the East Coast.''
   The future of I.G. ``Jack'' Davis, Resorts International's
current president, ``will be discussed with Jack over the next few
days,'' Gallagher said.
   Davis has been president of Resorts since 1960 and has a
multiyear contract with the company for $1 million annually.
   Trump said that once the Resorts deal is complete, construction
will resume on the Taj Mahal and the 1,250-room complex could open
14 or 15 months later, indicating a March 1990 grand opening.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
