<DOCNO> AP881025-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 0057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-RJRNabisco-OptionsProbe     10-25 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-RJR Nabisco-Options Probe,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Options Exchange Probes RJR Nabisco Trades</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-RJR Nabisco Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A surge in trading of RJR Nabisco Inc. stock
options during the two days before the announcement of a $17
billion management buyout plan has prompted an investigation by the
Chicago Board Options Exchange.
   The probe was launched last week after CBOE officials noticed a
sharp rise in the number of RJR Nabisco stock options traded last
Tuesday and Wednesday, CBOE spokesman Warren Moulds said Monday.
   Moulds said exchange officials monitor trading through
computerized systems, ``and when it breaks usual trading patterns,
that usually sets in motion an inquiry into the reasons why.''
   A stock option contract is a right to buy or sell 100 shares of
a certain stock at a specified price within a given time period.
The value of RJR Nabisco stock options increased during the two
days prior to the company's announcement.
   In September, only 1,039 contracts of RJR Nabisco options were
traded daily, Moulds said. Last Tuesday, 4,079 contracts were
traded; on Wednesday, the day preceding the announcement, 7,050
contracts were traded.
   After the buyout proposal was made public on Thursday, 25,850
RJR Nabisco options traded on the CBOE, Moulds said.
   After such an announcement, a large increase in trading volume
is normal because the buyout plans often include a large payout to
shareholders that can boost the value of the company's stock.
   But increased trading volume prior to the announcement can
indicate that someone with advance knowledge of the company's plans
was attempting to profit illegally.
   In a new development Monday, the investment firm Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts & Co. said it would begin a $20.28 billion tender offer for
RJR Nabisco.
   The latest CBOE inquiry follows a Securities and Exchange
Commission investigation into options trading shortly before Grand
Metropolitan PLC announced a $5.2 billion dollar bid for Pillsbury
Co. earlier this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
