<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     10-25 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Edges Up, Stocks Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against the Japanese yen
today, while share prices rebounded moderately on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 126.87 yen, 0.27 yen higher than Monday's
close of 126.60 yen. Opening at 127.08 yen, the currency moved
slightly lower while ranging mainly betweeen 126.77 yen and 127.20
yen.
   The dollar-yen rate moved little because there was no news to
stimulate it, said a dealer with Daiwa Bank in Tokyo.
   The dollar rose in early trading but ``it fell back as the
market players started selling the currency when it moved up into
the 127-yen level,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which lost 57.03 points
Monday, regained 139.95 points, or 0.51 percent, to close at
27,421.49. The index gained 10.48 points shortly after the market
opened and continued upward.
   Trading was active with volume on the first section estimated at
1.2 billion shares. Steels, gas and real estate stocks attracted
traders.
   Despite prospects for lower interest rates and declining oil
prices, negative factors including Emperor Hirohito's monthlong
illness have kept share prices from rising dramatically.
</TEXT>
