<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     10-25 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against all major currencies in
early European trading today. Gold prices also were higher.
   Currency dealers said the dollar's rise was mostly a reaction to
its fall last week and also followed renewed signals from the Bank
of Japan that it is ready to buy dollars if the currency declines
further.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar edged up 0.27 yen to a closing 126.87 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted at 127.10 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.7965 West German marks, up from 1.7860; 1.5235
Swiss francs, up from 1.5145; 6.1350 French francs, up from 6.1025;
2.0235 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0143; 1,338.35 Italian lire, up
from 1,330.85; and 1.2002 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1973.
   In London, the dollar also rose against the British pound, which
cost $1.7485 in early trading, cheaper than $1.7520 late Monday.
   Gold rose after falling several dollars on Monday, hurt by the
failure of eight key members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries to agree on production restrictions.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $406 a troy ounce, up
from $405.15 bid late Monday. At midmorning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $406.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $406.40, up from $405.50 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 32 cents to close at a bid
$408.52.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.21 a troy
ounce, down from late Monday's $6.23.
</TEXT>
