<2ND_LINE>PM-Maxxam-KaiserTech,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maxxam to Pay Wesray $13 Million in KaiserTech Acquisition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maxxam Group Inc., the winning bidder for
KaiserTech Ltd., has agreed to pay $13 million to the company it
defeated, Wesray Capital Corp., a published report said today.
   Wesray, a New Jersey partnership that had joined with
KaiserTech's top officers in the failed bid, will receive the
payment for helping Maxxam secure bank financing related to the
acquisition, the San Francisco Chronicle reported.
   Shareholders will vote on Maxxam's acquisition of KaiserTech
Thursday at the annual meeting that will be run by KaiserTech chief
executive James Pasman and Charles Hurwitz, the Texas financier who
controls New York-based Maxxam.
   The two men will be in New York Friday for the newly acquired
company's first board meeting.
   Analysts believe Maxxam, in its payment to Wesray, wishes to
placate Pasman and Kaiser President Stephen Hutchraft, who were
part of the Wesray bid, the Chronicle reported. Both will continue
to be in charge after the acquisition.
   KaiserTech is the nation's third-largest aluminum producer,
while Maxxam is involved in real estate and lumber.
</TEXT>
