<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 0831EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PoultryDiplomacy 1stLd-Writethru   10-25 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poultry Diplomacy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frank Perdue Takes Soviet Ambassador on Poultry Tour</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS graf 3 to delete extraneous word</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ACCOMAC, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Ambassador Yuri V. Dubinin met
poultry magnate Frank Perdue and walked away with two ``Oven
Stuffer Roasters'' and some insight into chicken processing.
   Dubinin on Monday took a daylong tour of Perdue Farms on the
Eastern Shore to get a firsthand look at the mechanics of poultry
processing.
   As chairman and chief owner of Perdue Farms, Dubinin's
68-year-old host oversees a chicken empire that's expected to gross
more than $1 billion in sales this year. Perdue's face is familiar
on television where he appears in his own commercials.
   ``It's something that's very well developed in the United States
and with Perdue especially,'' Dubinin said of American poultry
production. ``The problem in the Soviet Union is output quality and
quantity.''
   Perdue accompanied the ambassador and his entourage of eight
including Dubinin's wife, Liana, and two daughters through a
hatchery in Westover, and a processing plant in Accomac that
employs 1,700 people and slaughters an average 300,000 chickens a
day.
   Afterward, he presented the diplomat with an ice chest bearing
the Perdue logo that contained the two roasting chickens. The rest
of the Soviet delegation from Washington received similar freebies.
   Dubinin said the visit was his first contact with chicken
processing in any country. He called his trip a demonstration that
``diplomacy is not just politics, it's economic relations ...
technological relations.''
   The ambassador said the Soviet Union would like to increase
chicken production. Watching eviscerated poultry moving swiftly
through the production line, is ``an interesting experience for
me,'' he told reporters.
   As for Perdue's television commercials, Dubinin said he has seen
them and found them amusing. But he added that he is less concerned
with the marketing aspects of poultry production and more concerned
about output.
   Dubinin said there is potential for some joint enterprise with
Perdue and the Soviet Union, but ``we will have a better idea''
about that after Perdue makes a planned visit to the Soviet Union.
   Perdue spokeswoman Chris Whaley confirmed that Perdue is
scheduled to make a visit soon, but she declined to speculate on
what business dealings might be under discussion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
