<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TaxShelter-Galanis     10-25 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tax Shelter-Galanis,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tax Shelter Promoter Sentenced in $150 Million Scam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former tax shelter promoter who is in federal
prison has been sentenced to seven to 21 years in state prison
after pleading guilty to charges of bilking investors of more than
$150 million.
   John Peter Galanis, 45, of Greenwich, Conn., pleaded guilty
Friday to four larceny counts of a 105-count Manhattan grand jury
indictment. He admitted that, from February 1984 through June 1986,
he and nine others defrauded investors through a real estate
venture.
   Manhattan District Attorney Robert Morgenthau said Galanis and
his co-conspirators set up Consolidated Mortgage Co. and sold $75
million worth of partnerships with a promise of tax writeoffs that
later proved unlawful.
   In another case, Morgenthau said, the conspirators formed Nashua
Trust Co., a firm that supposedly would rehabilitate hotels and
commercial property in Atlantic City. More than 1,300 people
invested in the firm, which lost the properties and went bankrupt,
the district attorney said.
   Galanis was sentenced to up to 27 years in federal prison
following his conviction in White Plains last summer on
racketeering and other charges.
   State Supreme Court Justice Harold Rothwax ordered Galanis to
serve the state sentence concurrently with the federal time.
</TEXT>
