<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 0856EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-GoldFields     10-25 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gold Fields,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British, U.S. Actions Set Back Minorco Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British government and a U.S. federal judge
have dealt damaging blows to Minorco SA's hostile bid for
Consolidated Gold Fields PLC, citing concerns about monopolization
of the world gold market.
   In London today, the government said the takeover offer, which
values Gold Fields at roughly $5 billion, would be investigated by
the Monopolies and Mergers Commission for its possible adverse
effect on competition.
   The ruling blocks for up to three months the bid by the
Luxembourg-based investment arm of the South African gold and
diamond mining giants, Anglo American Corp. and De Beers
Consolidated Mines Ltd.
   On Monday, U.S. District Judge Michael B. Mukasey in New York
issued a temporary injunction against the bid on antitrust grounds.
Gold Fields has contended that a takeover by Minorco would imperil
American access to gold and strategic minerals.
   Minorco offered $22.86 in cash and stock for each Consolidated
Gold Fields share it does not already own on condition the bid was
not referred to the British monopolies commission.
   Minorco has lifted its stake in Consolidated Gold Fields to
about 29.6 percent.
   Minorco issued a statement saying it was considering its
position in the light of the British government's decision.
   Trade Secretary Lord Young asked the monopolies commission to
report to him within the three months.
   The British investigation will center on the proposed takeover's
impact on strategic metals, in particular titanium and zircon, a
spokesman at the Department of Trade and Industry said.
   Titanium, a metal largely used as a whitener in paints, also is
used in jet engines, a Consolidated Gold Fields metallurgist said.
Zircon is mainly used as a refracting agent in glass and steel
furnaces, but is also a critical substance in nuclear submarines
and power plants, and in rocket nose cones, he said.
   Consolidated Gold Fields says that Australian-based Renison
Goldfields Consolidated Ltd., in which it has a 49 percent stake,
is the world's largest producer of mineral sands that serve as raw
materials for titanium and zircon.
   Consolidated Gold Fields' shares plummeted on news of the
investigation, while Minorco's shares rose.
</TEXT>
