<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FruehaufRestructuring     10-25 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fruehauf Restructuring,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drained Fruehauf Moves To Restructure Slumping Trailer Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financially drained Fruehauf Corp. is
restructuring its slumping trailer operations, a move that will
necessitate an unspecified number of layoffs and early retirements
at its headquarters here, the company announced.
   The truck-trailer and auto-parts maker began layoffs last week
in its engineering department, Fruehauf spokesman David Hladik said
Monday.
   About 40 percent of the department's 78 engineers received pink
slips, and others will be transferred, he added.
   ``There will be some layoffs in personnel and an early
retirement program has been implemented,'' Hladik said.
   Low profit margins and hot competition have depressed Fruehauf's
trailer division, which lost $29 million in 1986 and broke even
last year.
   The company has been struggling since a management-led leveraged
buyout in 1986 left it saddled with debt. Fruehauf has sold a
number of operations and trimmed its long-term debt to $705
million, down from $1.6 billion in 1986.
   Last week, the company in part blamed that debt for
third-quarter losses of $19.1 million. That compares to a loss of
$14.3 million or $1.77 per share in the third quarter of 1987.
   The company is discussing a possible merger with farm and
industrial machinery manufacturer Varity Corp. of Toronto.
</TEXT>
