<1ST_LINE>r f PM-InternationalPaper     10-25 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-International Paper,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Locked-out IP Workers Go To The Polls Friday To Vote On Compromise
Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Locked-out union workers go to the polls
Friday to decide whether to accept a compromise offer aimed at
breaking their 1{-year-old labor dispute with International Paper
Co.
   The offer covers a six-year period retroactive to Feb. 1, 1987.
The previous contract expired in January 1987 and union workers
were locked out of the plant on March 21, 1987.
   Don Langham, regional vice president of the United Paperworkers
International Union, said the proposed contract ``provides
tremendous shift differential improvement and it provides that all
union members would be returned to work immediately.''
   One of the major issues in the labor dispute has been IP's
policy of paying production employees extra when they work Sundays
and holidays. The company wanted to eliminate the bonuses to cut
costs.
   Frank Bragg, president of UPIU Local 265 and a member of the
committee that has represented the 1,200 locked-out workers at the
bargaining table, said the company would not address the bonus
issue.
   Bragg said the union membership appears to be ``split at this
point as to who wants to fight and who wants to quit.''
   ``We commend our people for fighting the battle as long as they
have,'' he said. ``But at some point in time, we had to go back to
the members for direction on which way they want us to go.''
   Company officials have said the locked-out workers cannot return
to their jobs until they accept a new labor agreement. The Mobile
mill has been operated by temporary workers since the start of the
lockout, which spread to strikes at IP mills in three other states.
   Those strikes have all been called off.
</TEXT>
