<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Stocks Narrowly Mixed In Nervous Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were narrowly mixed in light, nervous
trading Tuesday.
   With few major incentives for trading, players largely were
hanging back awaiting Thursday's release of British trade figures
for September.
   ``There is a lot of nervousness over the pound, interest rates
and the trade figures,'' said one dealer about the day's light
level of trading activity.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was unchanged
at 1,848.4 at midday.
   Volume was thin, with just 214.9 million shares changing hands,
compared with 289.5 million shares at the same time Monday.
   The major market-affecting news was a keenly awaited decision by
the British government to refer Minorco SA's 2.9 billion-pound, or
$5.06 billion, bid for Consolidated Gold Fields PLC to the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission to investigate its possible
impact on competition.
   The decision blocked the bid from proceeding and Consolidated
Gold Fields' shares plummeted on the news, which also depressed the
overall market. Consolidated Gold Fields shares fell 104 pence to
11.41 pounds.
</TEXT>
