<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Slightly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened slightly higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting positive technical
and fundamental signals following three days of losses in most of
the grain pits.
   The wheat market, which had rallied late Monday on news of
Chinese buying interest, continued to climb this morning on a
report that China had purchased 40,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at
subsidized prices overnight, analysts said.
   Corn futures got a boost from an Agriculture Department report
issued Monday afternoon that showed last week's corn exports to be
much larger than expected.
   And the Census Bureau's weekly soybean crush report showed the
amount of U.S. soybean meal stocks to be much lower than expected,
which was positive for soybean prices, analysts said.
   ``Of course, all the news wasn't friendly,'' said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``There were
some beneficial rains in Argentina and some more are forecast this
week for Argentina and Brazil,'' where soybeans are an important
crop.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 1\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.19} a bushel; corn was 1}
cents lower to 1\ cents higher with December at $2.78} a bushel;
oats were 1\ cents higher across the board with December at $2.46 a
bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents to 3{ cents higher with November at
$7.69 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .02 cent lower to .20 cent higher with December
at 74.97 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .17 cent
lower with October at 81.90 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to
.33 cent higher with December at 42.50 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .07 cent lower to .30 cent higher with February at
51.20 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled higher on Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
