<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     10-25 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0381</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was little changed today as
prices steadied somewhat in trendless trading peppered with
takeover speculation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up .36 at 2,170.70
at midday. Losers narrowly outpaced gainers by about 8 to 7 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with
584 up, 674 down and 534 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 77.69 million shares as of noon
on Wall Street.
   Traders said a government report showing a 4.1 percent drop in
durable goods orders in September was within market expectations.
The report, which hinted that inflation is being held in check,
coupled with stability in the bond and currency markets helped
support stock prices, said Emmanuel Geronimous, a senior vice
president at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Analysts are quick to note that two different markets currently
are functioning _ one that involves takeover and buyout issues and
another that involves the remaining equities untouched by actual
deals or speculation.
   Billion-dollar bids have been made recently for such big-name
companies as RJR Nabisco, Pillsbury, Kraft, West Point-Pepperell
and Chicago Pacific. Large bids tend to put the spotlight on the
industries of target companies, fueling further speculation about a
target company's peers as potential takeover candidates.
   The rest of the market, however, is not awash with excitement.
``The broad market looks tired,'' said Larry Wachtel, first vice
president at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Among actively traded Big Board issues, Rorer rose 3] to 45}
amid speculation that F. Hoffman-LaRoche might launch a $60-a-share
takeover bid. Hoffman declined comment.
   Among takeover issues, Nabisco was up } at 84}; Kraft fell 2 to
100 and Pillsbury was unchanged at 59|. Maytag, which announced
Monday it would acquire Chicago Pacific, slipped 1[ to 22|.
   Church's Fried Chicken was up | at 7~. The company received an
$8-a-share bid from Popeyes Fried Chicken.
   Cray Research plunged 9] to 59{ following the release of
lower-than-expected earnings for the third quarter.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped .08 to 158.77. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was off .80 at 304.15.
</TEXT>
