<1ST_LINE>a f BC-BuyingAtlanta Adv31   10-25 0793</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Buying Atlanta, Adv 31,0816</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Oct. 31 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Asian Money Looking For Property In Atlanta</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AB1 of Oct. 24</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scarlett O'Hara's hometown is for sale, and
cash-rich Japanese investors are the principal targets of
businessmen marketing Atlanta's highest profile office buildings.
   It is a poorly kept secret that a Japanese insurance company is
about to buy the IBM Tower, paying $300 million for Atlanta's
year-old showpiece skyscraper.
   And market professionals say other buildings, principally the
headquarters tower of Georgia-Pacific Corp., and CNN Center, hub
for Ted Turner's broadcasting conglomerate, are on the block and
may soon be sold to syndicates made up largely of foreign investors.
   The Asian invasion of the American real estate market has raised
hackles elsewhere in the United States, as major landmarks like the
Exxon Corp. building in New York City have been snapped up by the
Japanese. But here in Atlanta, the phenomenon follows years of
active campaigning for foreign investment.
   Georgia has been mining Japan for business since the mid-70s and
the state now ranks second to California in Japanese manufacturing
investment. Atlanta ranks third among American cities behind Dallas
and Houston in the number of Asian-owned businesses per 1,000 Asian
residents.
   ``Jobs. Jobs is the purpose of our efforts,'' said Randy
Cardoza, deputy commissioner of the Georgia Department of Industry
and Trade.
   A decade of self-promotion and airport improvements by the city
and state have helped fuel the drive for foreign investment, said
Allen Judd, a business consultant who was one of the founders eight
years ago of the Japan-America Society of Georgia, Inc.
   A survey on Atlanta real estate by the Braemar Group Ltd. says
12.06 percent of the city's office space is foreign-owned, and
Braemar Group owner and managing partner Tarby Bryant predicts 50
percent of the best office space will be foreign-owned by the year
2000, with the Japanese accounting for half.
   ``With all of the major Japanese banks currently in Atlanta and
two airlines, JAL (Japan Airlines) and Delta (Air Lines), now
flying direct links to Japan's Narita Airport, I am confident that
we will see more Japanese investors looking at our office
buildings, hotels and regional malls for acquisition,'' he said.
   Atlanta ``is at the top of the second tier'' of cities drawing
Japanese interest, Bryant said, because its so-called ``trophy
properties'' are available at cheaper rates than in the
``first-tier'' cities of New York, Los Angeles, Chicago, Boston and
Washington, D.C.
   There also is less competition in cities such as Atlanta to
purchase trophy properties _ defined loosely by Bryant as ``quality
real estate, architecturally significant with a major tenant.''
   The pending purchase of the IBM Tower by Sumitomo Life Insurance
Co. ``is the big foot in our pond,'' Bryant said, and more such
deals should follow fairly soon.
   Such deals have been aided by the recent strength of the
Japanese yen over the dollar and by Atlanta's expected strong
growth in the next several years. The combination makes real estate
investments particularly attractive.
   Among foreign investors, the Japanese have the most money and
are the most aggressive, Bryant said. In addition, he said, the
Japanese feel pressure from their peers to invest in America.
   The Consulate General of Japan in Atlanta says there were 236
Japanese-owned facilities in the state as of July 1, employing
12,100 people and representing an investment of $810 million.
   A report last year by the Georgia Department of Industry and
Trade said there were six Taiwanese-owned facilities and four owned
by Koreans. Two investors were from Singapore and one from Hong
Kong.
   Of those Asian-owned businesses, 38 are headquarters for U.S
subsidiaries, including Hitachi America Ltd., which makes
telecommunications equipment; Asahi Inc., athletic shoe
manufacturer; Mizuno Golf Co., a division of Japan's largest
sporting goods company; and TDK Manufacturing (US) Ltd. Co.,
manufacturer of video cassette tapes.
   There are numerous regional headquarters, and manufacturing
plants for some of the best-known Japanese products, including
Maxell tapes, Sony records, Mitsubishi televisions and Kubota
tractors.
   There are also nine Japanese banks, and Judd said a 10th is
expected to open soon.
   In all, there were 1,057 foreign-owned facilities in the state
last year, the Industry and Trade report said. The department said
Japanese capital investment ranked second in the state behind
Canada.
   Just last week, the Yamaha Motor Co. opened its Yamaha USA golf
car factory at Newnan, Ga., its first North American manufacturing
facility.
   Some of that investment may have been driven by fears the
Congress would enact severely protectionist trade legislation.
Despite passage of a watered-down trade bill, Bryant said he
doesn't expect the flood of foreign investment to slow anytime soon.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Oct. 31</NOTE>
