<1ST_LINE>a f BC-BuyingAtlanta-Koreans Adv31   10-25 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Buying Atlanta-Koreans, Adv 31,0414</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Oct. 31 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Making it in Atlanta, Korean Style</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Buying Atlanta</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Joon H. Song moved to Atlanta 26 years ago,
there were three Korean families in town.
   ``Then my brother came, and my sister, my father,'' Song said.
Other families followed, and now, Song estimates, there are between
15,000 and 20,000 Koreans living in the metropolitan area of 2.5
million people.
   There are also an estimated 30,000 to 40,000 Chinese and about
5,000 Japanese, according to Allen Judd, an independent business
consultant who has spent much of the past two decades promoting
Asian business connections in Atlanta.
   A recent study disclosed that many of those Asian-Americans own
their own businesses _ so many that Atlanta ranked third in the
country behind Dallas and Houston in the number of Asian-owned
businesses per 1,000 Asian residents.
   The study said there are 80.5 Asian-owned businesses per 1,000
Asian-Americans in Atlanta. Dallas was first with 90.3, followed by
Houston at 84.9. Places with large Asian populations such as
Honolulu and San Francisco were far down the list.
   The finding surprised Song, a past president of the Korean
Association, an umbrella organization of 72 Korean support groups
in the Atlanta metropolitan area.
   ``Just like the Irish went to Boston (and) the Polish went to
Chicago, Koreans and Chinese came to Atlanta,'' said Judd, a
founder of the Japan-America Society of Georgia Inc.
   Song estimates that about 70 percent of Atlanta's Asians are
direct immigrants with the rest coming from other major American
cities.
   They are drawn, he said, by the same factors that have made
Atlanta and the rest of the Sunbelt some of the fastest growing
areas in the country.
   ``Weather's good. Transportation's good. Lots of things (are)
good,'' said Song, who works for Citizens & Southern National Bank
in Oriental business development.
   The new arrivals also find a strong sense of community, 42
Korean churches, a Korean-American school and a Korean chamber of
commerce.
   ``Most of the Korean business is family business, that's why the
business is growing very fast,'' Song said.
   The exact Asian population of the Atlanta is hard to judge, with
the latest figures coming from the 1980 U.S. Census and most
experts agreeing the numbers have changed substantially since then.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Oct. 31</NOTE>
</DOC>
