<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1526EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Steel     10-25 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Steel,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USX Profit Up 63 Percent, Weirton Posts Gain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The oil and steel giant USX Corp. reported on Tuesday a 63
percent increase in its third-quarter profit and boosted its
quarterly dividend by 17 percent.
   ``Given our strong cash position and our confidence in the
sustainability of our profit, we are pleased to increase the return
to our shareholders,'' Chairman David M. Roderick said.
   Meanwhile, employee-owned Weirton Steel Corp. said its
third-quarter earnings edged up slightly from a year ago, its 19th
consecutive profitable quarter since employees bought the mill from
National Intergroup Inc.
   USX, the Pittsburgh-based parent of Marathon Oil and the nation's
largest steel producer, reported its quarterly profit rose to $228
million, or 80 cents per share, from $140 million, or 46 cents per
share, a year earlier.
   Third-quarter sales rose 7.7 percent to $4.2 billion from $3.9
billion.
   The latest quarter included $71 million gain from the settlement
of a federal tax issue and a pre-tax credit of $61 million from
asset sales. The 1987 third quarter benefited from a $47 million
credit on restructuring charges and a pre-tax credit of $22 million
from asset sales.
   The company boosted its dividend to 35 cents per share from 30
cents, payable Dec. 10 to stockholders of record at the end of
business Nov. 4.
   USX earned $598 million, or $2.07 per share, on sales of $12.4
billion in the first nine months of the year. USX earned $233
million, or 67 cents per share, on sales of $10.6 billion in the
1987 period.
   Marathon reported quarterly operating income of $183 million on
sales of $2.3 billion thanks to better margins on refined profits.
   ``Marathon is positioned to make a meaningful contribution to
corporate results, even in a market characterized by low and
volatile worldwide crude oil prices,'' Roderick said.
   The steelmaking USS division reported quarterly operating income
of $95 million on sales of $1.4 billion in the second year of the
steel industry's recovery from a seven-year slump.
   In Weirton, W.Va., Weirton Steel said it earned a record $34
million in the latest quarter, up from $33.6 million a year earlier.
   The company is owned by its 8,000-some employees and not public
stockholders, and as a result does not report earnings per share. It
said $17 million of its latest profit will be distributed to
employees, however, up from $11 million a year earlier.
   The company said its sales for July to September rose to $341
million on shipments totaling 671,000 tons, compared with $330
million on shipments totaling 708,000 tons a year earlier.
   For the first nine months of the year, the company's earned
$117.9 million on sales of $1.05 billion, compared with $97.3
million on sales of $997 million a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
