<DOCNO> AP881025-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1553EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Sears     10-25 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Sears,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sears Profit Down 16 Percent in 3rd Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. said Tuesday its
third-quarter net income fell 16 percent, marking the third
consecutive quarter of declining profits for the nation's largest
retailer.
   Sears blamed the drop on flat merchandise sales and intense
competition from other retailers.
   The company said its net income totaled $344.2 million, or 90
cents per share, for the three months ending Sept. 30, compared with
$409 million, or $1.08 per share, for the same period a year ago.
   Revenue for the 1988 third quarter rose 9.5 percent to $13.35
billion, compared with $12.19 billion last year.
   Sears' second-quarter net income was 5 percent below the
year-earlier results, and its first-quarter profit was off by 37
percent.
   For the first three quarters combined, Sears' net income was 18
percent below its net for the first nine months of 1987.
   Sears has been struggling to improve its performance, which has
been poor in comparison to other large retailers, and the company
has been rumored to be considering selling some of its assets.
   The Sears Merchandise Group, with responsibility for the
company's store operations, reported third-quarter income of $135.4
million, compared with $170.4 million a year ago. Sears said the
group's results were adversely affected by flat sales, intense
competition, pressure on gross margins and inventory adjustments.
   The merchandise group's results included a $26 million income-tax
benefit resulting from a bookkeeping change.
   The Dean Witter Financial Services Group reported third-quarter
income of $20.6 million compared with a loss of $4.2 million last
year. The group includes Discover Card, Sears' all-purpose credit
card, which showed a profit for the third consecutive quarter after
two years of losses.
   Discover Card reported income of $13.6 million compared with a
loss of $29.4 million last year.
   The Allstate Insurance Group had third-quarter income of $217
million, down from $240.5 million last year. Sears said the decline
was due to lower underwriting results, reduced tax benefits and
lower capital gains.
   The Coldwell Banker Real Estate Group reported third-quarter
income of $25.8 million, compared with $47.8 million a year ago.
Income in both quarters included the sale of shopping centers, Sears
said, with the timing of the 1987 sales accounting for the larger
income last year.
   For the nine months ending Sept. 30, Sears had net income of
$893.1 million, or $2.35 per share, on sales of $38.49 billion
compared with net income of $1.09 billion, or $2.86 per share, on
sales of $34.39 billion in the first nine months of 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881025-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1557EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Goodyear     10-25 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Goodyear,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goodyear Reports Earnings Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co. on Tuesday said its
third-quarter profits fell 65 percent from a year ago partly because
of difficult business conditions in its domestic tire operations.
   For the quarter ended Sept. 30, Goodyear earned $63.5 million, or
$1.11 a share. A year earlier, the company reported net income of
$178.7 million, or $3.13 a share. In the year-ago period, Goodyear
benefited from a $50 million gain on the sale of properties in
Arizona.
   Sales, however, rose 8 percent to $2.7 billion, from $2.5 billion
a year ago.
   Goodyear attributed the recent decline in profits partly to
higher natural rubber costs in its domestic tire operations. Plant
efficiencies also were reduced due to an unusually hot summer, when
the company was forced to cut back on electricity at some plants.
   Goodyear began a major cost-cutting effort and shed most of its
non-rubber operations beginning in late 1986 to raise cash and fend
off a hostile takeover attempt by financier Sir James Goldsmith.
   Chairman Robert E. Mercer said the company experienced a lag in
recovering costs through price increases. Tire unit sales in the
U.S. replacement market were down in the three months, although the
decline was partially offset by better unit sales of lower priced
tires to original equipment manufacturers.
   The company indicated its businesses in 27 foreign countries
showed improved earnings, but they were partially offset by greater
foreign currency lossses.
   Through the nine months, Goodyear earned fell 51 percent to
$293.7 million, or $5.13 a share, on sales of $8.1 billion. In the
year-ago period, earnings were $603.9 million, or $9.78 a share, on
sales of $7.4 billion.
</TEXT>
