<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1514EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   10-25 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Late Wheat Plunge Pulls Crop Futures To Lower Close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures closed sharply lower Tuesday on the
Chicago Board of Trade in a late, technically motivated sell-off
that spread from the wheat pit to the other grain and soybean
markets.
   Corn and soybeans finished moderately lower; oat prices closed
down sharply.
   Tuesday marked the fourth straight day of declining wheat prices
and the sixth session in the last eight in which wheat values have
dropped.
   Large brokerage firms including Refco Inc., Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. and Thomson McKinnon Inc. each sold more than 1 million
bushels of wheat late in the session after the price for December
delivery tumbled past $4.12\ a bushel, Monday's session low,
analysts said.
   Prices had opened higher on reports that China had purchased
400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat, but prices gradually slipped with
the bears gaining the upper hand around midday.
   ``We started a little better but the bulls couldn't consolidate
it, then the bears started to consolidate it and pushed it down,''
said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in
Chicago.
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to 11} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.07 a bushel; corn was 3
cents to 5 cents lower with December at $2.74{ a bushel; oats were 1
cent to 8\ cents lower with December at $2.36{ a bushel; soybeans
were 4{ cents lower to { cent higher with November at $7.61 a bushel.
