<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0435</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was narrowly mixed in dull
trading today as prices steadied in the face of profit-taking and
takeover speculation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 1.78 at 2,172.12
an hour before the closing bell.
   Losers narrowly outpaced gainers by about 9 to 8 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 653 up, 735
down and 546 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 128.75 million shares as of 3
p.m. on Wall Street.
   Traders were encouraged that the market did not lose ground as it
consolidated in the face of a weeks-long rally. ``The profit-taking
has been well contained,'' one dealer said.
   The market, however, has divided into two segments _ one that
involves takeover and buyout issues and another that involves the
remaining equities untouched by real bids or speculation.
   Billion-dollar bids have been made recently for such big-name
companies as RJR Nabisco, Pillsbury, Kraft, West Point-Pepperell and
Chicago Pacific. Large bids tend to put the spotlight on the
industries of target companies, fueling further speculation about a
target company's peers as potential takeover candidates.
   ``Takeover speculation has reached a new extreme,'' said Alfred
E. Goldman, a vice president at A.G. Edwards & Sons Inc. in St.
Louis. ``The crescendo keeps getting louder and louder.''
   The rest of the market, however, is not awash with excitement.
Analysts said the broad market appears tired and unable to mount a
sustainable advance.
   A government report showing a 4.1 percent drop in durable goods
orders in September was within market expectations. The report,
which hinted that inflation is being held in check, coupled with
stability in the bond and currency markets helped support stock
prices, said Emmanuel Geronimous, a senior vice president at
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Among Big Board takeover issues, Nabisco was up | at 84|; Kraft
fell 3] to 98|, Pillsbury was off [ at 59{, and West Point-Pepperell
was off 1{ at 48{.
   Elsewhere, Rorer rose 3[ to 45[ amid speculation that F.
Hoffman-LaRoche might launch a $60-a-share takeover bid. Hoffman
declined comment.
   Church's Fried Chicken was up } at 8. The company received an
$8-a-share bid from Popeyes Fried Chicken.
   Cray Research plunged 9{ to 59] following the release of
lower-than-expected earnings for the third quarter.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained
.02 to 158.87. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off 1.15 at 303.80.
