<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Computer     10-25 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Computer,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Control Data Reports First Loss After Four Profitable Quarters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Control Data Corp. of Minneapolis on Tuesday blamed market
``softness'' in key business sectors for causing the computer
company to post a net loss in the third quarter, its first loss
after four profitable quarters.
   Another computer company, Storage Technology Corp., said its
profit fell 76 percent in the latest quarter.
   Data-storage devices for mainframe computers are Storage
Technology's principal business and make up about one-third of the
revenue of Control Data.
   Control Data said it had a net loss of $2.4 million on revenues
of $841.4 million for the quarter ending Sept. 30.
   In the third quarter of 1987, Control Data had net earnings of
$6.8 million, or 16 cents per share, on revenues of $831.4 million.
   For the first nine months of 1988, Control Data reported net
earnings of $14.5 million, or 34 cents a share, on revenues of $2.7
billion, compared with earnings of $8.5 million, or 19 cents a
share, on revenues of $2.4 billion over the same period last year.
   ``We are disappointed that Control Data's 1988 results will come
in below mid-year expectations,'' said Robert M. Price, Control Data
chairman and chief executive officer. ``Nevertheless, the company's
recovery remains on track, and we continue to anticipate that
Control Data's operating performance in 1988 will be stronger than
it was in 1987.''
   Control Data's computer systems and services division has
received expected revenues later than anticipated, a trend that is
expected to continue into the fourth quarter, according to company
spokeswoman Nancy Foltz.
   Control Data said its results were helped by applying tax
benefits in the quarter worth $4.8 million.
   Third-quarter results also benefited from the sale of Control
Data's interest in Commercial Credit Corp.
   Imprimis Technology Inc., the company's disk drive subsidiary,
exceeded its third quarter 1987 performance and 1988 plan, even
though results for the period just ended were below those reported
in the first and second quarters of 1988, Control Data said.
   Storage Technology, of Lousville, Colo., which emerged from
Chapter 11 bankruptcy court protection last year, said its profit
fell to $752,000, or less than 1 cent a share, from $3.2 million, or
1 cent a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $128.3 million from
$107 million.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Storage Technology
said its profit fell to $15.7 million, or 7 cents a share, from
$20.4 million, or 9 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to
$372.9 million from $301 million.
</TEXT>
