<HEAD>Dollar Mixed; Gold Rises</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mixed against major foreign
currencies Tuesday, weighed down by a government report of a
slowdown in U.S. factory orders.
   The dollar edged down against the British pound and the Japanese
yen, but rose against the currencies of most other major U.S.
trading partners.
   The Commerce Department said orders for ``big-ticket'' durable
goods plunged an unexpected 4.1 percent in September.
   Currency traders took the decline as a sign that the U.S. economy
could be slowing down, something that would tend to decrease demand
for dollars by foreign investors.
   The factory orders report fit in with other signs of a slowdown
last month, including the second consecutive decline in retail sales
and a drop in manufacturing employment.
   The dollar's decline against the British pound was partly the
result of a speech by Nigel Lawson, Britain's Chancellor of the
Exchequer, that supported sterling, according to Frank Conte, a vice
president of Barclays Bank PLC in New York.
   In Tokyo, the dollar edged up 0.27 Japanese yen to a closing
126.87 yen. Later, in London, it rose to 127.75 yen. At the end of
the day in New York, the dollar fell to 126.80 yen from 127.02.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7535 to buy one pound, up from $1.7520 late Monday. In New York,
the pound rose to $1.7515 from $1.7501 Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.7903 West German marks, up from 1.7898; 1.5183
Swiss francs, up from 1.5175; 1.2012 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1986; 6.1230 French francs, 6.1100; and 1,333.75 Italian lire, up
from 1,332.88.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.7860 West German marks, unchanged; 1.5175 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5145; 6.1100 French francs, up from 6.1025; 2.0170
Dutch guilders, up from 2.0143; 1,332.00 Italian lire, up from
1,330.85; and 1.1990 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1973.
   Gold recovered some of its losses from Monday, when it had fallen
after eight key members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries failed to agree on production restrictions.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose 32 cents to close at a bid $408.52 a troy
ounce. Gold rose in London to $407.25 an ounce from $405.15 Monday.
In Zurich, it rose to $407 an ounce from $405.50.
   Republic National Bank of New York said gold bullion was bid at
$406.60 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $405.50 late Monday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for near-month
delivery rose to $406.40 an ounce from $405.80 Monday.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a late bid of $6.25 a troy ounce
from $6.23 late Monday. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
near-month delivery rose to $6.221 an ounce from $6.197.
</TEXT>
