<2ND_LINE>AM-Digital Buyback, 1st Ld-Writethru,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Digital Announces 10 Million Share Stock Purchase</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with analyst comments, final stock price, details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MAYNARD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Digital Equipment Corp. on Tuesday
announced plans to buy back shares with a current market value of
more than $900 million, boosting its stock price as sketchy takeover
rumors swirled.
   Analysts said a takeover bid for the computer company seemed
quite unlikely and described the buyback as a step to take advantage
of the stock's bargain price while doing something to benefit its
shareholders.
   ``I don't think it's a defensive move by any means,'' said
Michael Pompian, an analyst in Boston for Needham & Co. of New York.
   Digital's stock rose $2 a share to $92 a share in consolidated
New York Stock Exchange trading, following a rise of $3 a share on
Monday.
   Digital, the world's second biggest computer company after
International Business Machines Corp., said its board of directors
had authorized management to buy back up to 10 million of its own
shares from time to time on the open market.
   That number of shares represents about 8 percent of the common
stock outstanding. They would be bought at whatever the prevailing
market price is at the time.
   The recent spate of takeover activity involving companies such as
Kraft Inc. and RJR Nabisco Inc. helped revive old rumors that
American Telephone & Telegraph Co. was interested in buying Digital.
Both companies have disparaged the rumors.
   ``Whoever would be buying DEC would need an awfully big
checkbook,'' said Barry Bosak, an analyst for Eberstadt Fleming Inc.
in New York.
   Digital's stock hit a peak of $199.50 in 1987, but has slumped
badly since then. The company has no dividend to support the stock,
so buybacks are one of the few ways to reward shareholders.
   ``We believe buying our stock is an attractive investment and a
sound way to build a shareholder value,'' James M. Osterhoff,
Digital's vice president for finance, said in a news release.
   Digital purchased 3 million shares of its stock for $363 million
in January and 5 million shares for $782 million in a program
completed in May 1987. Those shares were used for employee stock
plans.
</TEXT>
