<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   10-25 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Market Slows As Takeover Mania Subsides</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished narrowly mixed Tuesday
as a feeding frenzy in takeover issues subsided.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, off 13 points Monday,
gained 3.02 to close at 2,173.36. The key index had seesawed within
a 2-point range for much of the session.
   Declining issues narrowly outpaced advancers in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 701 issues
up, 727 down and 525 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE came to 155.19 million shares,
down from 170.59 million. Nationwide, consolidated volume in
NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional exchanges and on
the over-the-counter market, totaled 183.30 million shares.
   The market appeared steady throughout most of the session as
little fresh takeover news emerged. Philip Puccio, a senior vice
president at Dillon, Read & Co., noted that the market ``has kind of
dried up'' following a recent string of multibillion-dollar takeover
announcements involving companies with high-profile brand names.
   But while stocks that are the target of deals and takeover
speculation have basked in the spotlight, the broader market has
missed much of the enthusiasm.
   ``The broader market seems to have settled back into its
malaise,'' said Hugh Johnson, senior vice president at First Albany
Corp.
   ``People seem to have retreated to the sidelines until another
news event comes along,'' he said.
   On a more subtle level, some analysts are beginning to wonder
whether some skepticism is settling in among investors who are
concerned about the sheer size of the latest crop of deals. The
largest proposal to date is Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.'s $20.3
billion bid for RJR Nabisco.
   ``People are starting to question whether we can get the
financing done to get all these large mergers completed,'' Johnson
said. ``A substantial amount of financing has to be completed in a
very short time ... and there's a healthy skepticism creeping in.''
   While some traders were preoccupied with the release on Wednesday
of third-quarter gross national product figures, many predicted the
government's report would be a non-event. As Johnson noted, the
report looks back to the third quarter while the market is looking
ahead to the first quarter of 1989.
   Among Big Board takeover issues, Nabisco was up 1 at 85; Kraft
fell 3 to 99, Pillsbury was off [ at 59{, and West Point-Pepperell
was off 1~ at 48[.
   Elsewhere, Rorer rose 3] to 45] amid speculation that F.
Hoffman-LaRoche might launch a $60-a-share takeover bid. Hoffman
declined comment.
   Church's Fried Chicken was up ~ at 8[. The company received an
$8-a-share bid from Popeyes Fried Chicken.
   Cray Research plunged 9 to 59~ following the release of
lower-than-expected earnings for the third quarter.
   Digital Equipment rose 2 to 92. The company announced plans to
buy back shares with a current market value of more than $900
million. Analysts said the news gave a boost to other technology
issues.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $190 million.
   The NYSE index was at up .02 at 158.87.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index gained .18 to 325.66, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was up .10 to 282.38.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index stood at
304.38, down .57. The NASDAQ composite index for the
over-the-counter market closed at 386.12, down 1.11.
</TEXT>
