<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Church's-Popeyes     10-25 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Church's-Popeyes,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Popeyes Owner Offers $290 Million for Church's Fried Chicken</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs:Popeyes is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of Popeyes Famous Fried Chicken and
Biscuits said Tuesday it was launching a cash tender offer for
Church's Fried Chicken Inc. that values its fast-food chicken
restaurant rival at about $290 million.
   The deal would combine the second and third largest fast-food
chicken chains in the nation. The biggest is Kentucky Fried Chicken,
a unit of Pepsico Inc. of Purchase, N.Y.
   A. Copeland Enterprises Inc., based in New Orleans, said it was
offering $8 a share for each of Church's 36 million shares.
   Church's management, based in San Antonio, Texas, urged its
shareholders to defer tendering their shares until its board could
review the offer and make a recommendation.
   Analysts said the bidding could go higher. On the New York Stock
Exchange, Church's stock rose 87{ cents a share to $8.12{.
   Joseph Doyle, who follows the fast-food business for the
investment firm Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New York, said
the offer is ``reasonable and fair in one sense.''
   ``However, in this day and age of takeovers, the first offer is
generally not the last from the original offeree,'' Doyle said.
``Generally, the company under siege will try to come up with a
higher alternative offer.''
   The offer, which is to expire at midnight Nov. 22, is conditioned
upon tender of enough shares to give Copeland two-thirds of Church's
shares on a fully-diluted basis and upon obtaining sufficient
financing.
   Copeland Enterprises said it already owns nearly 1.2 million
shares, or 3.2 percent, of Church's shares.
   ``We intend to pursue it on an amicable basis,'' said James
Flynn, Copeland's president.
   Alvin C. Copeland, Popeyes chairman and chief executive, said in
a statement, ``The combination of Popeyes' proven industry expertise
in generating high per store sales on the basis of a superior
quality menu and Church's loyal customer base in its core markets
will create a dynamic fast-food restaurant operation.''
   Church's board of directors said it will make a recommendation to
its stockholders by Nov. 7 whether they should accept the offer and
why.
   ``Church's requests that its stockholders defer making a decision
to accept or reject the offer until they have been advised of the
company's position,'' the company said in a statement.
   Church's is the second-largest purveyor of fast-food chicken in
the country behind No.1 Kentucky Fried Chicken. New Orleans-based
Popeyes, founded in 1972, is the third largest, said Sawyer-Miller
Group spokesman Gary Bivings.
   Church's has 1,478 outlets in 34 states and several foreign
countries, a company spokeswoman said. Popeyes has 705 stores in 36
states and Canada.
   The merger of the two cahains probably would not radically change
the the national fried chicken business, Doyle said.
   ``Big is not necessarily better,'' Doyle said. ``I don't think it
would make much of an impact on the Kentucky Fried Chicken chain. I
think Kentucky Fried Chicken is much stronger than the Church's and
Popeyes chains.''
   Copeland's Flynn said hisd company would keep the restaurants'
menus separate with the possibility of adding some new products at
Church's.
   ``We intend to maintain two systems, and Church's would remain a
San Antonio-based company,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
