<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1943EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Oil     10-25 0895</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Oil,0922</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Profits Up At Mobil, Texaco, Chevron, Phillips; Down At Shell,
Amerada</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Jere in graf 18 is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Four of the nation's oil companies reported huge gains in their
third-quarter profits Tuesday as hefty demand in refining and
marketing segments offset declining crude oil prices.
   Mobil Corp. and Chevron Corp. each reported double-digit gains,
while profits at Texaco Inc. and Phillips Petroleum Co. more than
doubled in the latest period.
   Meanwhile, Shell Oil Co., Sun Co. and Amerada Hess Corp. each
reported sharp declines in their net earnings due partly to
declining crude oil prices.
   The larger oil companies said earnings were both hurt and helped
by falling crude prices. Lower costs for the raw product contributed
to higher profit margins in refining and marketing operations but
eroded gains in exploration and production.
   Mobil Chairman Allen E. Murray said his company's refining and
marketing segments turned in strong performances thanks to improved
margins stemming from tight refinery capacity and product
inventories.
   In addition, strong consumer demand boosted sales of gasoline and
lubricants. Mobil's chemical unit also reported a record quarter,
Murray said.
   However, those improvements were partially offset by a 26 percent
drop in crude prices and higher exploration costs, which lowered the
companies' profits from exploration and production.
   Analysts attribute most of this year's drop in crude prices to
the excess supply of oil on world markets arising from the failure
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to restrain its
production.
   For the latest quarter, New York-based Mobil had an after-tax
profit of $557 million, or $1.36 a share, up 69 percent from $330
million, or 80 cents a share, in the year-ago period. Revenue
totaled $13.12 billion, down a fraction from $13.14 billion in the
year-ago period.
   For the first nine months, profits at the nation's second-largest
oil company rose 86 percent to $1.62 billion, or $3.95 a share,
compared with $874 million, or $2.13 a share, in the same period
last year. Revenue totaled $40.99 billion, up 10 percent from $37.12
billion in the year-earlier period.
   Texaco, the nation's third-largest oil company based in White
Plains, N.Y., reported a 121 percent rise in its third-quarter
profits, to $239 million, or 98 cents a share, from $108 million, or
44 cents a share, in the 1987 quarter. Sales totaled $8.69 billion,
down 3 percent from $8.96 billion last year.
   For the first nine months, Texaco's profits jumped 183 percent to
$1.01 billion, or $4.14 a share, compared with $355 million, or
$1.46 a share, for the same period in 1987. Revenue totaled $26.8
billion, up 3 percent from $26 billion in the 1987 period.
   Texaco Chairman James W. Kinnear said the company is beginning to
see benefits from its recent restructuring.
   San Francisco-based Chevron, the fourth-largest U.S. oil concern,
said its profits rose 41 percent to $420 million, or $1.23 a share,
in the third quarter, compared with $297 million, or 87 cents a
share, in the 1987 period. Chevron's revenue, meanwhile, dropped 6.4
percent in the latest quarter to $7.2 billion, from $7.7 billion
last year.
   For the year, Chevron's earnings jumped 57 percent to $1.6
billion, or $4.66 a share, from $1.01 billion, or $2.97 a share. Its
revenue rose to $22 billion, up 1.3 percent from $21.7 billion.
   Phillips, based in Bartlesville, Okla., reported the strongest
quarterly profit gains _ nearly sixfold _ to $215 million, or 89
cents a share, from $31 million, or 11 cents a share. The company's
sales totaled $2.85 billion, up a fraction from $2.80 billion.
   Since January, Phillips' net surged to $515 million, or $2.17 a
share, from $2 million in the comparable 1987 period. It had revenue
of $8.5 billion, up 7.6 percent from $7.9 billion.
   Phillips' spokesman Jere Smith said a major streamlining, which
included the layoff of more than 1,500 workers, contributed to the
latest figures.
   Meanwhile, Shell, the sixth-largest U.S. oil company, said
sagging crude prices pulled its quarterly earnings down 16.2
percent. The company's net was $352 million on revenue of $5.4
billion, compared with $420 million in the 1987 quarter on sales of
$5.6 billion. The company does not report per-share figures.
   But for the first nine months, Houston-based Shell's net improved
134 percent to $1.9 billion, on revenue of $15.9 billion, compared
with a profit in the same period last year of $795 million, on
revenue of $15.3 billion.
   Lower crude prices also contributed to a 47 percent drop in Sun's
latest earnings, which declined 47 percent to $72 million, or 67 a
share, from $137 million, or $1.27 a share. Its revenue totaled
$2.46 billion, down 2.3 percent from $2.52 billion.
   Sun, headquartered in Radnor, Pa., reported a $69 million loss
for the first nine months, on revenue of $7.3 billion, compared with
a profit of $265 million in 1987, or $2.44 a share, on revenue of
$7.2 billion.
   New York-based Amerada Hess reported a 59 percent decline in its
quarterly net to $15.8 million, or 20 cents a share, from $38.6
million, or 45 cents a share. The company's revenue fell 17.5
percent to $925 million from $1.1 billion.
   In the first nine months, Amerada reported an 81 percent decline
in earnings to $57 million, or 71 cents a share, on revenue of $3.1
billion, from $309 million, or $3.66 a share, on revenue of $3.5
billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
