<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1841EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Delchamps-A&P     10-25 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delchamps-A&P,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delchamps Rejects A&P Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delchamps Inc. said Tuesday its board had
rejected a $224 million merger proposal from The Great Atlantic &
Pacific Tea Co. Inc., saying the offer was inadequate and that
combining the supermarket companies may raise antitrust questions.
   Delchamps spokesman Joel Swanson said the supermarket company's
nine-member board met Monday night and rejected the merger proposal
of $32 a share for Delchamps' 7 million shares, saying it was not in
the best interests of its shareholders.
   In over-the-counter trading, Delchamps fell $1.50 a share to
$23.75.
   A&P spokesman Michael Rourke of Montvale, N.J., was not
immediately available for comment Tuesday on the rejection.
   Delchamps attorney James H. McDonald Jr. said the board's
decision was based on a number of factors, including Delchamps
recent store expansion efforts and other programs which will enhance
the value of the company.
   He said the board's decision was also based upon the advice of
counsel that significant antitrust issues exist with respect to the
A&P merger proposal and the opinion of its financial advisor,
Goldman, Sachs & Co., that the $32 per share proposal is inadequate.
Both companies operate grocery stores.
   A&P began trying to buy Delchamps two years ago.
   A&P's chairman and chief executive, James Wood, had said in his
Oct. 20 letter proposing the merger that if the Delchamps board
rejected his final offer, A&P would have no alternative than to
withdraw its $32 a share merger proposal and its $30 per share
tender offer, valued at $210 million.
   A.F. Delchamps Jr., chairman of the Delchamps board and
president, stated, ``We would hope that Mr. Wood can be taken at his
word, since we agree with him that the dissension brought on by this
takeover fight is not in the best interest of our company or our
shareholders. We wish no ill will to Mr. Wood and A&P and look
forward to competing in the retail marketplace with A&P.''
   Delchamps has a federal court suit pending against A&P on the
antitrust allegations. A&P filed a countersuit.
   The board also reiterated its stand that the long-term best
interests of Delchamps stockholders would be better served by the
company remaining independent and pursuing its business plan than
merging.
   The board further noted that it had received significant
sentiment expressing support for the board's decision to remain
independent and not accept the A&P offer.
   A&P, based in Montvale, N.J., is 52 percent owned by the
Tengelmann Group of West Germany. A&P had sales of $9.6 billion in
1987 from its 1,170 stores in this country and Canada.
   Delchamps had sales of about $700 million last year and has 103
stores in Alabama, Mississippi, Florida and Louisiana, and six
liquor stores.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
