<DOCNO> AP881025-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 1952EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Polaroid     10-25 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Polaroid,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polaroid Reports $50.4 Million Loss For Third Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. on Tuesday posted a $50.4
million loss for its third quarter, due to costs of a corporate
restructuring and expenses of thwarting a hostile takeover bid.
   Polaroid said the after-tax loss came on sales of $436.3 million,
compared with a profit of $24.4 million, or 39 cents a share, on
sales of $425.9 million in the same period of 1987.
   Polaroid said the loss includes a $97 million charge to cover
costs associated with the restructuring, which included elimination
of 1,300 workers under a voluntary severance plan, planned global
distribution of 35mm color film and a $300 million employee stock
ownership plan.
   Polaroid, which faces a hostile buyout bid from Disney
family-owned Shamrock Holdings Inc. of Burbank, Calif., also
attributed the decline for the quarter ending Oct. 2 to start-up
costs for its new Impulse camera line.
   Polaroid spokesman Sam Yanes said the company spent more than $5
million on legal fees in the Shamrock battle and the bulk of the
losses were due to the severance payments.
   ``Our third quarter net results reflect a variety of temporary
factors that we expect to be behind us after the fourth quarter,''
Polaroid President I. MacAllister Booth said in a statement.
   But the company also said it expects to charge another $50
million in the fourth quarter to cover remaining costs of the
restructuring, announced in July.
   For the first nine months of the year, Polaroid reported a net
loss of $15.1 million on sales of $1.33 billion, compared with
earnings of $76.3 million, or $1.23 a share, on sales of $1.25
billion in the year-earlier period.
   Booth predicted total savings from the restructuring of more than
$100 million next year. He also said strong introductory sales of
Impulse in Europe boosted international sales by 11 percent.
   ``The underlying soundness of our business, together with the
progress we have been making in implementing our comprehensive
strategic plan, give us confidence in our ability to dramatically
improve the company's profitability in 1989,'' he said.
   Shamrock last month made a hostile $42-a-share offer after
Polaroid rebuffed two unsolicited bids. The two companies are
battling in a Delaware court over the legality of the 10 million
share employee stock plan, which Shamrock claims was enacted to
block a takeover.
   Two Polaroid officials took the stand in the trial in Delaware
Chancery Court on Tuesday before Vice Chancellor Carolyn Berger
delayed further hearings until Nov. 3.
   Polaroid stock closed at $37.50, down 50 cents in consolidated
New York Stock Exchange trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
