<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Kroger     10-25 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Kroger,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts 24 Percent Earnings Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kroger Co. said Tuesday that its
third-quarter earnings climbed 24.1 percent as sales rose 8.4
percent overall and results from its supermarkets in virtually every
major market were ahead of last year.
   The results were released as the nation's largest supermarket
operator was undertaking a $4.6 billion restructuring to fight off
takeover bids.
   The company said earnings rose to $56.2 million, or 65 cents a
share, in the third quarter from $45.3 million, or 54 cents a share,
a year earlier.
   Third-quarter sales increased to $5.58 billion from $5.15 billion
in 1987.
   Kroger management said the sales increase was in line with
projections the company made as part of its corporate restructuring
plan. The plan involves dividend payoffs to shareholders, sale of
some company assets including stores, and the previously-disclosed
dismissal of 300 headquarters employees.
   ``Sales vitality will be a critical measure of the company's
ability to generate sufficient cash to meet its debt obligations
after Kroger's special restructuring dividend is distributed, as
anticipated, to shareholders Friday,'' the company said in a
statement.
   For the year to date, Kroger's earnings increased 13 percent to
$153.5 million, or $1.81 per share, from $135.9 million, or $1.62
per share, before the effect of a change in accounting for income
taxes, the company said.
   Counting the change, the company's earnings fell 22.9 percent to
$153.5 million from $199.2 million a year earlier.
   Nine-month sales totaled $14.4 billion, an increase of 8.7
percent from $13.3 billion last year.
   Kroger's restructuring plan, which the company's board of
directors approved on Sept. 23, calls for payment to shareholders of
a special cash dividend of $40 per share, plus a debenture with an
estimated trading value of $8. Kroger management says the plan will
allow shareholders to retain their interests in what will be a
smaller, but still independent company.
</TEXT>
