<HEAD>Salomon's Profit More Than Doubles in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salomon Inc. reported Tuesday that its profit
more than doubled in the third quarter from a year earlier, boosted
partly by strong results from its oil operations.
   The financial services and commodity trading company said its net
income in the three months ended Sept. 30 jumped to $65 million, or
37 cents a share, from $27 million, or 18 cents a share, a year
earlier.
   The increased profit occurred despite a 17.3 percent decline in
third-quarter revenue to $1.29 billion from $1.56 billion.
   The company's Salomon Brothers financial subsidiary earned $86
million before taxes in the quarter, up from $49 million a year
earlier.
   Salomon said its Phibro Energy unit had pretax earnings of $45
million, triple the year before. It attributed the growth to strong
profits from oil refining and trading, high demand for gasoline, and
savings resulting from the second-quarter acquisition of a refinery
in Texas City, Texas.
   Other commodity trading operations incurred a combined loss of
$15 million, compared with a $5 million profit in the third quarter
of last year.
   In the first nine months of the year, Salomon's profit rose 47.2
percent _ to $318 million, or $2 a share, from $216 million, or
$1.40 a share.
   Nine-month revenue decreased to $4.33 billion from $4.67 billion.
