<1ST_LINE>u f AM-DebtorNation 1stLd-Writethru f0278 10-25 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Debtor Nation, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0278,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Disputes Depth of U.S. International Debt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs The study... to CORRECT figure to minus $263
billion sted million. Picks up 6th graf, In 1988...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's international debt is far
smaller than the government's figures indicate, according to a new
study whose authors say misleading figures have led to exaggerated
fears of economic decline.
   The United States, said by the Commerce Department to have become
a net debtor nation in 1985, actually remained in the black until
last year, according to the study by the Rand Corp.
   ``The big point about this is...that the public debate has been
misinformed and ill-served by frequent reiteration of flawed
numbers,'' Charles Wolf Jr., director of Rand's international
economic policy research, said Tuesday.
   The figure in question, called the U.S. international investment
position, is a cumulative total of all American spending and
investment overseas compared to foreign spending and investment in
this country.
   The study by the government-funded think tank indicates that in
1985, when Commerce Department figures showed the United States was
a net debtor to the tune of $112 billion, the country actually was a
$178 billion net creditor. In 1986, when the government figure was a
minus $263 billion, the Rand recalculation had the country a
creditor nation by $50 billion.
   In 1988, government figures indicated the country was $368
billion in debt. Rand researchers haven't calculated their version
of the 1988 number, but know it would be negative, Wolf said.
   The Rand study, conducted under Wolf's direction by University of
Michigan graduate student Sarah A. Hooker, adjusts the government's
measures in several ways:
   _It converts ``direct investment,'' the department's measure of
private holdings of foreign capital, including real estate, to
current dollar value. Because much American investment overseas was
made years ago, when the dollar was worth less than today, this
increases the vaue of Americans' foreign holdings relative to
foreigners' more recent investments in this country.
   _It boosts the value of U.S. gold reserves, another component of
the Commerce Department figure, by using a market price of $380 per
ounce rather than the department's ``official'' price of $42.22 an
ounce.
   _On the negative side, the researchers cut the value of loans
owed to U.S. banks by developing nations. Based on the theory that
many of these shaky loans will never be repaid, the study fixed
their value at what they would bring on the secondary market, where
banks trade debts of various kinds.
   These adjustments reflect previously voiced criticism of the
Commerce Department figures. But the researchers believe they are
the first to actually recalculate the department numbers based on
the criticism, Wolf said.
   Even after the changes, the numbers show a steady slide in the
U.S. position. That isn't necessarily bad, Wolf said, to the extent
that it represents foreigners' confidence in the United States
economy as a safe, stable haven for their money.
   ``The point is, you don't contribute to what we like to think of
as an informed and educated debate by using figures that are $300
million off the mark,'' Wolf said. ``...There's a perception problem
in how you view the situation: Is it grave, or serious, or just a
matter of concern. ...I think it's a matter of concern.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881025-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 2119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Earns-Media 1stLd-Writethru f0277 10-25 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Media, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0277,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cap Cities-ABC Profit Up 63 Percent in Quarter, Washington Post
Profit Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 new grafs, to UPDATE with Washington Post Co.
earnings, edit to conform. Picks up 4th graf, Capital Cities-ABC
said... ADDS 3 grafs with Washington Post details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capital Cities-ABC Inc. reported Tuesday it had a
63 percent jump in its third-quarter income, while the Washington
Post Co. reported its profit was down by 39.6 percent from a
year-earlier period when it had large one-time gains.
   Capital Cities-ABC, which owns the ABC television network and
other broadcast and print properties, said it earned $62.6 million,
or $3.55 a share, during the quarter ended Sept. 30. That was up
from $38.4 million, or $2.23 a share, in the same period of 1987.
   The company reported revenue of nearly $1.01 billion, up from
$946.21 billion in the third quarter a year earlier.
   Washington Post Co. reported from Washington that it had a profit
of $38.1 million, or $2.96 per share, in the three months ended
Sept. 30, compared with $63.1 million, or $4.77 per share, in the
year-earlier period. Sales rose to $329.4 million from $312.9
million in third-quarter 1987.
   Capital Cities-ABC said its broadcasting operations had a 24
percent rise in income, while income from its publishing operations
was flat.
   For the first nine months of the year, Capital Cities-ABC said it
earned $246.9 million, or $14.43 a share, up from $162.1 million, or
$9.56 a share, in the same period of 1987.
   The company reported nine-month revenue of $3.46 billion, up from
$3.03 billion a year earlier.
   Capital-Cities-ABC also owns six radio networks, eight television
stations and 21 radio stations. It provides programming for cable
television, and its publishing businesses includes daily and weekly
newspapers, specialty and business periodicals and books.
   The third quarter 1987 profit for Washington Post Co. included
one-time after-tax gains of $30.2 million, or $2.35 per share, from
the sales of certain cellular telephone and SportsChannel cable
television interests.
   Newspaper division revenue increased 8 percent in the third
quarter over the comparable period last year, according to the
company report. Post-Newsweek television stations' revenue was up 5
percent in the third quarter, and cable division revenue increased
17 percent.
   For the nine months, the company had a profit of $232.2 million,
or $18.04 per share, compared with $122.3 million, or $9.51 per
share, in the same period of 1987. Revenue during the nine months
rose to $996.8 million from $950.4 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
