<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 2219EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-ClaridgeSale     10-25 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Claridge Sale,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Del Webb and Golden Nugget Terminate Claridge Hotel Sale Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Del Webb Corp. and The Golden Nugget Inc. said
Tuesday they had mutually terminated their Oct. 2 preliminary
agreement under which Golden Nugget was to acquire the Claridge
Hotel-Casino in Atlantic City, N.J. for $110 million.
   In a news release, Del Webb said various difficulties had made it
impossible to proceed with a definitive agreement.
   A primary difficulty was a determination that certain operational
changes requested by Golden Nugget from the New Jersey Casino
Control Commission could not be granted under applicable law, Del
Webb stated. The company did not elaborate.
   Del Webb, which has a 10 percent interest in the Claridge, has
the management contract for the facility.
   The company and Atlantic City Boardwalk Associates have been
seeking a possible buyer since May for the 501-room Claridge. Hotel
president Roger Wagner had indicated that more than 170 potential
purchasers contacted Del Webb's investment banker, Oppenheimer &
Co., about the Claridge.
   Del Webb suffered a $96.6 million net loss in 1987, with the
Claridge responsible for 78.8 percent of the loss.
   Philip J. Dion, chairman and chief executive officer of Webb,
said the company had presented to the NJCCC a restructuring proposal
for the Claridge which substantially reduced the facility's debt and
would allow it to operate on a solid financial basis.
   The proposal, which is awaiting commission approval, was
developed by Del Webb prior to the Oct. 2 announcement of the
preliminary agreement with The Golden Nugget, the company said.
   Del Webb has been selling off assets in its leisure group, which
includes other casino and recreational properties. Late in
September, Golden Nugget Chairman Steve Wynn closed a deal to
purchase the Nevada Club casino in Laughlin, Nev., from Del Webb for
$40 million.
   Wynn left the Atlantic City casino industry in 1987 when he sold
the Golden Nugget hotel-casino in the resort town to Bally
Manufacturing Corp. for $440 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
