<FILEID>AP-NR-10-25-88 2313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SchererFight     10-25 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Scherer Fight,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winner Of Disputed Proxy Election Seated On Scherer Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The formal seating Tuesday of Theodore Souris,
winner of a disputed proxy election to the R.P. Scherer Corp. board
of directors, ended a successful battle by dissidents aiming to
force the sale of the pharmaceutical supply company.
   Souris was seated during the final session of Scherer's annual
shareholders meeting, the company said in a statement.
   Results of the proxy election he won Aug. 17 were accepted after
the Delaware Court of Chancery ruled Oct. 5 against challenges filed
by the corporation and the board candidate he defeated, the
statement said.
   The dissident group was led by Karla Scherer Fink and John
Scherer, children of the company's founder. Ms. Fink also is the
estranged wife of Peter Fink, the company's president and chief
executive, who opposes a sale of Scherer.
   John Scherer won uncontested re-election to the board, as did
Peter Fink.
   Souris's seating Tuesday marked the first time the board was at
full strength since Aug. 17, when he and New York investment banker
Frederick Frank won the seats held by incumbent directors Peter Dow
and Richard Manoogian, the statement said.
   Scherer stock closed Tuesday at $32.12{ a share, down 25 cents
from Monday's close in national over-the-counter trading.
   R.P. Scherer manufactures gelatin capsules for the pharmaceutical
and nutritional industries. It employs about 2,800 people at 22
facilties in 13 countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
